WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.760
[Amit Varma]: On June 5, 1989, a bunch of tanks in single file rolled down Chang'an Avenue, with Tiananmen

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:15.080
[Amit Varma]: Square behind them. The previous day, protests at Tiananmen Square had been crushed by the

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:20.200
[Amit Varma]: Chinese government, with hundreds if not thousands of people killed. Just one day later, the

00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:25.040
[Amit Varma]: streets were empty, except for these massive tanks rolling past. And then, suddenly, a

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.560
[Amit Varma]: man dressed in a white shirt and black trousers, holding what appeared to be shopping bags,

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:33.800
[Amit Varma]: walked over in front of the first of those tanks, and just stood there as it advanced

00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:39.200
[Amit Varma]: towards him. It stopped just in time. A few seconds passed. Two other tanks stopped behind

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:43.720
[Amit Varma]: the first tank. A fourth one approached from behind. Then that first tank started and swerved

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:48.080
[Amit Varma]: away from the man and tried to go past him. He ran into its path and stood there. The

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:52.240
[Amit Varma]: tank swerved again, the man swerved again. This went on for a bit till the tank just

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:56.840
[Amit Varma]: stopped. The man was three feet away from it at most. It's an iconic photograph, and

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:01.240
[Amit Varma]: there's also an iconic video of it. But we don't know who the man was. And we don't know

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:07.840
[Amit Varma]: what happened to him. 53 years before this, on June 13, 1936, a group of workers gathered

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:12.080
[Amit Varma]: at a shipyard in Hamburg. There was a moment when they all raised their hand in the Nazi

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:17.640
[Amit Varma]: salute, except one man. In another iconic photograph, you see this man in the crowd,

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:23.520
[Amit Varma]: the only man not saluting, as alone as the man 53 years later who we now call Tank Man.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And as I think of these men, a part of me wonders why they did what they did. What is

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:33.040
[Amit Varma]: the point? You can't win. The tank is always stronger than you. The mob is always stronger

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:37.760
[Amit Varma]: than you. The instinct for self-preservation dictates that you keep quiet. It dictates

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.800
[Amit Varma]: that the unknown man in China goes home with his shopping bags and empties them on the

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:46.560
[Amit Varma]: kitchen platform and maybe makes himself a cup of tea. The man in the shipyard, he can

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:51.000
[Amit Varma]: raise his arm, he can go with the mob so that he's not the odd one out. But these two people

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.400
[Amit Varma]: didn't do that. And we have to ask, what is it that made those men do what they did? And

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:01.880
[Amit Varma]: why do we feel inspired when we look at those photographs? Maybe those men were foolish,

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:07.120
[Amit Varma]: but we think of them today as heroes. Why do we feel that way? Would you have walked

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:12.320
[Amit Varma]: in front of that tank?

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:17.520
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:24.280
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:27.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. My guest today is Aakar Patel, someone I've known

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:33.880
[Amit Varma]: off for many years as an enterprising reporter, an excellent editor, a provocative columnist.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:38.320
[Amit Varma]: In recent years, though, in addition to all of these, I think of Aakar as a principled

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:43.600
[Amit Varma]: dissenter. Aakar was a journalist through the 90s and aughties, took a break in 2010,

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.760
[Amit Varma]: decided at one point to become head of amnesty in India, and after our government clamped

00:02:47.760 --> 00:02:54.720
[Amit Varma]: down on amnesty, has been an outspoken dissenter. To me, dissent is the highest form of patriotism.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:59.760
[Amit Varma]: And Aakar has gone all in. Over the last couple of years, he's written two superb books,

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:04.720
[Amit Varma]: Our Hindu Rashtra, What It Is, How We Got Here, and Price of the Modi Years. He also

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:09.280
[Amit Varma]: has one of my favourite Twitter accounts of all time, where he's mastered a unique form

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:15.000
[Amit Varma]: of satire in a unique voice that is unlike anything else in that space. On some days,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.200
[Amit Varma]: I feel grateful that Narendra Modi exists, because if he didn't, Aakar Patel may not

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:24.160
[Amit Varma]: have been Aakar Patel. Now, Aakar has been on the show before, in 2019, when we discussed

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.680
[Amit Varma]: the intellectual foundations of Hindutva, as that episode title was, I'll link it from

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:33.440
[Amit Varma]: the show notes. I visited Bangalore recently to record a bunch of episodes, and given how

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:38.320
[Amit Varma]: prolific Aakar has been, it made sense to catch up with him. We spoke about politics,

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.860
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about the media, and we spoke about Aakar's passport, which at that point had

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:47.160
[Amit Varma]: been impounded by the government and had been with them for a long time. Well, guess what?

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Soon after we had our conversation, Aakar's passport was returned to him. I'm like, wow,

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:55.720
[Amit Varma]: you would have thought someone was listening in. Be that as it may, check out this quick

00:03:55.720 --> 00:04:00.080
[Amit Varma]: commercial break, which is a commercial for me only, what else is there? And then check

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:03.240
[Amit Varma]: out our conversation.

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.880
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:12.720
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've enjoyed teaching 21 cohorts of my online course, The

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Art of Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:21.600
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.000
[Amit Varma]: interaction. In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.080
[Amit Varma]: share all I know about the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises,

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:36.240
[Amit Varma]: much interaction, a lovely and lively community at the end of it. The course costs Rs. 10,000

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:43.680
[Amit Varma]: GST, or about $150. And registration is now open for my April 2022 cohort. The first webinar

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:49.440
[Amit Varma]: is on Saturday, April 9. So if you're interested, head on over to register at IndiaUncut.com

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:54.640
[Amit Varma]: slash clear writing. That's IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing. Being a good writer doesn't

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:59.520
[Amit Varma]: require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear idea of what you

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:04.240
[Amit Varma]: need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.920
[Amit Varma]: Aakar, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you for having me.

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:13.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, I recorded a long episode with Abhinandan Sekri in November. And before we started,

00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:18.520
[Amit Varma]: we were kind of talking about you, admiringly. And my feeling was that Aakar has reached

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:23.280
[Amit Varma]: that stage of a person who has no more fucks to give. So you just write anything into it.

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:28.040
[Amit Varma]: And you're just, you're just kind of out there. And is that a characterization you'd kind

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:31.720
[Guest]: of agree with? And if so, how did you get here?

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:37.640
[Guest]: I don't know if that's true. And if it's true, I should be really worried. I do give a lot

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:39.760
[Amit Varma]: of fucks. I think no more fucks to give in a sense

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:48.720
[Guest]: of fear. No more fear. So I'm not really sure about how I got here. But certainly, it is

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:54.840
[Guest]: a fact that once you've faced what the state can do to you as an individual, and you've

00:05:54.840 --> 00:06:02.720
[Guest]: gone through it once, the fear of that diminishes in some sense, because you know exactly what

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:09.640
[Guest]: it is comprised of, that they can do this to you. And I have gone through that quite

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:17.240
[Guest]: a bit in the last four or five years. So that's now fine. That is sort of acceptable.

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:23.560
[Guest]: The other thing is that I run off at the mouth. So I think that because I find using Twitter

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:29.360
[Guest]: so entertaining for myself, I tend to do it a lot more than I should be doing. And because

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:33.720
[Guest]: purely in terms of volume, there is so much material, a lot of it might be seen as flying

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:39.840
[Amit Varma]: off the handle, which it probably is. I'm struck with a phrase you said that after

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:44.640
[Amit Varma]: having been through all of this, that's now fine. You know, so is that something you're

00:06:44.640 --> 00:06:47.200
[Amit Varma]: comfortable talking about? Because of course, you were harassed when you were in charge

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:51.360
[Amit Varma]: of amnesty and all those cases happened and all that. And even now, you are constantly

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:55.400
[Amit Varma]: being harassed. I believe your passport was impounded and all of that. Like, you know,

00:06:55.400 --> 00:06:59.400
[Amit Varma]: it just sounds like so incredibly, incredibly traumatic for me. Is that something you're

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.480
[Amit Varma]: comfortable talking about what that what happened, what that process was like?

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:11.680
[Guest]: Two separate things with amnesty, what happened was a series of raids, and the accounts were

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:17.480
[Guest]: frozen the following morning, we had people in the office, we were not allowed to move

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:22.960
[Guest]: for many hours till about 11 o'clock in the night. The worry always was how do we keep

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:28.560
[Guest]: the operation going, because this sort of action had been taken against other entities,

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:34.360
[Guest]: including Greenpeace. So, we knew what it was to anticipate. When it finally happened,

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:38.760
[Guest]: the lack of competence from the state showed and so we were able to get relief from the

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:43.440
[Guest]: courts fairly quickly the first time. The second time it happened on the same set of

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:49.480
[Guest]: transactions, this was the CBI coming in, we had raids by the MHA, the CBI, the Enforcement

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:55.400
[Guest]: Directorate. The second time also, there was a lack of competence, this time the ET charged

00:07:55.400 --> 00:08:02.240
[Guest]: us with money laundering. But the relief from the courts was only partial. So, at that my

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:08.520
[Guest]: my term had ended in November. The people who came after me felt that it was too difficult

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:16.640
[Guest]: to be able to carry on with that. So, they felt it was better to suspend operations.

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:27.920
[Guest]: Facing the state, I think, is slightly different for those who face the upper echelons of the

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:33.640
[Guest]: bureaucracy. So, when the CBI comes to you, it's not like inspector type person, it's

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:40.360
[Guest]: somebody fairly higher up. And they tend to talk to you in the way that people of that

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:47.520
[Guest]: level of education and that level of exposure will. The ED was much rougher, with me at

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:55.000
[Guest]: least. They were fairly accusatory in terms of why are you doing this kind of work. And

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:00.240
[Guest]: it occurred to me that the language that they used was pretty much the same as somebody

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:06.360
[Guest]: who would not be acquainted with the wider world would actually use. So, yeah. In terms

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:10.520
[Guest]: of purely harassment, there wasn't that much. I mean, there's continual summons. So, then

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:15.560
[Guest]: you go. Once you figure out that that's the way it works, when they call you, you go.

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:21.440
[Guest]: But with no resources, that becomes slightly more difficult. So, these days, not having

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:28.240
[Guest]: made too much money over the last several years, it's not that easy. Having your passport

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:33.440
[Guest]: impounded is, I mean, but it's the two years of COVID. So, I mean, where the heck would

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:40.240
[Guest]: you go in any case? So, it's fine for them to keep it. On the personal side, it was,

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:45.460
[Guest]: there was the possibility of jail till I got bail. So, I didn't have to go there. It might

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:50.240
[Guest]: still happen. I don't know. Because there is always the fear that somebody else files

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:55.760
[Guest]: a case for something you said or something you are accused of having said. That's the

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:59.680
[Guest]: nature of living in this country at this point in time. I think that you either put your

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:06.920
[Guest]: head down and say, fine, I'm not going to engage with this. But many people can't do

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:13.600
[Guest]: that. They have to engage with what they see around them. I can't look away from what it

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:22.480
[Guest]: is. And that means that necessarily you get into trouble sometimes. But that's the price

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:27.520
[Guest]: of being in this country at this point in time, which many people are paying a much

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:36.160
[Guest]: higher price than before. I'm one of the fortunate ones. I'm not inside. I can still write. Publisher's

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:45.480
[Guest]: dead though. Books will no longer be printed. But I suppose it's the same experience writers

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:53.920
[Guest]: would have in any part of the world with an authoritarian leader who doesn't like dissent

00:10:53.920 --> 00:11:04.960
[Guest]: and whose supporters see dissent, any kind of it, as a direct insult to his greatness,

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:10.520
[Guest]: which is why they act. And that is the reality of India post-2014.

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:15.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, your publisher is dead, but we all hope that they come back to life in

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:20.560
[Amit Varma]: some way or the other. So let's see how that goes. So I'm reminded of this book I read

00:11:20.560 --> 00:11:26.480
[Amit Varma]: called Exit Voice Loyalty by Albert Hirschman, where he says that when you are in an unpleasant

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:30.520
[Amit Varma]: situation, whether it is within an organization or within a country or whatever, you have

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:36.000
[Amit Varma]: three options, like the easiest option is just loyalty, you stay loyal. Another option

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.680
[Amit Varma]: is voice, that you voice out whatever the problem is, if you know, and how to make things

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:44.520
[Amit Varma]: better. And the third option is exit, that you just leave, right. And now within corporations

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:48.920
[Amit Varma]: and all the way markets work, exit is possible, that you don't like a job in a company, you

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:54.080
[Amit Varma]: look for another job, you know, and if you're doing something, which is kind of if the market

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:58.720
[Amit Varma]: is there for that, you kind of get out. And voice is always sort of dangerous. Now, you

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:02.000
[Amit Varma]: know, at a national level, now what happens is that many of us who may not be happy with

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:08.000
[Amit Varma]: what's going on, we've got two effective options, which is exit or voice. And this came to my

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.560
[Amit Varma]: mind, because I have been like, it's damn disturbing, Aakar, I have spoken to so many

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:17.480
[Amit Varma]: people who like me, years ago, decades ago, two decades ago, in the 90s, made a conscious

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:20.840
[Amit Varma]: choice that we will stay in India, we can go, but we will stay in India, because this

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:25.360
[Amit Varma]: is where we want to be. This is our comfort zone, it's our home, we will stay. And without

00:12:25.360 --> 00:12:29.360
[Amit Varma]: exception, they're all they've either left or they're thinking of leaving, right, which

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:32.440
[Amit Varma]: is heartbreaking, because these are not the kind of guys who would have left anyway. And

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:36.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm thinking, these are the privileged types, that they can leave, so they leave, most people

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:42.680
[Amit Varma]: can't leave. And most people can't even are afraid of the voice angle also, because for

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:47.920
[Amit Varma]: all kinds of reasons, right. And therefore, I sometimes think that there's another kind

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:52.080
[Amit Varma]: of exit that happens there, which is not an exit out of the country, but an exit into

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:56.800
[Amit Varma]: yourself, like a psychological thing where you become in denial, and you say, I don't

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:01.320
[Amit Varma]: want to, you know, almost a kind of effective loyalty, but not really. But you're just like,

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:06.480
[Amit Varma]: I'll do my own thing, you know, maybe not my circus, not my monkeys kind of thing. And

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:10.280
[Amit Varma]: I'll do my own thing and find people are being lynched, and girls aren't being allowed to

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:15.160
[Amit Varma]: enter schools, and that's somewhere else. And I'll just kind of focus on my own life.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:19.520
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, along this framework, how do you think of things like, of course, you can't

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:24.600
[Amit Varma]: exit because it took your passport. But if you were to, on the question of voice, you

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:28.160
[Amit Varma]: know, you are someone who's gone down that route that I'll, you know, I care, I'll keep

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:33.480
[Amit Varma]: saying what I have to say. And obviously, you know, many, many people like that, in

00:13:33.480 --> 00:13:39.520
[Amit Varma]: our circles, who are exactly the same, beyond the point, what happens, you know, have you

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:44.280
[Amit Varma]: seen people who have just become silent, because what's the point, nothing's going to change.

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:48.400
[Amit Varma]: And the fact is that that's rational, because nothing is going to change in a larger scheme

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:51.240
[Amit Varma]: of things, you know, some people might say, Oh, I'll play the longer game, I'll just stay

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:55.600
[Amit Varma]: at it, there needs to be someone who's speaking. So what are sort of your thoughts on this

00:13:55.600 --> 00:14:00.680
[Amit Varma]: as over the years, we've, you know, when we last spoke in our last episode was in early

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:04.720
[Amit Varma]: 2019, before the elections. And you said, Oh, there's going to be a hung parliament,

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:10.480
[Amit Varma]: I think, right. So, yeah, you said, I think there's going to be a hung parliament. No,

00:14:10.480 --> 00:14:15.440
[Amit Varma]: it's too late. It's a it's on the record. And so I think many of us had more hope than

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:19.800
[Amit Varma]: we do now many of us saw a greater point in actually speaking up than we might do now.

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:25.640
[Guest]: So you know, what are your thoughts? I think that most people don't have a voice or don't

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:31.680
[Guest]: have a sufficiently loud voice. This has changed with social media, where if you have if you

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:37.080
[Guest]: can generate content of reasonable quality, you will find a fairly large audience for

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:42.240
[Guest]: much of your content. Those of us who have a formal voice or have been given a formal

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:47.240
[Guest]: voice as you and I have, where over the years, we've been given platforms to be able to say

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:53.680
[Guest]: what it is that we want. I think that it's important for that set, especially to be able

00:14:53.680 --> 00:15:01.920
[Guest]: to use it. And I think that it is being used. What is striking about the formal media space

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:07.960
[Guest]: is that there is an informal media space, which is social media, but in the formal space,

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:17.680
[Guest]: while the industry has tilted towards Mr. Modi and towards his majoritarianism, I would

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:28.880
[Guest]: say a lot of people who could have either exited or could have turned inward and say,

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:35.840
[Guest]: you know, not my circus and not my monkeys have chosen to speak. And I don't think it's

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:44.660
[Guest]: a small number. I think the reason why the media dominance is stressed on by this government

00:15:44.660 --> 00:15:49.960
[Guest]: is that it sees, it suspects, and I think it is right, that what comes from the other

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:56.640
[Guest]: side, even though it might not be amplified too much, is powerful. And so I'm in very

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:01.960
[Guest]: good company, I think that we have a lot of people who may or may not be part of the media

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:07.800
[Guest]: system, but have a formal voice, such as people in civil society, who because of social media

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:16.920
[Guest]: have become formal spaces, where they can command authority in terms of their reach.

00:16:16.920 --> 00:16:24.240
[Guest]: I suppose it's also a question of a community. Many of us can't take the options that you

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:30.400
[Guest]: picked, two of them, because they belong to the persecuted, that for them, it's personal,

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:37.520
[Guest]: that it is even if it is not them who is being disrobed or who's being kicked out of their

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:45.480
[Guest]: prayer spaces or being told not to sell this or being beaten up for being who they are,

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:50.440
[Guest]: it is the sense of fraternity that they will feel will be very powerful. So for them, I

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:54.200
[Guest]: don't think it's possible to, I can't speak for them, but I suspect that for them it won't

00:16:54.200 --> 00:17:02.960
[Guest]: be possible to either exit or to look inward and say, I'm not going to engage with it.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:09.320
[Guest]: But for many of us, I think that we still believe, and I think we are right to believe

00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:16.760
[Guest]: that that space is actually available, that India is not a competently run authoritarian

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:23.760
[Guest]: state. It's not like China, where you will not come out of jail till you're on your knees

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:28.480
[Guest]: and you say you're not going to do it again, and maybe not even after that. We have a little

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:36.320
[Guest]: bit of space available, despite a fairly pliant judiciary, despite a fairly empowered mob,

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:43.960
[Guest]: to be able to say some things and to be able to get resonance and response for that. So

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:51.440
[Guest]: I think that that quality of our country where there is so much chaos that even tyranny does

00:17:51.440 --> 00:18:01.440
[Guest]: not operate in lockstep fashion and the mob really is not able to efficiently control

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:07.560
[Guest]: our voices, that space is there. Many of us sense it. Some of us get into trouble at some

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:15.360
[Guest]: points because of it, but it is there. I think that those who choose to engage with the polity

00:18:15.360 --> 00:18:20.680
[Guest]: and of course, engagement should always be from the positive sense, that people say what

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:30.320
[Guest]: they do for the most part because they want things to be better. It is the case that we

00:18:30.320 --> 00:18:39.240
[Guest]: have in India today in 2022, enough freedom to be able to, just enough freedom to be able

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:47.520
[Guest]: to say some things. And I think that those who choose either to exit, whether physically

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:55.560
[Guest]: or intellectually and morally, are missing out on that because certainly they are doing

00:18:55.560 --> 00:19:00.680
[Guest]: so not because they like what they are seeing around them, but they believe it's safer for

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:05.760
[Guest]: them or they believe it's more comfortable for them to be able to disengage. I think

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:14.640
[Guest]: that they are missing out on something very valuable. I found that engaging with my fellow

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:25.360
[Guest]: country women and men on these substantial issues in these times is the most rewarding

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:32.080
[Guest]: thing I have done in my life, though I'm not making any money out of it. And it's rewarding

00:19:32.080 --> 00:19:39.240
[Guest]: in ways that few things ever can be. I think that the sense of solidarity, the sense of

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:52.400
[Guest]: meaning that you have when you speak for things that are so meaningful to so many people,

00:19:52.400 --> 00:20:01.720
[Guest]: so real, is very different, I think, and very new to me at least. I'm quite pleased that

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:07.600
[Guest]: though we've had very difficult times in the last two and a half years, these have also

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:13.760
[Guest]: been times that have given the opportunity for this maybe not insignificant number of

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:20.280
[Guest]: people to gather around values, as I think has not been the case for a very long time

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:25.560
[Amit Varma]: in this country. I think what I've also seen, and I think it's an observation I'd make about

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:29.040
[Amit Varma]: â€“ it's an observation I'd make a little more hesitatingly about the country as a whole,

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:32.320
[Amit Varma]: but it's certainly true of social media, is that what you see on social media are these

00:20:32.320 --> 00:20:38.200
[Amit Varma]: shrill, vocal minorities, but the vast silent majorities are not quite like that. And there

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:43.040
[Amit Varma]: are ways to sort of reach out and connect. And I wonder if at the level of a country,

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:47.120
[Amit Varma]: it might just be possible that there are many more people with us than we think, and those

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:53.280
[Amit Varma]: connections and become sort of valuable. And, but, you know, I understand what you're saying

00:20:53.280 --> 00:21:00.040
[Amit Varma]: that there is a space, and that space for dissent might be there because of inertia,

00:21:00.040 --> 00:21:03.960
[Amit Varma]: dissent might be there because those in power feel English speaking elites like us are not

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:08.680
[Amit Varma]: important enough. And that space can shrink very fast. Like, you know, if the emergency

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:13.360
[Amit Varma]: was on, for example, if this was 1976, I'm sure both of us would be in jail, right? That

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:19.720
[Amit Varma]: space can shrink very fast. And other spaces have shrunk very fast, right? Especially as

00:21:19.720 --> 00:21:24.680
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out for Muslims, which is, you know, which has been their locus so far. But,

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:28.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, if they also decide at some point that, okay, let's get down to it and teach

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:33.320
[Amit Varma]: these elite liberals a lesson instead of ignoring them, that it can shrink very fast. And in

00:21:33.320 --> 00:21:37.360
[Amit Varma]: many ways, I think about sort of the process being the punishment, that it is not necessary

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:42.040
[Amit Varma]: that an Amit Shah sends a powerful state after you. It is, you know, some random guy somewhere

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:45.880
[Amit Varma]: can go to a police station. I mean, you've pointed out how you had some Suomoto case

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:50.760
[Amit Varma]: filed against you by your local police station, and then that process becomes a punishment.

00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, no matter how skilled you are at avoiding Twitter notifications and all

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:58.560
[Amit Varma]: that, there was a time where people were claiming you were a Muslim as if that is a bad thing

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:04.000
[Amit Varma]: to be and calling you Akar Amit Patel and all of that. And that's also got to be disturbing

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:10.280
[Amit Varma]: at some level. So, you know, one, has this stuff affected you as it's happened in your

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:15.920
[Amit Varma]: own time? And two, if the space should suddenly constrict, at what point do you see a point

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:19.960
[Amit Varma]: where you like, do they have to kind of physically lock you up and shut you up for you to kind

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:25.720
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, stop? Or is there a point where you can think of, you can say, right, look,

00:22:25.720 --> 00:22:31.560
[Amit Varma]: okay, for my family or for whatever, and it's not practical, let's lie low for a while?

00:22:31.560 --> 00:22:37.440
[Guest]: I foresee a continuation of what we have seen in the past eight years, we are going to enter

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:44.080
[Guest]: year nine very soon, rather than a deterioration. And I think part of that is structural, that

00:22:44.080 --> 00:22:49.920
[Guest]: India engages with the world, and no country can be fully sovereign in the 21st century,

00:22:49.920 --> 00:22:54.680
[Guest]: you are dependent on country X for something, some other countries dependent on you for

00:22:54.680 --> 00:23:00.320
[Guest]: something. No country is fully sovereign, which means that you, at some point, nations

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:07.600
[Guest]: have to follow broad rules. We are sitting down on a day, just hours after this has been

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:12.880
[Guest]: violated. But that is exceptional. I think that for the most part, you have to do things

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:20.480
[Guest]: in a particular way. Broadly speaking, I think India continues to tell the world that we

00:23:20.480 --> 00:23:29.080
[Guest]: are this liberal democracy, liberal, not as defined by Twitter, but liberal as defined

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:34.360
[Guest]: by a constitution that it says that it looks at the individual not through the prism of

00:23:34.360 --> 00:23:44.560
[Guest]: faith, but through the prism of their humanity and their citizenship. Into this, the BJP

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:49.960
[Guest]: has introduced the element of faith, that using this secular carapace, this Nehruvian

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:56.040
[Guest]: carapace, which overarches the polity, they have introduced laws that go after Muslims

00:23:56.040 --> 00:24:00.920
[Guest]: specifically, whether it is on interfaith marriage, whether it is on what they eat,

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:06.080
[Guest]: or through policies like what they may wear, where they may pray, where they may not pray.

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:12.480
[Guest]: But because that carapace exists externally, it's difficult for India to be able to continue

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:21.960
[Guest]: doing what it is doing beyond a point, which is why I foresee only what is going on being

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:29.800
[Guest]: the case without any deepening of it. I could be wrong. And it's our vulnerability to the

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:38.040
[Guest]: external world with whom we have relationships, with whom we have dependencies, that ensure

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:45.240
[Guest]: that we haven't gone down a far nastier path than we have chosen to go down. That is the

00:24:45.240 --> 00:24:53.440
[Guest]: reality. And I think that that will not change. We will see what has been going on continuing.

00:24:53.440 --> 00:25:04.560
[Guest]: I don't see it deepening. And there are structural reasons why I think that this will fail, not

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:12.840
[Guest]: from the point of view of pure optimism. My sense is that we have reached the period from

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:20.080
[Guest]: where things will get better. And I don't think that that time is too far off. So while

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:26.000
[Guest]: it's entirely possible that I'm wrong, and things do get worse, and they will go after

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:32.320
[Guest]: not just Muslims, but other people and, you know, sort of brutalize them the way that

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:40.040
[Guest]: they are doing, they're doing to Muslims now. I don't foresee that happening for structural

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:48.640
[Guest]: reasons. And I foresee that things will improve on the on the rights front, in short order,

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:53.200
[Guest]: but not too much longer than five or seven years.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:56.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I've been saying for a long time that things will get worse before they get better.

00:25:56.920 --> 00:26:00.840
[Amit Varma]: But sometimes I wonder if they will kind of get better at all. You know, there is that

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:05.320
[Amit Varma]: old quote, in fact, you begin the last chapter of our Hindu Rashtra with that quote by Martin

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:11.080
[Amit Varma]: Luther King about the arc of history is long, but it bends towards justice. And, you know,

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:15.120
[Amit Varma]: and I wonder if that is naive, because we have a low sample size history isn't really

00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:18.840
[Amit Varma]: that long, how the hell do we know it bends towards justice, maybe we're just being optimistic,

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:20.280
[Amit Varma]: maybe it doesn't bend towards justice.

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:27.120
[Guest]: So if you look at the last 150 years, it's hard to think of a single battle that liberals

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:35.880
[Guest]: have lost. They've won everything from slavery, to the rights of women to vote, adult suffrage,

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:44.100
[Guest]: on torture, on colonialism, on war, like, it's very hard to think of an issue on which

00:26:44.100 --> 00:26:51.580
[Guest]: what is called the traditional right or the conservative has won big seed space continually.

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:59.040
[Guest]: But this is only visible if you if we step back and look on time as being in maybe a

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:05.800
[Guest]: century and a half rather than years. Somebody who looks at India, from the lens of 30 years

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:13.000
[Guest]: might say things have become very bad, and they have. But I think that the arc is not

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:19.400
[Guest]: something that the shift is not really possible. I think it can only move towards justice.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:28.520
[Guest]: Because humanity is good in a way that is difficult to introduce malign influence, which

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:34.600
[Guest]: remains for too long. It does come and it does stay sometimes. But it's not permanent.

00:27:34.600 --> 00:27:42.920
[Guest]: I think the permanent shift is towards goodness, more freedom, more rights, more understanding

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:49.720
[Guest]: and, yeah, so I think he got that right. If, if you look at it from the long point of view,

00:27:49.720 --> 00:27:54.280
[Guest]: and I think I see the same happening here as well, not not just in our country. But

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:58.760
[Guest]: I think across the world that the next 20 years will be very good for us that because

00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:04.640
[Guest]: we have so many things to unite us as, as a planet, the fact that we are all endangered

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:14.880
[Guest]: by one thing, the climate shift, the recognition that, you know, in most countries that war

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:19.600
[Guest]: is not the way to resolve issues, as we've seen in the last 30 years, very little violence,

00:28:19.600 --> 00:28:25.160
[Guest]: which is a state on state. The changes we are seeing in science that what what we are

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:35.960
[Guest]: bringing in in terms of from rocketry to intelligence to, to the shift that is on us on labour,

00:28:35.960 --> 00:28:42.920
[Guest]: I think that will produce very good things. The causes might be bad. I think that what

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:49.520
[Guest]: India is facing today, whether for mismanagement, or just the fact that we are a very large

00:28:49.520 --> 00:28:55.280
[Guest]: nation of very poor people at this point in history, with so many people out of work,

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:59.760
[Guest]: there are 5 crore fewer people working in India today than were working in 2014. I don't

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:06.160
[Guest]: think that this is an issue that's sufficiently spoken about. But this is government data

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:11.720
[Guest]: that the labour force participation rate fell, started falling, and went from 52%, which

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:17.520
[Guest]: it was in 2014 to 40%. And this is before the pandemic, it's not really the last two

00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:24.640
[Guest]: years that have done the damage. But what this will produce is a state that looks at

00:29:24.640 --> 00:29:31.120
[Guest]: its citizens with much more sympathy than has been the case in the past. So, I believe

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:36.760
[Guest]: that the arc of history does bend towards justice. And I think it will continue to.

00:29:36.760 --> 00:29:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And you referred to recent events, I should point out to my listeners that we are recording

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:47.040
[Amit Varma]: this on Feb 25. And the whole Russia, Ukraine thing happened yesterday. And yeah, and like

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:50.080
[Amit Varma]: you said, and like you've pointed out, I mean, I've done tons of episodes on the economy

00:29:50.080 --> 00:29:54.320
[Amit Varma]: before the pandemic, and we were already in dire straits. So we obviously only made worse

00:29:54.320 --> 00:29:58.440
[Amit Varma]: by COVID. I'm glad to see you so optimistic about the arc of history. Because I think

00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:02.120
[Amit Varma]: yeah, sure. I mean, if you step back and see the last 150 years, good things have happened.

00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: If you step a little further back and see 3000 years, you say 150 years is just a blip,

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:11.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, who knows. But so I did this recent episode with Rupur Dhawan Singh and Adil Hussain

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:17.400
[Amit Varma]: on this excellent book where they've reproduced Nehru's debates with four people. And one

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:23.440
[Amit Varma]: of them is Jinnah. And the reason this reminded me was that at the same time as one realizes

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:28.440
[Amit Varma]: that things change very fast, one also realizes that things fester very long. And there is

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:32.080
[Amit Varma]: an in that fascinating debate which Nehru and Jinnah are happening and how that their

00:30:32.080 --> 00:30:36.280
[Amit Varma]: book is structured is they write an introductory essay, but then it's Nehru's words and Jinnah's

00:30:36.280 --> 00:30:40.840
[Amit Varma]: words speaking for themselves. And it's a fascinating debate. And Jinnah is really not

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:46.080
[Amit Varma]: at his best in that particular debate. He's written much better elsewhere. And in that

00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:51.120
[Amit Varma]: debate, Nehru keeps berating him that I want to focus on poverty, I want to focus on this

00:30:51.120 --> 00:30:54.760
[Amit Varma]: and this is happening in the 30s. And I don't want to talk about the communal question.

00:30:54.760 --> 00:31:01.320
[Amit Varma]: The communal question is an issue only for you elites, right? And there I feel was one

00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:06.520
[Amit Varma]: place when Nehru was clearly wrong. It was not just an elite issue, Jinnah's fears of

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:11.600
[Amit Varma]: what a Hindu majority may do. And I think over there, he used the term Hindu Raj in

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:15.240
[Amit Varma]: one place. And Nehru was like, what are you talking about? How can there be a Hindu Raj?

00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:20.240
[Amit Varma]: And there I feel that, you know, Jinnah's fears were justified. His belief in the communal

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:24.120
[Amit Varma]: divide as it were his words, the communal question as it were his words, were borne

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:27.400
[Amit Varma]: out in a sense by partition and Nehru himself may have realized that he got a little bit

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:33.040
[Amit Varma]: wrong. And I think that many liberals have made a similar mistake to Nehru, thinking

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:36.200
[Amit Varma]: that hey, we'll put a constitution in place and we'll put these liberal values in place

00:31:36.200 --> 00:31:40.360
[Amit Varma]: and we'll put all these rights in there. And then there'll be no problem and it'll go away.

00:31:40.360 --> 00:31:44.320
[Amit Varma]: And I tend to side with Mahatma Gandhi's view on this, where Gandhi's view was that, listen,

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:47.760
[Amit Varma]: you have to change society from the bottom up. Even Ambedkar realized this when he called

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:52.720
[Amit Varma]: the constitution a topsoil, right? So, and what you see, and this is something that has

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:56.080
[Amit Varma]: festered, you know, I did an episode with Akshay Mukul on his great book on the Gita

00:31:56.080 --> 00:32:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Press. And one of the realizations there is that all of this has been there from, you

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:05.240
[Amit Varma]: know, has been an inherent part of our society from before. You look at the sales of the

00:32:05.240 --> 00:32:09.840
[Amit Varma]: Gita Press books, for example, you know, things like Love Jihad, even if it's a new term,

00:32:09.840 --> 00:32:13.800
[Amit Varma]: but things like Love Jihad and Cow Slaughter and all of that were live political issues

00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:19.320
[Amit Varma]: in the 20s and all of that, right? And we've kind of reached this space where now you could

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:24.320
[Amit Varma]: say society has caught up with politics, where in a sense, while I don't think we were ever

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:28.280
[Amit Varma]: much of a republic, you could say that we probably become more of a democracy because

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:34.760
[Amit Varma]: this is how the people feel. And our politics now reflects what our sort of society is.

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I look at that arc, and I don't see what is there to make me hopeful, because

00:32:39.240 --> 00:32:42.960
[Amit Varma]: the values that the constitution laid out, I mean, I know there are books like A People's

00:32:42.960 --> 00:32:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Constitution by Rohit De, which, you know, argue otherwise. And for India, you know,

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:51.080
[Amit Varma]: everything you say the opposite is true, as old cliche goes. But I look at that arc, and

00:32:51.080 --> 00:32:54.400
[Amit Varma]: I think that nothing has changed. We had this thing which festered, festered, festered,

00:32:54.400 --> 00:32:59.320
[Amit Varma]: you tried to brush it away, you tried to be in denial about it. And the elites basically

00:32:59.320 --> 00:33:04.200
[Amit Varma]: ran the country in an incompetent way. But now that that has kind of changed. This is

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:07.880
[Amit Varma]: what we always were. And this has now been amplified.

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:13.720
[Guest]: That's very true. I think that what Ambedkar observed in terms of the constitution being

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:21.240
[Guest]: a document that didn't necessarily reflect the society on the issue of caste has also

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:26.960
[Guest]: turned out to be true on the issue of communalism. There's absolutely no question that if you

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:32.680
[Guest]: look across India today, where we have 28 states, no Muslim chief minister, 15 states

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:38.520
[Guest]: in India, no Muslim minister at all, 10 states, one Muslim minister normally given a minority

00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:44.440
[Guest]: affairs, a ruling party with 303 Lok Sabha MPs, none of whom is a Muslim, which had 282

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:51.000
[Guest]: Lok Sabha MPs, none of whom was a Muslim. It is stark that the issue on which India

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:57.440
[Guest]: was partitioned, which is that one community saying that we want legally guaranteed means

00:33:57.440 --> 00:34:03.720
[Guest]: of representation, which was denied to them, which led to partition. It would be very difficult

00:34:03.720 --> 00:34:08.720
[Guest]: in 2022 to look across the landscape and deny what it is that you've said. That this is,

00:34:08.720 --> 00:34:16.800
[Guest]: as you've said, a society meeting its politics and agreeing that leave the constitution aside,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:23.160
[Guest]: this is who we want to be. And we are comfortable with this. Is this sustainable? I would say

00:34:23.160 --> 00:34:28.840
[Guest]: no. I don't think there are too many instances of democracies across the world. I would say

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:36.160
[Guest]: there is none, where 85% continually vote against 15% for them being the 15%. It doesn't

00:34:36.160 --> 00:34:41.640
[Guest]: make sense. We are an outlier on many other issues. So maybe it is the case that we will

00:34:41.640 --> 00:34:47.120
[Guest]: continue to do this to ourselves. I don't think that that will be the case. And I don't

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:53.760
[Guest]: think it will be too long before this shifts. And the reason I'm saying this is that at

00:34:53.760 --> 00:35:03.080
[Guest]: some point, the evidence cannot be denied. It is in front of you. And for a polity that

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:09.880
[Guest]: is coming into year nine, the evidence is there now. I don't think it's easy for people

00:35:09.880 --> 00:35:14.840
[Guest]: to look away from what has been done to this country over the last eight or nine years

00:35:14.840 --> 00:35:19.680
[Guest]: and say that it is good. You could be happy about the fact that a bunch of people are

00:35:19.680 --> 00:35:24.480
[Guest]: being brutalized. That's fine. And I'm sure there are many of us who do feel that. Are

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:30.160
[Guest]: there enough of that lot to make sure that this continues into eternity or at least for

00:35:30.160 --> 00:35:37.480
[Guest]: the next couple of decades? I would say no. It's highly improbable that given the performance.

00:35:37.480 --> 00:35:44.480
[Guest]: Would it be different if they were competent and authoritarian? I don't know. And it would

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:51.160
[Guest]: not be easy to tell because you would not know whether the vote is coming for the competence

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:57.920
[Guest]: or for the authoritarianism. But right now you've got incompetence and you've got a kind

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:03.640
[Guest]: of brutality, which is the primary selling point. I don't think the prime minister goes

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:08.760
[Guest]: out and says that I've changed the rate of GDP growth and we're going to become the next

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:12.520
[Guest]: China because we're not. He doesn't say that I'm going to get you a good job because he's

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:18.120
[Guest]: not. What does continue is the narrative that we've seen the latest one being in Karnataka,

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:25.600
[Guest]: the state we are in with what it is that Muslim women cannot be allowed to wear. Is this sustainable?

00:36:25.600 --> 00:36:37.720
[Guest]: I would say no. And I don't think I'm using my emotional side here. It's not possible.

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:46.360
[Guest]: It's highly improbable that such a polity continues in a democratic space. And I foresee

00:36:46.360 --> 00:36:49.240
[Guest]: it changing not before long.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:54.400
[Amit Varma]: No. So it's interesting that you said the evidence can't be denied. And of course, you

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:59.440
[Amit Varma]: wrote a book full of the evidence. And that's what I rather naively felt. Like, for example,

00:36:59.440 --> 00:37:04.760
[Amit Varma]: when demonetization happened. And I was very sure they're going to get massacred in UP

00:37:04.760 --> 00:37:08.480
[Amit Varma]: because I thought, you know, the largest assault on property rights in human history, the poor

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:13.480
[Amit Varma]: have suffered far more. How can they possibly win an election now? Right. And they swept

00:37:13.480 --> 00:37:17.000
[Amit Varma]: it and not, you know, obviously, there are little factors like schadenfreude, the poor

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:22.600
[Amit Varma]: thought the rich were hurt more and all that, which, but I, you know, I don't give, I think

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:29.120
[Amit Varma]: what has happened is that one people have always in India because of 70 plus years of

00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:34.640
[Amit Varma]: misgovernance become almost apathetic of the role of governance in their lives. They assume

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:39.040
[Amit Varma]: that everything is broken and it will remain broken. They exist and they do what they do

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:44.640
[Amit Varma]: despite the state. And therefore, they don't make that link between necessarily between

00:37:44.640 --> 00:37:49.760
[Amit Varma]: their vote and the governance that they are getting. And therefore, I'm not sure how much

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:54.360
[Amit Varma]: of this evidence really matters. And part of it is, of course, muddied by COVID because

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:57.960
[Amit Varma]: now it's easy to build narratives and say, hey, this happened and at least Modiji saved

00:37:57.960 --> 00:38:03.400
[Amit Varma]: your life and whatever other nonsense there is. So we'll see how that kind of plays out

00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:10.040
[Amit Varma]: because I feel that we've sort of entered a space where I don't know if reality matters.

00:38:10.040 --> 00:38:15.120
[Amit Varma]: It's all narrative battles. And when you think about it, no one person within himself actually

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:21.960
[Amit Varma]: sees reality. They see their own limited reality in their limited circles. Figures like what

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:27.080
[Amit Varma]: GDP growth may be or what is women participation in the workforce and all of those things.

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:30.440
[Amit Varma]: They are abstract things. They're not real to me. I see what is real to me and what is

00:38:30.440 --> 00:38:36.360
[Amit Varma]: real to me. If I'm poor and if I'm, you know, is that everything's been, it's been screwed

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:43.080
[Amit Varma]: forever. And then that kind of tribalism kind of kicks in. And I wonder if this is a realization

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:48.640
[Amit Varma]: that the other parties have also come to because the thing that dismays me even more than the

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:53.880
[Amit Varma]: way our government behaves is that all the other parties seem to think that this Hindutva

00:38:53.880 --> 00:38:58.600
[Amit Varma]: vote, this Hindu vote is a big deal, that they have to cater to it. One guy will win

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:03.400
[Amit Varma]: and do, you know, have recitations of Hanuman Chalisa. Another, you know, the Congress boasted

00:39:03.400 --> 00:39:07.640
[Amit Varma]: when the court judgment on Babri Masjid came out that it was after, you know, Priyanka

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:13.160
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi said, it was my father who opened these gates. So there seems to be this understanding

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:18.120
[Amit Varma]: that the core issue of today is this Hindutva thing that you can't go against that and whatever

00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:21.920
[Amit Varma]: else you do, like whatever AAP says about good governance and schools and all that,

00:39:21.920 --> 00:39:28.720
[Amit Varma]: it is on the margins. But this, this Hindu vote thing is a given thing. And, you know,

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:32.160
[Amit Varma]: in an idealistic way, I would like to believe that we contain multitudes. There are many

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:36.520
[Amit Varma]: aspects to our nature. You know, even if there is one person who doesn't like Muslims and

00:39:36.520 --> 00:39:40.200
[Amit Varma]: who doesn't want them to eat beef, he also wants jobs, he also wants a better future

00:39:40.200 --> 00:39:44.520
[Amit Varma]: for his children. But then I see the political parties who would surely understand this better

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:48.600
[Amit Varma]: than me. And they're not trying to appeal to those aspects. They are keeping in mind

00:39:48.600 --> 00:39:52.480
[Amit Varma]: that. So what's your feeling on this? Are the parties showing a lack of imagination?

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:59.160
[Guest]: No, I think that politicians understand the electorate, by which I mean the population

00:39:59.160 --> 00:40:03.320
[Guest]: better than most of us, better than all of us, I would say. And this is purely because

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:08.760
[Guest]: of the amount of contact they have, mass contact and regular mass contact. And so if they're

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:13.920
[Guest]: doing something, it has to be on the basis of something that they know. It's not, they're

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:22.240
[Guest]: not operating on instinct. They are actually functioning on knowledge. Do I expect that

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:28.880
[Guest]: a chart on employment or on GDP growth or whatever else might convince somebody to shift

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:37.720
[Guest]: their vote in a moment of epiphany or knowledge? I don't think so. I think that all of us as

00:40:37.720 --> 00:40:46.600
[Guest]: a species, for some reason, operate and decide things often on hope and change, which tends

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:53.200
[Guest]: to be narratives that are common to democratic politics around the world. And hope and change

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:58.440
[Guest]: is hope for something which is different from this and change from something which is different

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:07.500
[Guest]: from this. And I think that what this is, is not necessarily data. Because as you said,

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:12.800
[Guest]: most of us really don't know or cannot even be able to comprehend what it is that GDP

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:18.280
[Guest]: growth rate means. What does it actually mean? I have no idea. In a part of the world where

00:41:18.280 --> 00:41:25.600
[Guest]: consumption is limited to 15% of the economy and the vast multitude only consumes food

00:41:25.600 --> 00:41:33.720
[Guest]: and a bit of water and a bit of power and a bit of 4G and nothing else. What does GDP

00:41:33.720 --> 00:41:41.120
[Guest]: growth even mean? I really don't know. So, I don't think that it will be the facts by

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:47.940
[Guest]: themselves that produce the change. I think it is the reality that the facts are communicating

00:41:47.940 --> 00:41:56.720
[Guest]: that hope and change will come out of. And to believe that it will not, that this will

00:41:56.720 --> 00:42:04.920
[Guest]: not be the case, is to not be empirical. I think we will have to look at many decades

00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:11.760
[Guest]: of democratic nations and conclude that we are totally different from this, that we that

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:17.600
[Guest]: what we, we will remain democratic in the sense that we will come to the booth and vote,

00:42:17.600 --> 00:42:26.680
[Guest]: but we will almost never vote for anything other than hatred. I think that's what separates

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:33.600
[Guest]: the real Hindutva of the BJP from the fraud one of the Congress and Kejriwal. Theirs is

00:42:33.600 --> 00:42:41.600
[Guest]: a defensive one. It doesn't do what real Hindutva does, which is attack. It goes after the minorities,

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:45.720
[Guest]: the three things that made this party great. Muslims shouldn't keep that mosque, Muslims

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:51.320
[Guest]: shouldn't keep their autonomy, Muslims shouldn't keep their personal law. This that these people

00:42:51.320 --> 00:42:57.320
[Guest]: don't have. They might wear a janeu and they might go to a temple. That's not really Hindutva.

00:42:57.320 --> 00:43:06.160
[Guest]: It's not, it's not Hindutva at all, actually. Hindutva is the desire of people to actively,

00:43:06.160 --> 00:43:15.740
[Guest]: legally, politically exclude and brutalize minorities, especially Muslims. And that is,

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:23.240
[Guest]: if we are saying that has permanent appeal, I believe we would be either very wrong, which

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:29.800
[Guest]: I think we are, or we would be very different from the rest of humanity, which I don't think

00:43:29.800 --> 00:43:33.560
[Amit Varma]: we are. So I by your point that there might be an

00:43:33.560 --> 00:43:38.400
[Amit Varma]: active Hindutva as it were and a passive Hinduness. But at the same time, I think of Kejriwal

00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:41.880
[Amit Varma]: when 370 was repealed, he put out a tweet celebrating it saying it's a good thing for

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:48.920
[Amit Varma]: the people of Kashmir. You know, he equivocated on CAA and, you know, at no point did he sort

00:43:48.920 --> 00:43:53.120
[Amit Varma]: of support the protesters and all of that. So, you know, in our earlier episode, you

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:57.560
[Amit Varma]: had very eloquently said something that you argued in your book and that stayed with me,

00:43:57.560 --> 00:44:02.640
[Amit Varma]: is that if you think about Hindutva today, everything by which you define them is by

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:06.720
[Amit Varma]: what they are against, which is basically Muslims, right? There is nothing that they

00:44:06.720 --> 00:44:12.280
[Amit Varma]: are for, right? Now, the thing is, I also then wonder what are these other parties for?

00:44:12.280 --> 00:44:16.880
[Amit Varma]: We don't see enough of an articulation of that. What are the principles that you actually

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:22.120
[Amit Varma]: stand for? What is your vision for a better India? There will occasionally be lofty rhetoric,

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:27.600
[Amit Varma]: but when these fault lines open up, like Kashmir, like CAA and so on, one doesn't really get

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:30.640
[Amit Varma]: that. A lot of the time, of course, they will say the right thing simply because they are

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:36.880
[Amit Varma]: opposing something that is wrong. But apart from that, one really wonders, like, you know,

00:44:36.880 --> 00:44:42.960
[Amit Varma]: one conclusion that I have come to is that we think of, so many of us think of 2014 as

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:48.000
[Amit Varma]: a dividing line in two ways, where the BJP and so on will behave as if history ended

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:52.400
[Amit Varma]: at 2014, nothing happened after it. So everything is Nehru and Indira and this and that. And

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:56.880
[Amit Varma]: after 2014, you don't need to discuss shit that has gone wrong. But the other side, which

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:02.160
[Amit Varma]: is the opposition, will behave as if nothing happened before 2014, right? Where you are

00:45:02.160 --> 00:45:07.040
[Amit Varma]: not going to talk about, you know, everything that went wrong in the past. You know, for

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:10.880
[Amit Varma]: example, you argue, you know, people talk about the sedition law and the way Modi is

00:45:10.880 --> 00:45:14.640
[Amit Varma]: using it. But the fact is, it was declared unconstitutional in 1950. It was Nehru who

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:18.960
[Amit Varma]: brought it back with the First Amendment. And, you know, when Sanjay Gandhi's birthday

00:45:18.960 --> 00:45:22.640
[Amit Varma]: comes around, and you'll find it this year also, whenever it comes around, all the Congress

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:26.880
[Amit Varma]: Party official handles will be treating what a great guy he was, you know, there is no

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:34.320
[Amit Varma]: recognition of, you know, all of that. So, and it's so easy to kind of be virtuous in

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:39.600
[Amit Varma]: opposition as well. I mean, and there are other reasons why I'm kind of, you know, sort

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:43.680
[Amit Varma]: of pessimistic on several margins, and we'll go into them. But what is what what would

00:45:43.680 --> 00:45:45.840
[Guest]: be your response to this?

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:51.760
[Guest]: Many things here. I think firstly, Kejriwal's constituency has a bigger component of the

00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:59.000
[Guest]: urban middle class than most other large parties. And he's a large party only because of geography

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:04.520
[Guest]: and where he is rather than purely the number of voters. So, I'm not surprised that he would

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:13.280
[Guest]: take the opposition on Kashmir that he did. I think he's using the same thing as a visit

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:19.920
[Guest]: to a temple or being seen in a general event. And once again, I suspect and I think I'm

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:25.740
[Guest]: right that this is a defensive thing. And why is it defensive? I think that these parties

00:46:25.740 --> 00:46:30.560
[Guest]: are operating, this is your this is coming to your second point, they are operating at

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:35.960
[Guest]: a time when the narrative dominance of the BJP is absolute. So, they feel compelled to

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:42.800
[Guest]: do things and not talk about either the economy or the GDP because they are forced to speak

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:49.880
[Guest]: of specific things. Is this how politics and the language of politics was in 2003? I would

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:56.640
[Guest]: say no. From both the BJP and from the opposition, the language was different. It's not as if

00:46:56.640 --> 00:47:02.280
[Guest]: the BJP didn't want to go after Muslims then it did, but it didn't know how to and it didn't

00:47:02.280 --> 00:47:08.000
[Guest]: know I think Modi gave them a clarity of voice and a clarity of mission, which was lacking

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:18.640
[Guest]: in the past. So long as the narrative dominance is what it is, you will find the parties in

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:23.880
[Guest]: the opposition compelled to at least sort of address that bit before trying to talk

00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:30.360
[Guest]: about other things. Should parties talk about how bad they were in the past? I would probably

00:47:30.360 --> 00:47:34.880
[Guest]: say no, like there's no reason to politics is about the future and about optimism and

00:47:34.880 --> 00:47:39.560
[Guest]: hope. Should they defy people like Sanjay Gandhi? Definitely not. I think that's dumb.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:45.120
[Guest]: And I think that that shows that they haven't learned the lessons that they should have.

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:51.600
[Guest]: Look at Putin, somebody who's barely literate, dropped out of school after class 10, given

00:47:51.600 --> 00:47:56.760
[Guest]: charge and did so much damage. Arvind Narayan has written a very fine book called India's

00:47:56.760 --> 00:48:00.680
[Guest]: undeclared emergency, where he, from the first chapter chronicles what happened in those

00:48:00.680 --> 00:48:08.200
[Guest]: two years. Substantial damage. I think that it will be very difficult to argue that that

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:13.720
[Guest]: was a period, we were in any way different from what we are facing today from a pliant

00:48:13.720 --> 00:48:20.600
[Guest]: judiciary, no habeas, people locked up, forcibly sterilized, for God's sake, kicked out of

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:27.440
[Guest]: their homes. It was not very different in terms of the damage the state could do. And

00:48:27.440 --> 00:48:32.400
[Guest]: there is no question that when we move on from where we are today from the BJP, whether

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:37.160
[Guest]: it is the party itself or a change in the party that says that, okay, we will no longer

00:48:37.160 --> 00:48:41.600
[Guest]: focus on these things. And we'll move on to some other things. We will need to have a

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:49.600
[Guest]: new agreement within society, informally, at least, that we will not continue doing

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:55.960
[Guest]: what it is that we have in the past. I think that will come. And the reason I say that

00:48:55.960 --> 00:49:01.040
[Guest]: is because that is the nature of democratic politics, that you have to go back every five

00:49:01.040 --> 00:49:07.880
[Guest]: years and ask people a question and they have to give you an answer. And within that exchange,

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:14.880
[Guest]: I think we will find a more normalized way of functioning in our politics rather than

00:49:14.880 --> 00:49:20.240
[Guest]: being nasty to ourselves all the time, as has been the case in the past, I would completely

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:23.560
[Guest]: agree and is the case today.

00:49:23.560 --> 00:49:29.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when talking about current times, I often argue that we really have three problems

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:34.440
[Amit Varma]: and there's a proximate problem. And then there are two deeper problems that, you know,

00:49:34.440 --> 00:49:38.720
[Amit Varma]: remain with us and, you know, cause me to be so pessimistic. The proximate problem is,

00:49:38.720 --> 00:49:42.400
[Amit Varma]: of course, the government in power, right? Modi and Shah and whatever is happening and

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:46.520
[Amit Varma]: the proximate problem has been there since 2014. And we've seen what's going on. And,

00:49:46.520 --> 00:49:49.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, many people believe that proximate problem is the only problem that if the government

00:49:49.560 --> 00:49:53.280
[Amit Varma]: changes, you'll be fine. And I think that ignores the two deeper problems. Now, one

00:49:53.280 --> 00:49:58.120
[Amit Varma]: of those deeper problems is what we already discussed, which is the nature of our society.

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:03.200
[Amit Varma]: If our society is fundamentally illiberal, if our society is full of people who are bigoted

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:07.120
[Amit Varma]: and misogynistic and hate Muslims and all of that, then, you know, where is the hope?

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:11.760
[Amit Varma]: The other deeper problem is the oppressive state, right? And the oppressive state was,

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:16.200
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, hardwired into us. We took over the oppressive state from the British, you

00:50:16.200 --> 00:50:21.920
[Amit Varma]: know, the policeman state as one constitutionalist called it during those debates. We looked

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:26.600
[Amit Varma]: at it from the point of view of a policeman. And that oppressive state, that colonial state,

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:31.040
[Amit Varma]: as it were, remains a problem. Josie Joseph has a book about how it's been used and his

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:34.880
[Amit Varma]: book is not just about the Modi era, it goes back to way before. It is the way that it

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:40.560
[Amit Varma]: is. You know, all of many of these people who were arrested in this alleged Naxal conspiracy,

00:50:40.560 --> 00:50:45.960
[Amit Varma]: like Ferreira and so on, had been arrested before by the Congress in 2012, 2011, you

00:50:45.960 --> 00:50:50.240
[Amit Varma]: know, Ferreira wrote a book about his years in jail. And I think that those are the two

00:50:50.240 --> 00:50:55.560
[Amit Varma]: deeper problems. Now, I don't want it to seem that I'm minimizing this particular group

00:50:55.560 --> 00:51:00.640
[Amit Varma]: of people who are there. But what I am saying, and the one point where I'll differ with you

00:51:00.640 --> 00:51:03.960
[Amit Varma]: is that you say that when we are done with these people, we'll have a new agreement with

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:10.040
[Amit Varma]: society, your words. I think no, I think that even that new agreement in society is meaningless

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:14.800
[Amit Varma]: because people respond to the structures around them, to the incentives that they face. And

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:19.960
[Amit Varma]: this all powerful oppressive state in combination with the way that our society is, and you

00:51:19.960 --> 00:51:24.760
[Amit Varma]: know, it hasn't changed for decades for the better. So why should it now? And I'm not

00:51:24.760 --> 00:51:28.480
[Amit Varma]: saying there'll never be change. I just think that it's a really long haul. And if it changes

00:51:28.480 --> 00:51:32.360
[Amit Varma]: for the better, none of us may live to see it. But it's a really long haul. It's not

00:51:32.360 --> 00:51:36.920
[Amit Varma]: a six or eight year process. And these deeper problems bother me far more. Because I'm actually

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:41.160
[Amit Varma]: lucky to be living in Maharashtra, which is a state where the BJP is not in power. These

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:45.560
[Amit Varma]: deeper problems are around us. I meet bigots every day. I, you know, I feel the hand of

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:49.160
[Amit Varma]: the state. So, you know, what, how would you respond?

00:51:49.160 --> 00:51:54.960
[Guest]: I would actually agree with you. I don't think that anything you've said is either out of

00:51:54.960 --> 00:52:03.000
[Guest]: whack with what I think or what I've written. I think you've just organized it better. Is

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:08.760
[Guest]: one of the problems the state? I would say yes, that the way in which the laws have been

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:14.920
[Guest]: written, and the laws have been interpreted, the rights of the state override the rights

00:52:14.920 --> 00:52:22.880
[Guest]: of the individual almost every time that you have to go to a constitutional court to determine

00:52:22.880 --> 00:52:30.400
[Guest]: whether or not Article 25 is true and valid for the Muslim woman. And we are going through

00:52:30.400 --> 00:52:34.680
[Guest]: a period where a high court is listening to such a thing. Does the state have the right

00:52:34.680 --> 00:52:42.360
[Guest]: to deny somebody the right to wear a garment over their head? The state believes it does

00:52:42.360 --> 00:52:48.400
[Guest]: have that right. And the state wants to enforce that right. This is the important thing. The

00:52:48.400 --> 00:52:55.560
[Guest]: state is empowered in ways that it ought not to be. And the state chooses to engage with

00:52:55.560 --> 00:53:04.280
[Guest]: that power and chooses to wield it constantly. So, we may have spoken about this in the last

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:10.960
[Guest]: podcast, but the reality of that table of rights, you mentioned Singh, he's also written

00:53:10.960 --> 00:53:16.360
[Guest]: a book on Article 19. Do we have the right to peaceful assembly? We don't. You have to

00:53:16.360 --> 00:53:19.080
[Guest]: fill out a form and send it to the police station. The police has the right to tell

00:53:19.080 --> 00:53:22.720
[Guest]: you whether or not they will let you peacefully assemble. Do you have the right to freedom

00:53:22.720 --> 00:53:27.960
[Guest]: of expression? No, you don't. You've got criminal defamation, criminal contempt, sedition, you've

00:53:27.960 --> 00:53:34.640
[Guest]: got mob violence, you've got 153A. So, you don't really have the freedom to say things

00:53:34.640 --> 00:53:39.200
[Guest]: that people might be uncomfortable listening to. Do you have the right to occupation? The

00:53:39.200 --> 00:53:45.560
[Guest]: Supreme Court said no, that the right of the Bihari butcher to the fundamental right of

00:53:45.560 --> 00:53:53.960
[Guest]: the Bihari butcher to slaughter the animal that he had was overwritten by the rights

00:53:53.960 --> 00:53:59.360
[Guest]: of the majority not to have their sentiments offended. This is the Chief Justice of the

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:05.280
[Guest]: Supreme Court. So, there is a structural problem there with the state that you've given it

00:54:05.280 --> 00:54:10.520
[Guest]: too much power and it is enthusiastic and willing about using that power. Is there a

00:54:10.520 --> 00:54:17.280
[Guest]: mechanism that you can employ to change that? And I would say the answer to that is yes.

00:54:17.280 --> 00:54:24.040
[Guest]: And does history tell us that in the long view, states that have a fundamentally sound

00:54:24.040 --> 00:54:29.720
[Guest]: structure are able to reform themselves very quickly if need be? I would say yes, that

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:34.580
[Guest]: if you have a fundamentally sound structure, which I think we do, which is the Constitution,

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:40.200
[Guest]: the little stuff can be sorted out. Will the state be malign even if it doesn't legally

00:54:40.200 --> 00:54:45.680
[Guest]: have that power? I think it will to some extent because it is coded into the state to round

00:54:45.680 --> 00:54:50.160
[Guest]: up the house servants and beat them up first before they start any kind of, you know, sort

00:54:50.160 --> 00:54:54.680
[Guest]: of probe into theft. That's what they do. They beat people up. That's what the state

00:54:54.680 --> 00:54:58.640
[Guest]: is in India. The most efficient part of the state in India is the police. It's law and

00:54:58.640 --> 00:55:06.600
[Guest]: order. So, some of that will remain, it will be residual, but it will be drained out in

00:55:06.600 --> 00:55:14.240
[Guest]: time. There is no question that that is the trajectory of modern states.

00:55:14.240 --> 00:55:23.440
[Guest]: To the second point on society, slightly more difficult. I think because it's easy for us

00:55:23.440 --> 00:55:30.600
[Guest]: to engage with individuals and look at their traits, and it's much more difficult for us

00:55:30.600 --> 00:55:37.800
[Guest]: to portray that on a large number of people, that this is how they will continue to behave.

00:55:37.800 --> 00:55:43.880
[Guest]: Dindayal Upadhyay, in his lectures, which have been compiled, the four lectures which

00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:51.440
[Guest]: are called Integral Humanism, said that the nation was the same thing as a mob. And the

00:55:51.440 --> 00:55:57.560
[Guest]: mob he defined, these are not his words, I'm trying to explain what it is that he said.

00:55:57.560 --> 00:56:03.800
[Guest]: He said that it is possessed by a frenzy, which is not different one individual from

00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:09.080
[Guest]: the other within the mob. And at a larger level, this was what the nation was, that

00:56:09.080 --> 00:56:15.760
[Guest]: people felt something so similar that they could be compared to a mob and what the mob

00:56:15.760 --> 00:56:20.880
[Guest]: wanted. I found that sort of, you know, interesting. I don't think he's right. I think he's very

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:32.320
[Guest]: wrong. The human being has not evolved differently one nation from another. Cultures, faiths

00:56:32.320 --> 00:56:39.360
[Guest]: haven't evolved differently one nation from another. The effects on fertility rates of

00:56:39.360 --> 00:56:46.600
[Guest]: education, modernity, poverty, illiteracy, or wealth are exactly the same everywhere

00:56:46.600 --> 00:56:53.640
[Guest]: in the world. Now, if something so fundamental as sex and progeny is the same, is the rest

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:59.920
[Guest]: of it, can it be very different? I would say no. Is this purely once again, the question

00:56:59.920 --> 00:57:05.600
[Guest]: we were talking about a while back, whereas if you look at, let's say the sensex from

00:57:05.600 --> 00:57:12.600
[Guest]: where you're sitting, from 1980, it looks like this. But from where I'm sitting, and

00:57:12.600 --> 00:57:16.840
[Guest]: I've got a narrow view, it looks like that. And maybe are we looking at one of the troughs

00:57:16.840 --> 00:57:23.840
[Guest]: of a few years? I would say yes. So while I completely agree with you that the party,

00:57:23.840 --> 00:57:30.600
[Guest]: the first part of what you said was the issue, and you and I agree that it is a serious problem.

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:36.160
[Guest]: The other two have to be, you know, addressed. Will the second part be addressed through

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:41.760
[Guest]: a conversation we have with the ballot box? I think so. Will the third part automatically

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:46.680
[Guest]: then fall into place? Because it follows the rules of the second that the population believes

00:57:46.680 --> 00:57:52.360
[Guest]: that we need to do things differently, because our priorities must lie elsewhere in these

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:57.360
[Guest]: things. Does that change? I would say yes, it follows from there.

00:57:57.360 --> 00:58:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just think aloud. And of course, I agree with you entirely. And Mr. Upadhyaya

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:06.240
[Amit Varma]: is comparing a mob with the nation is rather strange. But there's one aspect in which he

00:58:06.240 --> 00:58:09.240
[Amit Varma]: might have something there, though I don't think he meant it this way. There's this wonderful

00:58:09.240 --> 00:58:12.840
[Amit Varma]: book by Gustave Le Bon written in the early 20th century, I think it's called The Madness

00:58:12.840 --> 00:58:15.560
[Amit Varma]: of Crowds or something. I don't remember. I'll look it up and link it from the show

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:21.480
[Amit Varma]: notes. But there's an interesting insight he shares on mob psychology, which is where

00:58:21.480 --> 00:58:27.920
[Amit Varma]: he has this concept of a threshold at which people sort of act. And you know, one of my

00:58:27.920 --> 00:58:31.880
[Amit Varma]: friends and you might know him as well, the journalist Rishi Majumdar, he was once lynched

00:58:31.880 --> 00:58:35.120
[Amit Varma]: somewhere in a small town, lynched in the sense lynched just means beaten up by a crowd,

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:39.600
[Amit Varma]: by the way, doesn't mean killed. So he was beaten up by a large mob. And he described

00:58:39.600 --> 00:58:43.200
[Amit Varma]: it to me the way he described it was that he was just arguing with a couple of people

00:58:43.200 --> 00:58:45.880
[Amit Varma]: and they were shouting at him and there were five, six people around him and they were

00:58:45.880 --> 00:58:50.200
[Amit Varma]: haranguing him. And then one guy who wasn't even part of that original bunch of people,

00:58:50.200 --> 00:58:54.560
[Amit Varma]: he just came from the fringes and he whacked him, right? Because whatever, I'm so macho,

00:58:54.560 --> 00:58:58.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to whack this guy. And then another guy whacked him and then people, then they

00:58:58.840 --> 00:59:02.840
[Amit Varma]: all joined in and everybody whacked him. Now what Gustave Le Bon, and I think this is Le

00:59:02.840 --> 00:59:06.360
[Amit Varma]: Bon's insight, I might get confused because I read a whole bunch of books on this at that

00:59:06.360 --> 00:59:11.560
[Amit Varma]: time. No, I think this is a crowds in power. Perhaps. Yeah. And the insight here is that

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:16.000
[Amit Varma]: everybody has a threshold that, you know, you might be a person who if you feel like

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:19.240
[Amit Varma]: hitting someone, you'll hit him. But then there might be someone else who will not hit

00:59:19.240 --> 00:59:23.480
[Amit Varma]: who be the first to hit. But if five other people hit, he'll join in and his threshold

00:59:23.480 --> 00:59:27.560
[Amit Varma]: is five. And there might be somebody else whose threshold is 20. And then eventually

00:59:27.560 --> 00:59:30.840
[Amit Varma]: everybody has a threshold and they all join in and they beat up whatever, right? And I

00:59:30.840 --> 00:59:35.120
[Amit Varma]: wonder if, you know, in the kind of actions we see around us, whether there are thresholds

00:59:35.120 --> 00:59:39.600
[Amit Varma]: in play as well. Anyway, that's a, I agree with you on the broad point that nations are

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:45.040
[Amit Varma]: not mobs. Now I'm going to sort of try to ask another broad question. And I'm going

00:59:45.040 --> 00:59:48.680
[Amit Varma]: to go back to what we discussed earlier of, you know, when we think of history, if we

00:59:48.680 --> 00:59:53.200
[Amit Varma]: think of 150 years, 200 years, it's a small sample size in the larger scheme of things.

00:59:53.200 --> 00:59:58.280
[Amit Varma]: And another way of thinking of it like that is that we think of nation states as having

00:59:58.280 --> 01:00:02.520
[Amit Varma]: some kind of permanence, right? That nation states have really been around for a few hundred

01:00:02.520 --> 01:00:06.920
[Amit Varma]: years, not, not really more than that in the modern form in which we know them. This particular

01:00:06.920 --> 01:00:11.960
[Amit Varma]: nation state of India has been around for less than 80 years now. In our minds, it is

01:00:11.960 --> 01:00:17.280
[Amit Varma]: a permanent thing. These are lines on a map. This is kind of what it is in the lived reality

01:00:17.280 --> 01:00:22.380
[Amit Varma]: of people. Once you forget about the oppressions of the state and the limitations that imposes,

01:00:22.380 --> 01:00:26.040
[Amit Varma]: this is not such a factor. Like I did an episode with Nirupama Rao a couple of days back, I

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:29.840
[Amit Varma]: recorded it a couple of days back, it might even release after this, where she spoke about

01:00:29.840 --> 01:00:34.200
[Amit Varma]: how the people of Tibet, when they would draw maps back in the day, there would be no borders

01:00:34.200 --> 01:00:37.880
[Amit Varma]: on it. You know, if there's a mountain, they don't want to divide it with a border. If

01:00:37.880 --> 01:00:42.340
[Amit Varma]: there's a river, they don't want to divide it with this thing that the cultural similarities

01:00:42.340 --> 01:00:46.040
[Amit Varma]: that we have and what brings people together and you've been to Pakistan, I've been to

01:00:46.040 --> 01:00:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan, we know this, we are the same people, right? You know, Lahore and Delhi have way

01:00:49.840 --> 01:00:56.120
[Amit Varma]: more in common with each other than Delhi and Chennai. And I sometimes wonder if, you know,

01:00:56.120 --> 01:01:00.480
[Amit Varma]: sitting from where we are, we make a mistake in assuming that this is the nation state

01:01:00.480 --> 01:01:04.320
[Amit Varma]: of India, it will always look like this borders will always be like this. And maybe that's

01:01:04.320 --> 01:01:07.680
[Amit Varma]: not the case. Maybe if you just step back, and you'll see that these things have been

01:01:07.680 --> 01:01:11.680
[Amit Varma]: in flux throughout, for example, you know, you do see a north south gap coming up, this

01:01:11.680 --> 01:01:17.200
[Amit Varma]: could explode when the delimitation issue kind of comes up. And we have the solidified

01:01:17.200 --> 01:01:21.880
[Amit Varma]: notion. And I would say that honestly, the India that you and I love, it's sort of an

01:01:21.880 --> 01:01:26.600
[Amit Varma]: abstract thing, which includes elements of culture and food and language and people and

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:32.640
[Amit Varma]: all of that. It is not lines on a map. Right? So what are kind of your thoughts on this?

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:37.240
[Amit Varma]: And do you think that some of the ways in which we think about the world could be constrained

01:01:37.240 --> 01:01:39.360
[Amit Varma]: by our thinking in terms of these lines on a map?

01:01:39.360 --> 01:01:43.640
[Guest]: Absolutely. I think that unless we acknowledge and come to terms with what we are doing in

01:01:43.640 --> 01:01:50.120
[Guest]: Kashmir, or what we have been doing for 65 years in the Northeast, this will not end

01:01:50.120 --> 01:01:57.200
[Guest]: well for those who think of nations as lines. Because it's unsustainable. We don't have

01:01:57.200 --> 01:02:02.920
[Guest]: enough sovereignty, because we live in a fairly engaged world, which we want to engage with,

01:02:02.920 --> 01:02:06.780
[Guest]: we are not telling the world go get lost, we are saying to the world, we want more responsibility

01:02:06.780 --> 01:02:12.080
[Guest]: in this world, give us a permanent seat on the Security Council. So we are as a polity

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:16.200
[Guest]: as a state, we are moving in a direction where we are willing to engage with the world more

01:02:16.200 --> 01:02:20.400
[Guest]: willing to engage with the world more necessarily means that you're giving up sovereignty on

01:02:20.400 --> 01:02:26.560
[Guest]: many things that you will listen to the world. That's the first aspect of losing sovereignty.

01:02:26.560 --> 01:02:32.320
[Guest]: That you have to stop speaking, let the other person speak and then respond to them, you

01:02:32.320 --> 01:02:36.080
[Guest]: might choose not to say anything back or you might say, as this government does, this is

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:41.120
[Guest]: our internal matter get lost. But the reason why you're forced to say even that is that

01:02:41.120 --> 01:02:47.440
[Guest]: it is the first element of a loss of sovereignty, which all states have no matter how powerful.

01:02:47.440 --> 01:02:53.320
[Guest]: In such a world as we are seeing develop, can you continue to have actions from the

01:02:53.320 --> 01:02:57.560
[Guest]: government as we have today in the Northeast and in Kashmir, I would say no, and I would

01:02:57.560 --> 01:03:04.440
[Guest]: say not for very long. And if you don't, the external world will force changes on you.

01:03:04.440 --> 01:03:09.920
[Guest]: And then you will not be able to see the same lines that you saw, or the lines that you

01:03:09.920 --> 01:03:14.440
[Guest]: even the lines on the ground today are not the ones that are there in my mind. Most Indians

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:19.680
[Guest]: would be very disturbed if they saw the actual map, and we're actually the line of control

01:03:19.680 --> 01:03:26.720
[Guest]: in Kashmir, for example, I was I think, 16 or 17 when I first saw it, and I was traumatized.

01:03:26.720 --> 01:03:32.880
[Guest]: Because the idea we have so anthropomorphize the map, and it looks so much like a like

01:03:32.880 --> 01:03:38.680
[Guest]: a person that any part of it, particularly the head, you know, being shown as being in

01:03:38.680 --> 01:03:43.040
[Guest]: a possession of somebody else seems very, very wrong and very off. And that's the way

01:03:43.040 --> 01:03:50.280
[Guest]: I felt then. External change will come. And I'm not just talking about the fact that we

01:03:50.280 --> 01:03:55.160
[Guest]: engage with the world and most nations want to be part of a rules based system where human

01:03:55.160 --> 01:04:00.720
[Guest]: rights is one of the rules, then it's not just that. I think the broadest parts of change

01:04:00.720 --> 01:04:06.240
[Guest]: come because of of technological shifts, and the rate at which it's happening today is

01:04:06.240 --> 01:04:13.640
[Guest]: much faster than it was in the past. Accelerating, in fact, one of the most obvious things that

01:04:13.640 --> 01:04:18.320
[Guest]: that occurs to somebody who looks on this and says, Okay, what does that have to do

01:04:18.320 --> 01:04:22.520
[Guest]: with the state? So when Jammu and Kashmir acceded to the Union, one of the conditions

01:04:22.520 --> 01:04:25.680
[Guest]: one of the handful of conditions they had was that communications would be controlled

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:30.720
[Guest]: by the Union government. Communications can't be controlled by anybody today. You know,

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:36.280
[Guest]: because communications that word meant the telegraph and the telephone, in a time of

01:04:36.280 --> 01:04:40.760
[Guest]: the world and maybe highways, if you were to sort of extend it. Today, none of that

01:04:40.760 --> 01:04:46.240
[Guest]: is actually relevant in a world where you can communicate without the without the state

01:04:46.240 --> 01:04:53.600
[Guest]: being an either a provider or an intermediary or an agent of any sort. A state can deny

01:04:53.600 --> 01:04:58.760
[Guest]: that to you for how long I don't know. But it cannot, it doesn't control communications

01:04:58.760 --> 01:05:04.880
[Guest]: anymore. That whole part is gone. One of only three or four things that the Union of India

01:05:04.880 --> 01:05:10.880
[Guest]: had wanted from Kashmir. So that that's, that's the nature of the world we live in. How much

01:05:10.880 --> 01:05:20.200
[Guest]: power will the state have over the individual and the way they lead their lives? 20 years

01:05:20.200 --> 01:05:26.240
[Guest]: from now, it's hard to imagine a world where what happens in Kashmir today, which is that

01:05:26.240 --> 01:05:33.880
[Guest]: there is no freedom of either assembly, where there's denial of community. Kashmiris are

01:05:33.880 --> 01:05:39.840
[Guest]: the only part of the world not to have had any education through the pandemic period,

01:05:39.840 --> 01:05:43.640
[Guest]: because for 17 months, they didn't have any net. It's hard to imagine a state doing that

01:05:43.640 --> 01:05:48.440
[Guest]: being able to get away with doing that 20 years from now, I don't think it'll happen.

01:05:48.440 --> 01:05:53.760
[Guest]: So what are the options? Either you fix it, or it'll fix itself. I think those of us who

01:05:53.760 --> 01:06:01.240
[Guest]: are line nationalists, as I have been for most of my life, will will have will be forced

01:06:01.240 --> 01:06:06.980
[Guest]: to fix it. These are problems that you cannot let fester for too long. If you want these

01:06:06.980 --> 01:06:16.920
[Guest]: lines to remain, it will be one or the other. And I think that the what you and I saw on

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:21.080
[Guest]: old maps, you know, where when you said it about the Tibetans, it sort of occurred to

01:06:21.080 --> 01:06:26.920
[Guest]: me that all really old maps don't have like they just say, Tibet, China, India here, you

01:06:26.920 --> 01:06:32.280
[Guest]: know, this is very big, there's no sort of nation state pipelines, it will probably become

01:06:32.280 --> 01:06:37.720
[Guest]: that. I'm saying that right now, again, looking at the kind of long view of history and the

01:06:37.720 --> 01:06:44.280
[Guest]: short view of history, global trade was low from 2014 onwards was very high before that.

01:06:44.280 --> 01:06:49.240
[Guest]: Last year was the biggest, there was a 23% boom in sort of global trade. Will that continue?

01:06:49.240 --> 01:06:54.320
[Guest]: Probably not, because there's a sort of limited space there is. But the desire is there that

01:06:54.320 --> 01:07:01.640
[Guest]: we want to be a world where it's easy for components to shift quickly, sort of in and

01:07:01.640 --> 01:07:08.920
[Guest]: out of countries without too much paperwork, so that efficiency is where it's at. I don't

01:07:08.920 --> 01:07:13.120
[Guest]: foresee that being too different for people either, that you will have movement, which

01:07:13.120 --> 01:07:21.240
[Guest]: will be fairly smooth and much simpler than it was 20 years ago, or is, you know, today,

01:07:21.240 --> 01:07:26.280
[Guest]: this sort of system, I don't think will continue for too long. And it's for nation states that

01:07:26.280 --> 01:07:32.120
[Guest]: are particularly nationalistic or have lots of nationalistic people within them to ask

01:07:32.120 --> 01:07:37.640
[Guest]: themselves what because there'll be a lot of trauma. This will come with a lot of pain

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:47.720
[Guest]: for many people who don't think of the world as a benign place outside of the nation, they

01:07:47.720 --> 01:07:53.280
[Guest]: see their geography in sort of Chanakyan terms, you know, where the immediate neighbor is

01:07:53.280 --> 01:07:59.120
[Guest]: an enemy and then so on. That's not I mean, that's neither is that the reality, nor is

01:07:59.120 --> 01:08:05.520
[Guest]: that something that they will be able to escape from in the very near future. I think in our

01:08:05.520 --> 01:08:11.320
[Guest]: lifetimes, I don't think that you and I will die in a nation that is even remotely similar

01:08:11.320 --> 01:08:17.240
[Guest]: to the one that we are living in. Yeah, I'm assuming we don't die too soon.

01:08:17.240 --> 01:08:20.080
[Amit Varma]: Well, I mean, in the long run, we're all dead, as you can see.

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:21.080
[Guest]: Yeah, that's very true.

01:08:21.080 --> 01:08:26.120
[Amit Varma]: I'm struck by what you said there about the relevance of the nation state and that in

01:08:26.120 --> 01:08:30.040
[Amit Varma]: many ways, it might gradually be becoming more and more helpless, because one of the

01:08:30.040 --> 01:08:35.300
[Amit Varma]: themes I've been thinking about and in different contexts, and it seems to really apply uniformly

01:08:35.300 --> 01:08:41.120
[Amit Varma]: and might apply to this also, is the dissipation of mainstreams and the decentralization of

01:08:41.120 --> 01:08:44.800
[Amit Varma]: everything. We see this in the media, for example, where you had a consensus on the

01:08:44.800 --> 01:08:48.960
[Amit Varma]: truth in the 90s, because you had these mainstream outlets, and they controlled everything. And

01:08:48.960 --> 01:08:53.240
[Amit Varma]: that's completely dissipated, you know, information, knowledge, anyone can kind of go there. And

01:08:53.240 --> 01:08:57.440
[Amit Varma]: I think net net, it's a good thing. But obviously, it has obvious negative effects, which we've

01:08:57.440 --> 01:09:01.600
[Amit Varma]: kind of seen equally in, you know, in the world of cinema, in the world of music, you

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:06.960
[Amit Varma]: have these kinds of dissipation, Steve Van Zandt said in a spoken and old interview about,

01:09:06.960 --> 01:09:11.020
[Amit Varma]: you had a mainstream in music, which was rock, only and in the Western world, only really

01:09:11.020 --> 01:09:16.160
[Amit Varma]: between the 60s, Beatles, Dylan going electric to Nirvana. And after that is kind of dissipated

01:09:16.160 --> 01:09:21.360
[Amit Varma]: in all kinds of little niches that often don't even talk to each other. And I wonder if that's,

01:09:21.360 --> 01:09:26.180
[Amit Varma]: that's, you know, one of those illustrations of something that is mainstream, not recognizing

01:09:26.180 --> 01:09:31.960
[Amit Varma]: its own irrelevance is the whole nation state kind of thing where we don't need to function

01:09:31.960 --> 01:09:36.700
[Amit Varma]: within those frameworks as well. Individuals are empowered by technology and trade to kind

01:09:36.700 --> 01:09:43.720
[Amit Varma]: of go beyond it. And a lot of the authoritarianism that you see is in a sense, a kind of response

01:09:43.720 --> 01:09:45.000
[Amit Varma]: to that.

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:54.700
[Guest]: I think that the the nation state is constructed for a reality which is very fast eroding.

01:09:54.700 --> 01:10:02.260
[Guest]: So let's say one aspect is the military, which is like a disproportionate sum is spent by

01:10:02.260 --> 01:10:10.200
[Guest]: many nations, which face very little threat on things on toys that they will never use.

01:10:10.200 --> 01:10:19.360
[Guest]: We bought 36 planes for 59,000 crore rupees, when the last war where we use fighter jets

01:10:19.360 --> 01:10:26.740
[Guest]: in meaningfully was 50 years ago. Do we foresee of war with the state sort of anytime soon?

01:10:26.740 --> 01:10:34.060
[Guest]: I hope not. But that is the the architecture of the state that it looks on itself, not

01:10:34.060 --> 01:10:44.220
[Guest]: only as a provider of security and a sovereign, but also a provider of services to the community

01:10:44.220 --> 01:10:53.940
[Guest]: that it services itself. Are we built for purpose as the corporate set would say? No.

01:10:53.940 --> 01:11:00.700
[Guest]: Because the impulse of the state in many parts of the world, including ours, is to focus

01:11:00.700 --> 01:11:06.140
[Guest]: disproportionately large resources on the negative side of what it does, stopping people

01:11:06.140 --> 01:11:13.300
[Guest]: from doing something, law and order, rather than being able to make things more sort of

01:11:13.300 --> 01:11:19.020
[Guest]: not just efficient, because that's a word that has been captured by the set that extols

01:11:19.020 --> 01:11:26.100
[Guest]: Aadhaar, but by making things easier for the citizen and the individual to enjoy their

01:11:26.100 --> 01:11:32.860
[Guest]: lives more. There is a disconnect between that kind of Ram Rajya type thing, which I

01:11:32.860 --> 01:11:38.300
[Guest]: presume is what was meant when that when that phrase was constructed. I hope it wasn't the

01:11:38.300 --> 01:11:45.140
[Guest]: fact that we should have a sort of society that is stratified by caste. But we're not

01:11:45.140 --> 01:11:53.860
[Guest]: and this will break. Either you change yourself or you fail. And failure comes to many states.

01:11:53.860 --> 01:11:59.340
[Guest]: It may interest your listeners to know that India has substantially moved away from the

01:11:59.340 --> 01:12:08.060
[Guest]: Nordic states on the failed states index towards Somalia and Yemen. We are moving in that direction.

01:12:08.060 --> 01:12:15.020
[Guest]: We're not there yet, obviously. But the direction of the movement is sort of in the wrong way.

01:12:15.020 --> 01:12:20.580
[Guest]: And I think only one reason is that first part of the three part problem that you spoke

01:12:20.580 --> 01:12:24.820
[Guest]: of, which is the party in power, I think, in large measure is also the third part, which

01:12:24.820 --> 01:12:31.300
[Guest]: is that the state is not built for the purpose of modern living tends to focus on the wrong

01:12:31.300 --> 01:12:38.180
[Guest]: things too much of the time. And we'll have to change or we'll have change forced on it.

01:12:38.180 --> 01:12:44.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm reminded of, you know, Francis Fukuyama had sort of, I learned about a framework of

01:12:44.260 --> 01:12:50.300
[Amit Varma]: looking at the state through him where there are you look at it alongside accesses of access

01:12:50.300 --> 01:12:55.420
[Amit Varma]: of scope and strength. And the problem with the Indian state really is that it should

01:12:55.420 --> 01:12:59.940
[Amit Varma]: do a few things and do them really well, like protect rights, like rule of law and all of

01:12:59.940 --> 01:13:04.460
[Amit Varma]: that. But it does many things and does them really badly. And of course, it does a few

01:13:04.460 --> 01:13:09.380
[Amit Varma]: things like rent seeking exceedingly well. But that aside, so you know, this is just

01:13:09.380 --> 01:13:16.520
[Amit Varma]: sort of a fundamental problem with it. I want to sort of, you know, almost continuing along

01:13:16.520 --> 01:13:21.240
[Amit Varma]: these same lines, but on a sideways theme, you know, one of the, for me, the most interesting

01:13:21.240 --> 01:13:26.380
[Amit Varma]: debate in that Nehru book I mentioned was between Nehru and Mohammad Iqbal. And there

01:13:26.380 --> 01:13:31.820
[Amit Varma]: I realized that, you know, there's almost a sense that Nehru doesn't understand what

01:13:31.820 --> 01:13:35.940
[Amit Varma]: Iqbal is all about. And then Iqbal writes him this letter where he's very patiently

01:13:35.940 --> 01:13:41.380
[Amit Varma]: explaining to him that it's almost like, dekho beta ye hai. And it seems to me that Nehru's

01:13:41.380 --> 01:13:47.100
[Amit Varma]: focus is on the nation state that is to come. That is true. That is India. And he's already

01:13:47.100 --> 01:13:52.460
[Amit Varma]: got that idea of India in his head, which he develops, solidifies all of that. And that

01:13:52.460 --> 01:13:57.620
[Amit Varma]: is where we are. And that is where we went. Iqbal's focus is on a bunch of different things.

01:13:57.620 --> 01:14:01.180
[Amit Varma]: And his thing is the Muslims of India and indeed elsewhere, are not just thinking of

01:14:01.180 --> 01:14:07.260
[Amit Varma]: a nation state, you know, they are also simultaneously grappling with does their loyalty lie to Umma,

01:14:07.260 --> 01:14:12.740
[Amit Varma]: which is a larger sort of Muslim brotherhood, a Muslim nation, as it were. And at this point,

01:14:12.740 --> 01:14:18.180
[Amit Varma]: we are in the British Empire, there is no Indian state yet. So, you know, while Nehru

01:14:18.180 --> 01:14:22.820
[Amit Varma]: is focused on that one thing, they are talking at cross purposes, because to Iqbal, there

01:14:22.820 --> 01:14:28.580
[Amit Varma]: are other worries, which encompasses which go well beyond this, all of those things.

01:14:28.580 --> 01:14:33.120
[Amit Varma]: And so tell me a little bit about and perhaps you could argue that, you know, some Hindus

01:14:33.120 --> 01:14:37.440
[Amit Varma]: may have also, you know, had a crude version of the same thing that it was not about nation

01:14:37.440 --> 01:14:42.700
[Amit Varma]: state, it was reaching ancient Hindu glory again, and all of that. But leaving that aside,

01:14:42.700 --> 01:14:48.820
[Amit Varma]: and it seems to me that in a sense, it's a tragedy for the Muslims of this geography,

01:14:48.820 --> 01:14:55.540
[Amit Varma]: that they kind of first got trapped by partition, and then they got trapped into a particular

01:14:55.540 --> 01:15:00.340
[Amit Varma]: nation state, which has now gone along this particular direction. And it almost seems

01:15:00.340 --> 01:15:03.980
[Amit Varma]: a discontinuity with history, they will, you know, there were thoughts kind of going in

01:15:03.980 --> 01:15:07.820
[Amit Varma]: different this thing. And I'm not obviously saying that the Umma could be something concrete,

01:15:07.820 --> 01:15:13.300
[Amit Varma]: or it could be something but in terms of your sense of identity, then perhaps being constrained

01:15:13.300 --> 01:15:18.500
[Amit Varma]: in one way, and perhaps being expanded in a good way, where you know, as a citizen of

01:15:18.500 --> 01:15:24.180
[Amit Varma]: a nation state, you know, there are good aspects to that as well. So what is kind of your sense

01:15:24.180 --> 01:15:28.220
[Amit Varma]: of the history of this, because now sitting in the current moment, everything seems solid

01:15:28.220 --> 01:15:33.740
[Amit Varma]: to us, that nation state India line on a map, it is solid, you know, we have Muslims, you

01:15:33.740 --> 01:15:38.140
[Amit Varma]: know, Pakistan doesn't have so many Hindus. So we are secular, but we have 15% all of

01:15:38.140 --> 01:15:43.620
[Amit Varma]: this is happening. Everything kind of seems solid. But these are really to me, for lack

01:15:43.620 --> 01:15:47.460
[Amit Varma]: of a better term, I'm not being very eloquent. These are kind of liquid questions. These

01:15:47.460 --> 01:15:50.860
[Amit Varma]: are, you know, the resonances of the past continue to echo today.

01:15:50.860 --> 01:15:56.300
[Guest]: No, the two things that I think would stand out in terms of not being as solid in the

01:15:56.300 --> 01:16:04.460
[Guest]: period that you're speaking of, would be first that the because they were in a weaker opposition

01:16:04.460 --> 01:16:10.900
[Guest]: in bargaining terms, the Muslim League said, they said two things. One is guarantee us

01:16:10.900 --> 01:16:17.100
[Guest]: a certain number of seats in these areas, and in the union, separate electorates, which

01:16:17.100 --> 01:16:21.100
[Guest]: was which the Congress said no. The second thing that they said as a compromise, if not

01:16:21.100 --> 01:16:27.540
[Guest]: this, then this. Not a strong union government, a federal government, a federation of states

01:16:27.540 --> 01:16:33.500
[Guest]: that become a unified India. Congress said no to that. Nehru wanted, Nehru is closer

01:16:33.500 --> 01:16:36.860
[Guest]: to the BJP in many ways, he sees India as this kind of, you know, civilizational state

01:16:36.860 --> 01:16:40.020
[Guest]: Bharat Mata, as you said, forward looking into what it could become rather than what

01:16:40.020 --> 01:16:46.540
[Guest]: it what it was. And also exactly like the BJP, the BJP, this is the same set of speeches

01:16:46.540 --> 01:16:54.500
[Guest]: again, did not want the states. He said that we cannot have Tamil Mata, Banga Mata, Bihar

01:16:54.500 --> 01:16:59.300
[Guest]: Mata, we only have Bharat Mata. So, there will only be one legislative body in the center,

01:16:59.300 --> 01:17:04.700
[Guest]: and you will have the village. And the dislike of federation continues. I think that GST,

01:17:04.700 --> 01:17:09.780
[Guest]: with GST, we've seen the states give up a lot of the power that they had, which they

01:17:09.780 --> 01:17:16.060
[Guest]: shouldn't have, I think. And you're seeing that people are questioning even article one

01:17:16.060 --> 01:17:21.980
[Guest]: of the Constitution, perhaps not knowing that it's there, that we are a union of states,

01:17:21.980 --> 01:17:30.620
[Guest]: which is what we are. So, at that point, I don't think they foresaw it becoming this.

01:17:30.620 --> 01:17:36.220
[Guest]: And I think that they would have acted, or at least tried to, I hope, in substantial

01:17:36.220 --> 01:17:44.580
[Guest]: measure to not reach where we have today. Iqbal, who died 10 years before partition,

01:17:44.580 --> 01:17:52.260
[Guest]: 1938, he went to Spain. So, he's a lawyer, not a man who was part of government, also

01:17:52.260 --> 01:17:58.580
[Guest]: poet, very fine one, went to Spain and went to saw the West and said, Spain is obviously

01:17:58.580 --> 01:18:05.100
[Guest]: the sort of what many Muslims consider to be the high watermark of their civilization

01:18:05.100 --> 01:18:08.900
[Guest]: and felt that there's something wrong that's happening here. And it's happened because

01:18:08.900 --> 01:18:13.940
[Guest]: of faith, that there's some linkage to faith, that if we are able to fix that, we can go

01:18:13.940 --> 01:18:18.820
[Guest]: back to be as good as we were then. And then we can compete with the West on good terms.

01:18:18.820 --> 01:18:23.740
[Guest]: I don't think that the idea was conquest. The idea was, okay, what's wrong with us?

01:18:23.740 --> 01:18:30.700
[Guest]: No, that what can we fix? And to his mind, the biggest influencer was faith, that if

01:18:30.700 --> 01:18:37.420
[Guest]: you fixed faith, then you would be able to fix yourself. So, he is a supporter of the

01:18:37.420 --> 01:18:42.180
[Guest]: idea that you Islamize government, that you bring in faith into the state. And then by

01:18:42.180 --> 01:18:46.460
[Guest]: that thing, two things change. One is the faith itself becomes more modern. And then

01:18:46.460 --> 01:18:52.580
[Guest]: the state itself becomes more sort of Islamic. When Liaqat Ali Khan speaks to the Constituent

01:18:52.580 --> 01:18:58.660
[Guest]: Assembly, the minorities are very vocal, they say that this is a problem, you're going to

01:18:58.660 --> 01:19:05.700
[Guest]: introduce religion into the law, we'll be discriminated against. His speech, he says,

01:19:05.700 --> 01:19:09.860
[Guest]: no, we'll make sure that that's not the case. But most of his speeches on the fact that

01:19:09.860 --> 01:19:14.620
[Guest]: he's saying that this is not aimed at you, it's aimed at Muslims, that the modernity

01:19:14.620 --> 01:19:19.580
[Guest]: had run far ahead, he's speaking in 1950. So, this is just a few years after the atom

01:19:19.580 --> 01:19:26.380
[Guest]: bomb is thrown on Japan. He's saying that it's reached far beyond the spiritual side

01:19:26.380 --> 01:19:31.420
[Guest]: of man, and we need to integrate the two. And so, he comes to the same conclusion as

01:19:31.420 --> 01:19:34.940
[Guest]: you know, Iqbal does that if we were to integrate faith into the state, we could reform both

01:19:34.940 --> 01:19:40.100
[Guest]: and make them sort of better, which didn't happen, obviously. The interesting thing to

01:19:40.100 --> 01:19:47.100
[Guest]: me is that while India in the last few years, legally speaking, has become communal, it

01:19:47.100 --> 01:19:51.740
[Guest]: has become has introduced religion into the idea of citizenship, the right to propagation

01:19:51.740 --> 01:19:57.500
[Guest]: was taken away from the Christians very early on, which is both a criminal offence and a

01:19:57.500 --> 01:20:05.100
[Guest]: fundamental right in this strange nation. And the sort of introduction of the criminalization

01:20:05.100 --> 01:20:11.780
[Guest]: of the possession of beef, what we are seeing with the hijab and the law, Pakistan's moving

01:20:11.780 --> 01:20:16.860
[Guest]: in the opposite direction, it's secularizing itself. So, Pakistan, Bangladesh and India

01:20:16.860 --> 01:20:23.980
[Guest]: have the same 150 year old penal code, which was given to us by a Macaulay. The only way

01:20:23.980 --> 01:20:27.460
[Guest]: that Pakistan felt it could do something different from us was to change that penal code. So,

01:20:27.460 --> 01:20:35.140
[Guest]: they introduced in the 80s, lashing for drinking, which they haven't carried out in decades.

01:20:35.140 --> 01:20:39.260
[Guest]: In fact, the Supreme Court has read down the offence of a drinking saying that it's not

01:20:39.260 --> 01:20:47.220
[Guest]: a sin. They introduced the hudhud punishments where you would cut somebody's hand off at

01:20:47.220 --> 01:20:52.840
[Guest]: the wrist for theft and then the leg the next time and so on. And they trained a set of

01:20:52.840 --> 01:20:58.340
[Guest]: surgeons to carry out these amputations and never even carried out one. Doctors were terrified

01:20:58.340 --> 01:21:03.580
[Guest]: when they were being trained, the judges were all trained in common law. So, Pakistan has

01:21:03.580 --> 01:21:10.420
[Guest]: tried to become sort of Islamic and very different from India and from Bangladesh but has failed.

01:21:10.420 --> 01:21:15.940
[Guest]: Laws that were introduced also in the 80s on say rape, where rape was taken out of the

01:21:15.940 --> 01:21:20.740
[Guest]: penal code and sent into Sharia, where if the woman who was raped couldn't prove by

01:21:20.740 --> 01:21:24.980
[Guest]: bringing four male witnesses to the act of rape, which was an impossibility, then she

01:21:24.980 --> 01:21:31.060
[Guest]: will be charged with a fornication. So, under Musharraf, that law was brought back into

01:21:31.060 --> 01:21:39.060
[Guest]: the penal code from Sharia. So, it's very difficult to tell the difference between the

01:21:39.060 --> 01:21:43.660
[Guest]: Islamic state of Pakistan and the secular republic of sort of India in terms of law

01:21:43.660 --> 01:21:48.700
[Guest]: because they pretty much show the same thing. Even in terms of policy, they show the same

01:21:48.700 --> 01:21:53.580
[Guest]: thing. Pakistan, by law, no non-Muslim can become the prime minister there. There is

01:21:53.580 --> 01:21:58.620
[Guest]: no chance of a Muslim becoming a prime minister here. So, whether it's through your actions

01:21:58.620 --> 01:22:04.940
[Guest]: or through your statement of intent on what you want to be, there is not that much difference.

01:22:04.940 --> 01:22:11.380
[Guest]: And I think that both sets of people, Nehru on this side because he was the most obstinate

01:22:11.380 --> 01:22:18.140
[Guest]: and I think Liaquat and Jinnah himself and the rest of them, Iqbal certainly, had looked

01:22:18.140 --> 01:22:25.700
[Guest]: on the subcontinent of 2022, would have had to recalibrate the way that they imagined

01:22:25.700 --> 01:22:29.260
[Guest]: both the nation state and the role of faith.

01:22:29.260 --> 01:22:33.660
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I mean, if Pakistan is moving in the right direction, then that's that's

01:22:33.660 --> 01:22:37.340
[Amit Varma]: one thing that supports your argument of the arc of history going towards a good place

01:22:37.340 --> 01:22:40.940
[Amit Varma]: as well. And one thing the arc of history certainly does is go towards a commercial

01:22:40.940 --> 01:22:47.740
[Amit Varma]: break. So, we'll take a quick break and then we'll come back and continue this discussion.

