[Amit Varma]: the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else. So please do head on over to IndiaUncut.substack.com

01:23:36.980 --> 01:23:41.900
[Amit Varma]: and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land

01:23:41.900 --> 01:23:47.500
[Amit Varma]: up in your email inbox. You don't need to go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The

01:23:47.500 --> 01:23:53.620
[Amit Varma]: India Uncut newsletter at IndiaUncut.substack.com. Thank you.

01:23:53.620 --> 01:23:56.900
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Aakar Patel.

01:23:56.900 --> 01:23:57.900
[Guest]: Hello.

01:23:57.900 --> 01:24:03.940
[Amit Varma]: So one of the really interesting bits about your Price of the Modi years book, and it's

01:24:03.940 --> 01:24:07.740
[Amit Varma]: a great book, a lot of it is interesting, but I love the introduction where you speak

01:24:07.740 --> 01:24:12.460
[Amit Varma]: about Modi and at one point you have this passage in the book where you write, Modi's

01:24:12.460 --> 01:24:17.300
[Amit Varma]: contribution has been to align the party to its original RSS roots while retaining and

01:24:17.300 --> 01:24:22.540
[Amit Varma]: increasing mass support and bringing crores more to the ideology of Hindutva. He has legitimized

01:24:22.540 --> 01:24:28.260
[Amit Varma]: and normalized the RSS and made its values promoting an exclusionary nationalism acceptable

01:24:28.260 --> 01:24:33.380
[Amit Varma]: to Indians. What was once communal is now legitimate and what was secular has been made

01:24:33.380 --> 01:24:37.980
[Amit Varma]: inauthentic. It is a remarkable achievement and must be acknowledged. Stop quote. And

01:24:37.980 --> 01:24:42.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, I want to ask you at this point about, you know, Carlisle's great man theory

01:24:42.100 --> 01:24:45.140
[Amit Varma]: of history, where the great man theory of history is, of course, that there are great

01:24:45.140 --> 01:24:49.620
[Amit Varma]: men who move history and make things happen and blah, blah, blah. Yeah. And many historians

01:24:49.620 --> 01:24:53.940
[Amit Varma]: would argue that that's not the case. We are giving too much credit to great men and women

01:24:53.940 --> 01:24:58.340
[Amit Varma]: and mostly men in history, unfortunately. And really currents of history move in a particular

01:24:58.340 --> 01:25:03.060
[Amit Varma]: direction and individuals don't play such a great role in that. And the reason I read

01:25:03.060 --> 01:25:07.660
[Amit Varma]: out the Para is I was, I was struck by this. Modi's contribution has to, is this, it is

01:25:07.660 --> 01:25:12.300
[Amit Varma]: a remarkable achievement. Now, on the one hand, it strikes me that, you know, that in

01:25:12.300 --> 01:25:16.300
[Amit Varma]: a sense is that this was waiting to happen. Society catching up with politics was waiting

01:25:16.300 --> 01:25:21.180
[Amit Varma]: to happen. Inevitably, at some point it happened. And, you know, you can argue about the timing

01:25:21.180 --> 01:25:25.860
[Amit Varma]: this way or that way, but it would have happened. But the other argument is that, like you're

01:25:25.860 --> 01:25:30.340
[Amit Varma]: saying individuals do make a difference. There's Modi who managed to build this personality

01:25:30.340 --> 01:25:35.820
[Amit Varma]: cult. There's Amit Shah, whose skills as an election manager are indisputable in the way

01:25:35.820 --> 01:25:40.460
[Amit Varma]: that he managed to consolidate the Hindu vote. And again, there are all the counterfactuals

01:25:40.460 --> 01:25:45.660
[Amit Varma]: like Keshava Guha wrote an essay about, think of all the untimely deaths, which enabled

01:25:45.660 --> 01:25:49.380
[Amit Varma]: the state of events today. Pramod Mahajan dying, for example, would Modi have come up

01:25:49.380 --> 01:25:53.700
[Amit Varma]: in the party in the way that he did if Pramod Mahajan hadn't died? Or within the Congress,

01:25:53.700 --> 01:25:58.980
[Amit Varma]: strong leaders like, you know, Cyndia Pilate and so on dying, you know, would, would the

01:25:58.980 --> 01:26:05.460
[Amit Varma]: family have captured the party so completely if those guys had still been around? So what

01:26:05.460 --> 01:26:10.100
[Amit Varma]: are your kind of views on this? Because it's very easy to make this one man, Modi, the

01:26:10.100 --> 01:26:14.780
[Amit Varma]: locus of the whole thing and say that, okay, he's come around and he's changed all this

01:26:14.780 --> 01:26:19.860
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. But the other side also seems plausible to me that this shit

01:26:19.860 --> 01:26:22.780
[Amit Varma]: would have happened anyway. Maybe somebody else would have been in charge. Maybe the

01:26:22.780 --> 01:26:27.540
[Amit Varma]: BJP would have come to power in 2019 instead of 2014. Maybe it would have been Adityanath.

01:26:27.540 --> 01:26:32.900
[Guest]: Maybe it would have been someone else. We don't know. But I'd see it as a, as a car,

01:26:32.900 --> 01:26:36.820
[Guest]: the car, the first gear is the most, the most powerful gear in the car. It takes you from

01:26:36.820 --> 01:26:42.900
[Guest]: zero to somewhere. Going from 40 to 60 is not that big a deal. Modi took a party which

01:26:42.900 --> 01:26:47.500
[Guest]: was at about 20% of the vote to about 38%. That is his contribution. He's widened the

01:26:47.500 --> 01:26:54.020
[Guest]: base he's brought in people who are not traditionally BJP voters into the party. He has also for

01:26:54.020 --> 01:27:00.260
[Guest]: the first part of what you read out, the context is a technical, that is the, when in 1980,

01:27:00.260 --> 01:27:07.060
[Guest]: the BJP decided to rename itself from the Janasangh, Vajpayee said that he wanted to

01:27:07.060 --> 01:27:13.020
[Guest]: transform what was a carder-based party by which he meant all the office bearers of the

01:27:13.020 --> 01:27:17.060
[Guest]: beat of the Janasangh were members of the RSS. That was the qualification that they

01:27:17.060 --> 01:27:21.660
[Guest]: needed to have. From that carder-based party, Vajpayee said, I'm going to make, let's make

01:27:21.660 --> 01:27:27.100
[Guest]: this a mass-based party, by which he meant that you don't necessarily have to be a part

01:27:27.100 --> 01:27:33.220
[Guest]: of the RSS to be a part of the BJP. But he was not able to succeed in large measure.

01:27:33.220 --> 01:27:40.300
[Guest]: But the fact is that from single digit vote shares, all through the 50s, 60s and 70s,

01:27:40.300 --> 01:27:46.820
[Guest]: the BJP only achieved double digit vote share and its first state victories after Advani

01:27:46.820 --> 01:27:52.140
[Guest]: took over the party and decided that this was a good issue to campaign on. Vajpayee

01:27:52.140 --> 01:27:57.700
[Guest]: didn't know what to mobilize people on. He had no idea that even Advani did not know

01:27:57.700 --> 01:28:02.220
[Guest]: that this would be a big issue to mobilize on. He says, he writes in his book, My Country,

01:28:02.220 --> 01:28:07.860
[Guest]: My Life, that he was surprised when he got the response that he did on his Arath Yatra,

01:28:07.860 --> 01:28:15.220
[Guest]: which Modi was the organizer of the first leg from Somnath. Then you had a very serious

01:28:15.220 --> 01:28:20.700
[Guest]: episode of violence and 3,000 Indians died. But the party got its first states, UP, it

01:28:20.700 --> 01:28:27.500
[Guest]: won UP. That was, I think, the shift for the BJP from being many decades run as a hardworking

01:28:27.500 --> 01:28:33.100
[Guest]: kind of RSS type discipline force into a mass force. That is what Advani did. Modi carried

01:28:33.100 --> 01:28:39.460
[Guest]: it to the next step. So, I don't think it is fair to either to Advani or the rest of

01:28:39.460 --> 01:28:44.420
[Guest]: the people within the BJP to say that this is one man's doing. It's not. It's much easier

01:28:44.420 --> 01:28:50.020
[Guest]: to take the party from 20 to 38 than it is from 0 to 5, which is what a lot of people

01:28:50.020 --> 01:28:56.580
[Guest]: did before him, including Dindayal Upadhyaya and Balraj Mathuk and Vajpayee, of course.

01:28:56.580 --> 01:29:04.940
[Guest]: What he's done in a period of our history, where the idea that India is destined for

01:29:04.940 --> 01:29:11.180
[Guest]: greatness and that greatness was not very far off, and that greatness could be achieved

01:29:11.180 --> 01:29:21.100
[Guest]: through an individual charismatic person, came together with this man. He had one more

01:29:21.100 --> 01:29:25.500
[Guest]: advantage, which is that he's the only leader in our history, the only chief minister in

01:29:25.500 --> 01:29:31.500
[Guest]: our history, because law and order is a state problem, to remain in office after a major

01:29:31.500 --> 01:29:36.820
[Guest]: pogrom. Nobody else in our, everybody else, if you look at Gujarat itself, 69, you know,

01:29:36.820 --> 01:29:42.420
[Guest]: Mahendra Desai loses his job. Wherever we've had violence, including in Maharashtra, Nayak

01:29:42.420 --> 01:29:50.940
[Guest]: was taken out, Pawar. When you have mass violence, we seem to think that we know that justice

01:29:50.940 --> 01:29:57.220
[Guest]: will almost never come. But one thing that we can do to move on from this is to change

01:29:57.220 --> 01:30:05.300
[Guest]: the face of the leadership so that society can feel that the past was wrong. And then,

01:30:05.300 --> 01:30:10.060
[Guest]: you know, we've moved on. It didn't happen in Gujarat. Not only did it not happen, he

01:30:10.060 --> 01:30:17.980
[Guest]: was endorsed by the Hindu voters three times after that. And so he was able to, without

01:30:17.980 --> 01:30:28.860
[Guest]: doing anything, retain that Hindutva majoritarian charisma that was his when he oversaw the

01:30:28.860 --> 01:30:35.820
[Guest]: events which are this week, exactly 20 years old. Vajpayee was unable to remove him. He

01:30:35.820 --> 01:30:42.220
[Guest]: tried to wrestle him down in Goa. And Modi said that he would resign if the party wanted

01:30:42.220 --> 01:30:49.740
[Guest]: it to. The carder barked at Vajpayee and said, you can't do this. He has to remain. And I

01:30:49.740 --> 01:30:56.220
[Guest]: think he expresses a very confident majoritarianism, which Vajpayee did not or could not. Advani

01:30:56.220 --> 01:31:03.060
[Guest]: tried to but also muffled his voice by saying, you know, saddest day of my life sort of nonsense.

01:31:03.060 --> 01:31:07.500
[Guest]: There is nothing apologetic about what Modi says or does, which is what makes him attractive

01:31:07.500 --> 01:31:14.980
[Guest]: to a large part of his constituency. In his absence, to sort of return to what you said,

01:31:14.980 --> 01:31:20.980
[Guest]: would we still have arrived at this place? I would say no. It is highly unlikely that

01:31:20.980 --> 01:31:26.900
[Guest]: the natural course would have brought us here. And for this reason that in taking the party

01:31:26.900 --> 01:31:33.580
[Guest]: from 20 to 38, he brought in people who are not traditionally majoritarian voters. A large

01:31:33.580 --> 01:31:41.860
[Guest]: part of his popularity, which is then reflected in his image in the media, is his messianic

01:31:41.860 --> 01:31:47.220
[Guest]: quality as somebody who will bring India to what is called a developed nation, whatever

01:31:47.220 --> 01:31:53.660
[Guest]: that means. That will sort of become the next US or the next China, which we are not clearly

01:31:53.660 --> 01:32:02.700
[Guest]: now that the evidence is there. And that part of that vote would not have come to the BJP

01:32:02.700 --> 01:32:09.220
[Guest]: just automatically. You needed somebody from a mercantile type background, running a state

01:32:09.220 --> 01:32:18.060
[Guest]: for several years and able to still retain that quality of being Hindutva minded automatically

01:32:18.060 --> 01:32:22.140
[Guest]: as he is. So, he was able to bring those things together. In his absence, I don't think they

01:32:22.140 --> 01:32:29.340
[Guest]: would be at 38%. Would he have brought the party to 5% from zero? I would say no. He

01:32:29.340 --> 01:32:37.700
[Guest]: doesn't have the focus or the concentration, extremely solipsistic and sort of inward looking.

01:32:37.700 --> 01:32:42.500
[Guest]: He is the antithesis of all those people who we barely remember the faces of, who brought

01:32:42.500 --> 01:32:51.980
[Guest]: the party to 18 and 20%. And I think because he's spent two decades in office of sitting

01:32:51.980 --> 01:33:00.900
[Guest]: over absolute majorities for all of these 20 years, he's never learned how to compromise,

01:33:00.900 --> 01:33:06.780
[Guest]: how to take no for an answer, how to step back. And he's been forced to externally by

01:33:06.780 --> 01:33:11.980
[Guest]: the women of Shaheen Bagh on the issue of CA, by the farmers mostly Sikh on the issue

01:33:11.980 --> 01:33:18.740
[Guest]: of the farm laws, as will happen also on the issue of hijab. And that is not the sign of

01:33:18.740 --> 01:33:23.740
[Guest]: somebody who can build something. You can only construct when you have the patience

01:33:23.740 --> 01:33:28.660
[Guest]: and the ability to work with people. If you focus on yourself all the time, which he is,

01:33:28.660 --> 01:33:35.460
[Guest]: you're not going to be able to build too much. So, in this instance, definitely, I would

01:33:35.460 --> 01:33:42.460
[Guest]: say that in his absence, the party would not be where it is today. But also that in his

01:33:42.460 --> 01:33:47.460
[Guest]: presence, the party would not be aware it was in the 60s and 70s.

01:33:47.460 --> 01:33:52.960
[Amit Varma]: Lots to think about that. But you know, my brief counterpoint to that would be that this

01:33:52.960 --> 01:33:58.300
[Amit Varma]: widening of the base, I think it started happening before that. I mean, even if you think back

01:33:58.300 --> 01:34:04.820
[Amit Varma]: to 2010-2011, India against corruption, the anger against the debt dispensation coming

01:34:04.820 --> 01:34:09.460
[Amit Varma]: to the brim, people just fed up of corruption, people fed up of everything that was happening,

01:34:09.460 --> 01:34:13.300
[Amit Varma]: you know, and had Vajpayee been 10 years younger and still been around, he would actually have

01:34:13.300 --> 01:34:17.300
[Amit Varma]: had a record in government to point out because he did do a lot of economic reforms. And in

01:34:17.300 --> 01:34:22.380
[Amit Varma]: that sense, he had already walked that talk to some extent. I feel like Modi was right

01:34:22.380 --> 01:34:26.340
[Amit Varma]: time right place in the sense he came along at a time where everything was there and he

01:34:26.340 --> 01:34:30.420
[Amit Varma]: captured it and he embodied it. And there's no question that he obviously didn't believe

01:34:30.420 --> 01:34:34.580
[Amit Varma]: it because a lot of the rhetoric that he gave like Salman Sohs was on my show and he said

01:34:34.580 --> 01:34:37.820
[Amit Varma]: even though I'm from the Congress, when he came to power, there's a part of me, which

01:34:37.820 --> 01:34:41.740
[Amit Varma]: said maybe it's a good thing. Maybe he'll do all of these things, minimum government,

01:34:41.740 --> 01:34:46.100
[Amit Varma]: maximum governance, and all of that. And of course, none of that happened. You realized

01:34:46.100 --> 01:34:50.100
[Amit Varma]: immediately that that was just kind of BS. I'm also struck by, you know, the narrative

01:34:50.100 --> 01:34:57.340
[Amit Varma]: of the 80s that when when Vajpayee started the BJP circa 1980, he spoke of Gandhian socialism,

01:34:57.340 --> 01:35:00.780
[Amit Varma]: because he wanted to kind of expand that, you know, they got very few seats in that

01:35:00.780 --> 01:35:05.660
[Amit Varma]: first 84 parliament, but Veer Sanghvi's argument in his book, and he also expanded upon it

01:35:05.660 --> 01:35:12.060
[Amit Varma]: in his episode with me, was that that 1984 vote for Rajiv Gandhi was a Hindu vote, because

01:35:12.060 --> 01:35:16.020
[Amit Varma]: it was an anti Sikh vote, it was a Hindu vote, he had the Hindu vote, the BJP realized that

01:35:16.020 --> 01:35:18.900
[Amit Varma]: what the hell is happening, we are talking Gandhian socialism, while the Congress is

01:35:18.900 --> 01:35:23.820
[Amit Varma]: getting the Hindu vote. So they pivoted, and they went hardcore and Rajiv Gandhi didn't

01:35:23.820 --> 01:35:27.860
[Amit Varma]: realize this, and he lost that. And you know, and it worked out for the BJP right time,

01:35:27.860 --> 01:35:32.340
[Amit Varma]: right place, everything, but it was Rajiv Gandhi who opened up, you know, the Babri

01:35:32.340 --> 01:35:39.780
[Amit Varma]: Masjid at that time. So it's, it's like, that force in society, you know, whether you call

01:35:39.780 --> 01:35:44.220
[Amit Varma]: it the Hindu vote, whether you judge it one way or another way, that doesn't matter that

01:35:44.220 --> 01:35:49.700
[Amit Varma]: force was there, it was going to be expressed, it was going to grow. And it kind of, you

01:35:49.700 --> 01:35:53.980
[Amit Varma]: know, went in that direction. Would you differ with for example, some, you know, Veer's view

01:35:53.980 --> 01:35:59.500
[Guest]: of the 80s and so on? I haven't read his book, but I'll say this, that what do we know about

01:35:59.500 --> 01:36:02.900
[Guest]: the manifestos of the Jana Sangh and the BJP, they don't change at all. It's exactly the

01:36:02.900 --> 01:36:11.260
[Guest]: same issues throughout the decades. When Vajpayee cedes the presidency to Advani for two years,

01:36:11.260 --> 01:36:15.860
[Guest]: Advani doesn't do anything, he doesn't know what to do, basically. What happens is that

01:36:15.860 --> 01:36:21.020
[Guest]: a bunch of people within the BJP who are also connected to the VHP, including Raj Mathas

01:36:21.020 --> 01:36:28.220
[Guest]: India and Katiyar, they begin to associate themselves with this movement, which says

01:36:28.220 --> 01:36:34.760
[Guest]: that we need to break this mosque, and we need to build a temple. Advani at some point

01:36:34.760 --> 01:36:38.620
[Guest]: determines that he will throw the party's weight behind it, despite the fact that as

01:36:38.620 --> 01:36:42.500
[Guest]: you see the BJP's constitution, the first page of which says that we will, we will sort

01:36:42.500 --> 01:36:48.300
[Guest]: of adhere to Gandhian socialism, that will be the party's guiding, that will be the party's

01:36:48.300 --> 01:36:53.100
[Guest]: official philosophy, I think, if I'm not mistaken, and the guiding philosophy will be integral

01:36:53.100 --> 01:36:57.900
[Guest]: humanism. They also, Vajpayee, nine years before the law was passed, puts in secular

01:36:57.900 --> 01:37:04.780
[Guest]: into the party's constitution saying that we will sort of adhere to secularism. I think

01:37:04.780 --> 01:37:11.340
[Guest]: the shift is the Babri Masjid, that you can you mobilize around violence against Muslims

01:37:11.340 --> 01:37:17.740
[Guest]: and Advani figures that the answer to that is yes. Would that naturally have happened

01:37:17.740 --> 01:37:22.820
[Guest]: in democratic politics? No, you need an agent to make it nasty. Democratic politics, like

01:37:22.820 --> 01:37:30.060
[Guest]: the reason why it is the if you are sane in this country, you don't have a problem with

01:37:30.060 --> 01:37:36.860
[Guest]: TMC, like don't have too much of a problem with the TMC, or the INC or the ADMK or the

01:37:36.860 --> 01:37:45.300
[Guest]: DMK or whatever or Naveen Patnaik or PDP or you know, whoever else. But if you do have

01:37:45.300 --> 01:37:49.420
[Guest]: that bent of mind, you there is only one party for you. It's only the BJP wherever in the

01:37:49.420 --> 01:37:55.260
[Guest]: country you are. So, that tells you that it's not normal. Doing this requires something

01:37:55.260 --> 01:38:01.380
[Guest]: within you that most people don't have, most parties don't want to have. The BJP has it,

01:38:01.380 --> 01:38:07.860
[Guest]: it wants to do this. It's the best at doing it. For this reason, that it's genuine. It's

01:38:07.860 --> 01:38:15.260
[Guest]: the real thing. It's genuinely bigoted. And it displays its bigotry. Well, Modi is the

01:38:15.260 --> 01:38:23.300
[Guest]: best person to express it. You spoke about Vajpayee and the deautees or the late 90s

01:38:23.300 --> 01:38:27.220
[Guest]: and walking the talk. Modi doesn't walk, he only talks. There is no the demonstration

01:38:27.220 --> 01:38:31.300
[Guest]: is there. Eight years is sufficient evidence. There is no this is the period between the

01:38:31.300 --> 01:38:36.980
[Guest]: capture of the chancellorship and the beginning of the Second World War. All of the work has

01:38:36.980 --> 01:38:42.140
[Guest]: all the time is already there. The data shows that there is failure. You could argue that

01:38:42.140 --> 01:38:47.740
[Guest]: we got one lakh crore rupees in GST last year, which is what, in his defense, he said that,

01:38:47.740 --> 01:38:53.580
[Guest]: oh, you know, the GST, we are back to where we were in 2018. And that's a great sign.

01:38:53.580 --> 01:39:01.380
[Guest]: I don't know what that means. But he's not able to walk. He's shown that. He walks in

01:39:01.380 --> 01:39:08.060
[Guest]: disastrous ways like demonetization was literally stamping on the messianic figures in our part

01:39:08.060 --> 01:39:11.940
[Guest]: of the world are dangerous, whether they are from the Congress Party, or whether they are

01:39:11.940 --> 01:39:17.940
[Guest]: from from the BJP, because the polity will just dissolve, not only bend, it will not

01:39:17.940 --> 01:39:25.820
[Guest]: there is no ability to say no. And there is no ability to execute with competence, which

01:39:25.820 --> 01:39:30.660
[Guest]: is the worst kind of thing to be in and have a very strong leader, which we which is what

01:39:30.660 --> 01:39:36.100
[Guest]: we have. And which is why we are where we are. I did an episode with Vinay Sitapati

01:39:36.100 --> 01:39:40.540
[Amit Varma]: on his book on you know, the BJP for Modi as it were. And one of the interesting points

01:39:40.540 --> 01:39:45.460
[Amit Varma]: he made there was that in his view, you know, Vajpayee and Advani were playing the game

01:39:45.460 --> 01:39:50.220
[Amit Varma]: because that's where they saw the biggest benefit for their politics that this is how

01:39:50.220 --> 01:39:53.340
[Amit Varma]: you can mobilize people and blah, blah, blah. But according to him, Modi and Shah were true

01:39:53.340 --> 01:39:58.660
[Amit Varma]: believers, you know, which is dangerous and which ties in with what you're kind of saying.

01:39:58.660 --> 01:40:04.260
[Amit Varma]: I want to talk a little bit about Modi now, but in a sense that there is a wider application

01:40:04.260 --> 01:40:09.260
[Amit Varma]: to of this as well. So I had written a column a few years back called the Aankho Dekhi Prime

01:40:09.260 --> 01:40:14.180
[Amit Varma]: Minister. And that was based on an anecdote that a friend of Modi's told me. And this

01:40:14.180 --> 01:40:19.220
[Amit Varma]: friend of his used to work with him in the aughties when he was CM of Gujarat. And she

01:40:19.220 --> 01:40:23.420
[Amit Varma]: describes that one evening there was like a personal gathering at his residence of six

01:40:23.420 --> 01:40:29.380
[Amit Varma]: or seven people. And he was telling them a story about how his mother was once ill. When

01:40:29.380 --> 01:40:32.700
[Amit Varma]: he was a boy, his mother was very ill and he went to switch on the fan because she was

01:40:32.700 --> 01:40:37.260
[Amit Varma]: feeling hot. And he realized that there is no electricity. And as he related the story,

01:40:37.260 --> 01:40:42.940
[Amit Varma]: he started crying. And my friend's point of this was that his understanding of the world

01:40:42.940 --> 01:40:50.060
[Amit Varma]: is purely experiential. He has experienced that electricity is a big deal. He has experienced

01:40:50.060 --> 01:40:55.460
[Amit Varma]: that roads matter. So when he comes to power, these are the things he focuses on. But beyond

01:40:55.460 --> 01:41:01.040
[Amit Varma]: this, he can't comprehend anything. In fact, my column was sort of in a sense an argument

01:41:01.040 --> 01:41:06.180
[Amit Varma]: for reading more that, you know, an experiential understanding of the world only goes so far.

01:41:06.180 --> 01:41:10.140
[Amit Varma]: There are so many things beyond this, especially when you're running a country, you'll you

01:41:10.140 --> 01:41:15.500
[Amit Varma]: think of things like, you know, spontaneous order, the way economies organize themselves

01:41:15.500 --> 01:41:19.660
[Amit Varma]: and how all human interactions are a positive sum game. And these are unintuitive things

01:41:19.660 --> 01:41:24.700
[Amit Varma]: that you do not really understand all the time from personal experience. And my point

01:41:24.700 --> 01:41:28.900
[Amit Varma]: with him was that in his case, one cannot judge him for not being a good reader, because

01:41:28.900 --> 01:41:32.260
[Amit Varma]: that's a question of privilege. If he hasn't read, he hasn't read. But then the approach

01:41:32.260 --> 01:41:37.740
[Amit Varma]: of a person like that is that you have the intellectual humility, you surround yourself

01:41:37.740 --> 01:41:42.980
[Amit Varma]: with experts, and you listen to them. And you understand the limitations of your own

01:41:42.980 --> 01:41:47.700
[Amit Varma]: knowledge and understanding. And in that area, he's completely lacking. And I want to quote

01:41:47.700 --> 01:41:52.140
[Amit Varma]: this bit. And this is really you quoting Modi. So it's Modi himself, where in your book,

01:41:52.140 --> 01:41:56.940
[Amit Varma]: you quote this Madhu Kishwer interview from 2014. And there and these are Modi's words

01:41:56.940 --> 01:42:01.180
[Amit Varma]: which are quoting that as a YouTube link, I'll put in the show notes. And he told Ms.

01:42:01.180 --> 01:42:05.300
[Amit Varma]: Kishwer, quote, three or four days after I had taken office as chief minister, the chief

01:42:05.300 --> 01:42:09.660
[Amit Varma]: secretary came to me, he brought a heap of files this tall, and he made a gesture about

01:42:09.660 --> 01:42:13.740
[Amit Varma]: three feet high, they must have weighed 15 or 20 kilos, the PN left them on my table,

01:42:13.740 --> 01:42:18.500
[Amit Varma]: the chief secretary sat and said to me, this is a file for Narmada. I can remember Narmada,

01:42:18.500 --> 01:42:22.420
[Amit Varma]: but there were three other files also. The CES said, these are on Gujarat's vital and

01:42:22.420 --> 01:42:26.220
[Amit Varma]: sensitive issues, take the time out to read them, you may need to speak on or take a position

01:42:26.220 --> 01:42:31.300
[Amit Varma]: on at any time and address all these issues. I kept looking up and down the height of the

01:42:31.300 --> 01:42:35.300
[Amit Varma]: stack three or four times I said to him, you leave here and we shall meet in a few days.

01:42:35.300 --> 01:42:39.420
[Amit Varma]: I did not even open those files, they stayed where they were, stop quote, and so on and

01:42:39.420 --> 01:42:43.620
[Amit Varma]: so forth. And basically, the thrust of it is that he'll tell any of the bureaucrats

01:42:43.620 --> 01:42:48.900
[Amit Varma]: with him that you summarize it in a couple of words, and in a couple of lines, or, you

01:42:48.900 --> 01:42:53.300
[Amit Varma]: know, you know, give me a couple of slides and basically, just sort of sum it up. So

01:42:53.300 --> 01:42:57.180
[Amit Varma]: obviously no appetite for complexity. And this also reminds me of something that Harry

01:42:57.180 --> 01:43:01.500
[Amit Varma]: Truman said when he was president, where he said, give me a one handed economist, because

01:43:01.500 --> 01:43:05.020
[Amit Varma]: all his economists kept saying on one hand this on the other hand that so he was like,

01:43:05.020 --> 01:43:12.580
[Amit Varma]: no, you want certainty, you want to be able to take decisions. And I and the reason I,

01:43:12.580 --> 01:43:16.700
[Amit Varma]: you know, love this part where you talk about Modi is that you talk about two qualities

01:43:16.700 --> 01:43:21.900
[Amit Varma]: that are ascribed to him, decisiveness and charismatic, and you break it down. And you

01:43:21.900 --> 01:43:27.740
[Amit Varma]: talk about why they are really bad qualities. And it seemed to me that this simplistic appetite

01:43:27.740 --> 01:43:32.660
[Amit Varma]: for knowledge that you know, make it simple and give it to me. And you know, the certainties

01:43:32.660 --> 01:43:37.020
[Amit Varma]: that come from this, it seems to me that they tie in directly to these two words decisive

01:43:37.020 --> 01:43:40.860
[Amit Varma]: and charismatic. So break those down a little bit for me, because I love the way you did

01:43:40.860 --> 01:43:45.420
[Guest]: that in the book. Yeah, the guy who was the chief secretary then 21 years ago is still

01:43:45.420 --> 01:43:49.500
[Guest]: in Modi's office guy called PK Mishra. Wow. So these are the same people he's worked with

01:43:49.500 --> 01:43:53.740
[Guest]: and is you know, a comfortable working with who are willing to do what it is that he requires

01:43:53.740 --> 01:44:00.460
[Guest]: them to do. And it appears based on his words that he does not like as you said, a complexity

01:44:00.460 --> 01:44:07.380
[Guest]: that the simplification of an issue down to its essential elements is sufficient for him

01:44:07.380 --> 01:44:13.500
[Guest]: to understand it at at like, whatever depth he feels is necessary. But to add to that

01:44:13.500 --> 01:44:19.140
[Guest]: he has the quality of based on that material deciding what it is that should be done next.

01:44:19.140 --> 01:44:25.180
[Guest]: And I think that a lot of the things that you might look at as unique things that he

01:44:25.180 --> 01:44:31.420
[Guest]: has brought into the system, on the side of the economy, on the side of foreign policy,

01:44:31.420 --> 01:44:37.260
[Guest]: on the side of national security can be seen as emanating from these two characteristics

01:44:37.260 --> 01:44:42.420
[Guest]: where the problem is simplified, and then that simplified problem is given a solution,

01:44:42.420 --> 01:44:46.340
[Guest]: which doesn't really work. It doesn't even work at the level of a household forget at

01:44:46.340 --> 01:44:54.260
[Guest]: the level of a nation, where things unfortunately, are so complex, that they can never be simplified.

01:44:54.260 --> 01:45:00.740
[Guest]: It's not possible that the what ifs are so many, that to calculate each of them would

01:45:00.740 --> 01:45:10.140
[Guest]: be to count the atoms of the universe that it but that is what certitude is, it says

01:45:10.140 --> 01:45:15.740
[Guest]: that there is a certain way of doing things, which will either break from the past or be

01:45:15.740 --> 01:45:20.220
[Guest]: done right by this person who means well, I think that's the one thing I think he's

01:45:20.220 --> 01:45:26.420
[Guest]: able to absorb his mistakes. Because I think he genuinely believes and maybe it is the

01:45:26.420 --> 01:45:33.260
[Guest]: case that he means well. So once once that is internalized, then it doesn't matter then

01:45:33.260 --> 01:45:40.500
[Guest]: then, then failure or what somebody else sees as failure is just fate. It's not for lack

01:45:40.500 --> 01:45:47.300
[Guest]: of the person's intent and lack of the person's honesty, you know, somebody who breaks down

01:45:47.300 --> 01:45:53.460
[Guest]: crying while speaking about himself will have such characteristics. And I think that it

01:45:53.460 --> 01:46:00.140
[Guest]: will be interesting if somebody once again looks at him. I'm not talking of a psychological

01:46:00.140 --> 01:46:06.420
[Guest]: profile, but I'm saying that somebody who with who understands human beings at large

01:46:06.420 --> 01:46:11.340
[Guest]: and how they behave, just like Ashish Nandy looked at him and said that these this is

01:46:11.340 --> 01:46:16.220
[Guest]: much before he became the chief minister, and was able to identify traits in him that

01:46:16.220 --> 01:46:24.780
[Guest]: have all come to be shown by a Modi and so are true. He shows them quite openly I think

01:46:24.780 --> 01:46:29.340
[Guest]: if if your listeners were to go back to that video, he's quite proud of the fact that he

01:46:29.340 --> 01:46:34.100
[Guest]: does he can't get the I can't do this through academics study that is what those are the

01:46:34.100 --> 01:46:40.580
[Guest]: words that he that he uses. And then he repeats himself I can't do that. He sort of emphasizes

01:46:40.580 --> 01:46:47.300
[Guest]: that that is not my way. My way is to like, like, you know, get get the gist of something

01:46:47.300 --> 01:46:55.260
[Guest]: and then throw the silver bullet at it. And one of the problems is that very complex problems

01:46:55.260 --> 01:47:01.820
[Guest]: require very big minds to be thrown at them. And when you have a very complex problem with

01:47:01.820 --> 01:47:07.380
[Guest]: somebody who refuses to approach it intellectually and has a cabal around him, which is willing

01:47:07.380 --> 01:47:13.540
[Guest]: to go the same person that spoken of in that interview sits in the PMO today, P.K. Mishra

01:47:13.540 --> 01:47:18.380
[Guest]: is bizarre, that nothing has been learned not only by Modi, but by those who feed him

01:47:18.380 --> 01:47:23.020
[Guest]: the stuff. There are technical problems with this, which I have also discussed, I think

01:47:23.020 --> 01:47:28.740
[Guest]: in this book, which is that you can only know what is fed to you. If you tell somebody summarize

01:47:28.740 --> 01:47:36.900
[Guest]: that book for me, I will only receive what that person chooses to summarize. Thirdly,

01:47:36.900 --> 01:47:41.020
[Guest]: because I'm very charismatic and very powerful, that person might not wish to displease me

01:47:41.020 --> 01:47:47.180
[Guest]: by saying something that might, you know, offend or sort of upset me, particularly if

01:47:47.180 --> 01:47:55.500
[Guest]: I have a gigantic ego. And so now you're looking at a now it's several problems that structurally

01:47:55.500 --> 01:48:00.940
[Guest]: Rathan Roy, who was on the Prime Minister's Economic Advisory Council, a group of only

01:48:00.940 --> 01:48:07.700
[Guest]: five people, says that people were angry with him for things that he said on television

01:48:07.700 --> 01:48:12.380
[Guest]: that had been sent to them in writing much before because they hadn't read it. Nobody

01:48:12.380 --> 01:48:17.420
[Guest]: read anything. But when you came on TV to say the same thing, they got upset because

01:48:17.420 --> 01:48:23.620
[Guest]: they felt, you know, this is not the way things are. So it's quite strange. I think we will

01:48:23.620 --> 01:48:31.780
[Guest]: never have it. But an insiders look into the PMO after 2014 would be both a fabulous book

01:48:31.780 --> 01:48:39.980
[Guest]: to write and a terrifying one to read. I think this the way that this places are in Gujarat,

01:48:39.980 --> 01:48:46.300
[Guest]: because we have a very strong union government, the damage that could be locally inflicted

01:48:46.300 --> 01:48:50.980
[Guest]: was minimal. And almost none of it through law, you can't do it, you can't make up laws

01:48:50.980 --> 01:48:56.940
[Guest]: like demonetization, or like GST, when you're sitting in Gandhi Nagar. So this part was

01:48:56.940 --> 01:49:03.580
[Guest]: hidden, actually, because he didn't have enough authority to be able to display his full prowess.

01:49:03.580 --> 01:49:09.780
[Guest]: But now, now that he's been given it not only in terms of the nature of the office, but

01:49:09.780 --> 01:49:16.940
[Guest]: also the number of seats that he's got, and the continual ability of this man to keep

01:49:16.940 --> 01:49:21.060
[Guest]: things focused on him means that this will not change.

01:49:21.060 --> 01:49:24.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I want to quote a couple of the lines of Ashish Nandy where he spoke about this

01:49:24.740 --> 01:49:29.060
[Amit Varma]: meeting and I for some reason the year 1988 keeps coming to my head. So I don't know if

01:49:29.060 --> 01:49:33.780
[Amit Varma]: I'm confusing it with something else or Nandy's interview was in 1988. But it was a long long

01:49:33.780 --> 01:49:39.360
[Amit Varma]: time before Modi rose to positions of power. And he wrote of Modi quote, he had the same

01:49:39.360 --> 01:49:44.760
[Amit Varma]: mix of puritanical rigidity, narrowing of emotional life, massive use of the ego defense

01:49:44.760 --> 01:49:49.820
[Amit Varma]: of projection, denial and fear of his own passions, combined with fantasies of violence,

01:49:49.820 --> 01:49:54.420
[Amit Varma]: all set within the matrix of clear paranoid and obsessive personality traits. I still

01:49:54.420 --> 01:49:59.140
[Amit Varma]: remember the cool measured tone in which he elaborated a theory of cosmic conspiracy against

01:49:59.140 --> 01:50:04.220
[Amit Varma]: India that painted every Muslim as a suspected traitor and a potential terrorist. I came

01:50:04.220 --> 01:50:07.700
[Amit Varma]: out of the interview shaken and told Yagnik, the person who went with him, that for the

01:50:07.700 --> 01:50:12.900
[Amit Varma]: first time, I had met a textbook case of a fascist, stop quote, and if it is 1988, it's

01:50:12.900 --> 01:50:19.660
[Guest]: like, quite, because this just sounds so familiar. I think it's just after the yatra was was

01:50:19.660 --> 01:50:23.820
[Guest]: organized. I could be wrong. But I think it's Yeah, I mean, I have that. He wrote about

01:50:23.820 --> 01:50:29.380
[Guest]: this in seminar in 2002. Just after the Yeah, he wrote. Yeah. You know, and it's interesting,

01:50:29.380 --> 01:50:33.420
[Amit Varma]: because what to us is a bug that here is a guy who doesn't read who's full of certainties

01:50:33.420 --> 01:50:37.620
[Amit Varma]: who doesn't have humility, then becomes a feature for the electorate. Because this is

01:50:37.620 --> 01:50:42.940
[Amit Varma]: the, for example, this is a result of his decisiveness, you know, that he has no self

01:50:42.940 --> 01:50:47.140
[Amit Varma]: doubt at all, he doesn't know enough to have self doubt and people want decisiveness. This

01:50:47.140 --> 01:50:51.900
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, his charisma comes from here. Because otherwise, you would expect people

01:50:51.900 --> 01:50:55.660
[Amit Varma]: to have humility, modesty to realize that they may be wrong, but he's like super league

01:50:55.660 --> 01:51:00.820
[Amit Varma]: confident and that kind of makes him charismatic. It's like, you know, he'd said the best lack

01:51:00.820 --> 01:51:04.860
[Amit Varma]: all conviction while the worst are full of passionate intensity. Think about it the you've

01:51:04.860 --> 01:51:11.020
[Guest]: got a bunch of very smart officers in the PMO, including the guy who's now the finance

01:51:11.020 --> 01:51:15.860
[Guest]: secretary, TV Somanathan, who are told by Modi one day that we are going to get rid

01:51:15.860 --> 01:51:23.780
[Guest]: of the currency and they are not only are they saying no to him, they are executing

01:51:23.780 --> 01:51:28.700
[Guest]: it with with whatever level of competence that they had. It's fascinating that you have

01:51:28.700 --> 01:51:34.760
[Guest]: such a person in office and he's popular for what he's done. It's also fascinating that

01:51:34.760 --> 01:51:40.080
[Guest]: really smart individuals responsible mature individuals who wouldn't do the sort of things

01:51:40.080 --> 01:51:49.060
[Guest]: that they do at home are willing to do them in office. And I don't know how many people

01:51:49.060 --> 01:51:55.140
[Guest]: know this, but this the man who came up with the demonetization scheme is this guy who's

01:51:55.140 --> 01:52:00.140
[Guest]: a diploma of engineer from Pune, who says that he went to Modi for 10 minutes, this

01:52:00.140 --> 01:52:05.660
[Guest]: is just before the 2014 polls. And then he's he spends more than an hour with him. And

01:52:05.660 --> 01:52:11.380
[Guest]: he said Modi was riveted by by what he said. And you've got these people with PhDs, you

01:52:11.380 --> 01:52:17.700
[Guest]: know, gone to Harvard and so on, who are standing around Modi, I doubt that they sit in his

01:52:17.700 --> 01:52:24.740
[Guest]: presence for carrying this out. It says something about us as a society that we don't have the

01:52:24.740 --> 01:52:28.980
[Guest]: ability, whether it's the Supreme Court, whether it's the High Court here, or whether it's

01:52:28.980 --> 01:52:35.300
[Guest]: the IAS, to be able to say no to this man, just we just go with what it is that he wants.

01:52:35.300 --> 01:52:39.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and actually demonetization is a classic example of the kind of folksy thinking that

01:52:39.500 --> 01:52:43.300
[Amit Varma]: he does, that, you know, the logic for him must have been that, hey, black money is kept

01:52:43.300 --> 01:52:47.700
[Guest]: in these big notes. So let's make sure he makes it very clear why it is that he's doing

01:52:47.700 --> 01:52:50.820
[Guest]: this, that it's going to get rid of corruption, it's going to get rid of black money is going

01:52:50.820 --> 01:52:55.620
[Amit Varma]: to get rid of terrorism. Yeah. And it also shows his disconnect with the real world.

01:52:55.620 --> 01:52:59.660
[Amit Varma]: Because had he actually, you know, he wouldn't have visited a panwala in 20 years. So he

01:52:59.660 --> 01:53:03.540
[Amit Varma]: wouldn't have known that these are really not high value notes, a medium of exchange,

01:53:03.540 --> 01:53:08.260
[Guest]: not storage. But then that goes back to your friend and what she or he said about the experiential

01:53:08.260 --> 01:53:14.980
[Amit Varma]: mind, right? Yeah. No, and just thinking back to a very interesting point that you made,

01:53:14.980 --> 01:53:19.300
[Amit Varma]: that you have all these intelligent people who are IAS officers and economists and they've

01:53:19.300 --> 01:53:23.420
[Amit Varma]: been to Harvard, Stanford, why are they not saying anything? And I think that this would

01:53:23.420 --> 01:53:27.540
[Amit Varma]: create a kind of negative feedback loop, which would make Modi even stupider than he is.

01:53:27.540 --> 01:53:33.260
[Guest]: Vivek Debroy said on television to Karan Thapar that demonetization would have no effect on

01:53:33.260 --> 01:53:40.780
[Amit Varma]: GDP growth. Which he must have absolutely 100% known is a blatant lie. It's like, you

01:53:40.780 --> 01:53:45.780
[Amit Varma]: know, no, I wrote a piece at that time talking about, you know, the useful idiots, a phrase

01:53:45.780 --> 01:53:50.660
[Amit Varma]: used by Lenin, you know, so the useful idiots, not in a literal way, but Lenin used it for

01:53:50.660 --> 01:53:55.820
[Amit Varma]: the so called intellectuals, who will then align with an authoritarian and they're useful

01:53:55.820 --> 01:54:01.620
[Amit Varma]: idiots, right? Therefore, and what I had written then was that any economist who supports demonetization

01:54:01.620 --> 01:54:06.500
[Guest]: is either a bad economist or a bad human being. You know, I think you have it there. It's

01:54:06.500 --> 01:54:12.860
[Guest]: the bad human beingness. Panagaria will one day say that the government's doing absolutely

01:54:12.860 --> 01:54:18.220
[Guest]: the wrong things. And the next day praise Modi for doing what he has on the economy.

01:54:18.220 --> 01:54:23.380
[Guest]: And I think that the consistent part of those two days, is the fact that what Modi does

01:54:23.380 --> 01:54:29.340
[Guest]: outside of the economy, Panagaria absolutely agrees with. So his love for the man doesn't

01:54:29.340 --> 01:54:31.780
[Guest]: come out of the mischief that is being played on.

01:54:31.780 --> 01:54:34.860
[Amit Varma]: He may not even agree with anything. He wants to be close to power.

01:54:34.860 --> 01:54:43.660
[Guest]: He left power. He left eventually. If you're a classical economist, and you've got where

01:54:43.660 --> 01:54:48.740
[Guest]: the sort of Holy Grail is the free trade, and you and you're running away, if not only

01:54:48.740 --> 01:54:51.860
[Guest]: are you running away from it, you're raising tariffs and so on, you're doing exactly the

01:54:51.860 --> 01:54:58.420
[Guest]: opposite of it. At some point, maybe his economist self said that, that that wants to wave you

01:54:58.420 --> 01:55:04.100
[Guest]: know, goodbye to the sort of more primitive, bigoted self that that adores what what else

01:55:04.100 --> 01:55:05.100
[Amit Varma]: was going on.

01:55:05.100 --> 01:55:08.020
[Amit Varma]: There's something larger here that bothers me a lot. And this is something I've seen

01:55:08.020 --> 01:55:13.100
[Amit Varma]: in recent years with even a small set of people who supported Modi, and a large set of people

01:55:13.100 --> 01:55:18.180
[Amit Varma]: who supported Trump, for example, Trump went against every value of the Republican Party,

01:55:18.180 --> 01:55:23.860
[Amit Varma]: in terms of being anti trade and all of that, just a whole bunch of whatever. And it leads

01:55:23.860 --> 01:55:28.660
[Amit Varma]: me to think about how many of us who claim to be principled, who posture of ourselves

01:55:28.660 --> 01:55:33.700
[Amit Varma]: as principled people, actually, it's a posturing, it's a tribe we are part of, and those principles

01:55:33.700 --> 01:55:37.380
[Amit Varma]: are part of the uniform we wear. But when push comes to shove, we don't really give

01:55:37.380 --> 01:55:38.380
[Amit Varma]: a shit about the principles.

01:55:38.380 --> 01:55:45.740
[Guest]: Does that also hold for me in my area of expertise, my domain knowledge, I've spent 60 years studying

01:55:45.740 --> 01:55:54.100
[Guest]: this stuff. And I think I know a set of is is this, can I be motivated sufficiently to

01:55:54.100 --> 01:55:59.780
[Guest]: violate every single principle that I believe to be true and good in that one part of the

01:55:59.780 --> 01:56:04.340
[Guest]: world that I know really well? And the answer seems to be yes, that I'm willing to go along

01:56:04.340 --> 01:56:06.740
[Guest]: with whatever, so long as

01:56:06.740 --> 01:56:11.100
[Amit Varma]: some people are some people aren't like speaking of you, I'm sure you never would, right. And,

01:56:11.100 --> 01:56:15.180
[Amit Varma]: you know, I've criticized every government has been there. And it's on the basis of principle.

01:56:15.180 --> 01:56:18.860
[Amit Varma]: So but you know, there's like Panagari has blocked me on Twitter, actually, because I

01:56:18.860 --> 01:56:23.660
[Amit Varma]: just kept ranting about him. And just this morning, somebody asked me, would I ever have

01:56:23.660 --> 01:56:28.620
[Guest]: Vivek Debra on my show? And, and I just feel so strongly about demonetization.

01:56:28.620 --> 01:56:31.220
[Guest]: On the media, he doesn't he doesn't appear anymore.

01:56:31.220 --> 01:56:35.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, he should be a little embarrassed of the last few years, I guess.

01:56:35.620 --> 01:56:39.580
[Guest]: I don't think he is, because he is sort of accessible on Twitter. So you can go and say,

01:56:39.580 --> 01:56:42.620
[Guest]: you know, whatever it is that you want to him, and he's fine with that.

01:56:42.620 --> 01:56:45.300
[Guest]: I have no desire to do that. But yeah,

01:56:45.300 --> 01:56:50.460
[Guest]: not just you, I'm saying that he's he's opening himself up to abuse, what he doesn't want

01:56:50.460 --> 01:56:55.180
[Guest]: is to be questioned on what the government has done. And he's free not to not to reply

01:56:55.180 --> 01:56:57.020
[Guest]: on Twitter. So he's got both things.

01:56:57.020 --> 01:57:01.060
[Amit Varma]: No, and he's written lovely books, you know, and Panagari, if you look at his economics

01:57:01.060 --> 01:57:06.340
[Amit Varma]: work before all of this, there's some fine work in there. So at some level, it's a human

01:57:06.340 --> 01:57:11.860
[Amit Varma]: tragedy for me, to kind of see people debase and degrade themselves in the manner that

01:57:11.860 --> 01:57:14.620
[Amit Varma]: these people have perhaps Vivek more than Mr. Panagari.

01:57:14.620 --> 01:57:20.020
[Guest]: Yeah. And also the the idea that there was a set of people who believe in conservatism,

01:57:20.020 --> 01:57:23.220
[Guest]: I don't know what is what the right means when it calls itself the right if it calls

01:57:23.220 --> 01:57:29.340
[Guest]: itself the right. But there is no conservatism. This man is a radical, he's trying to undo

01:57:29.340 --> 01:57:37.620
[Guest]: the system violently, through strokes on the economy on foreign policy on national security.

01:57:37.620 --> 01:57:43.020
[Guest]: This is exactly the opposite of what conservative right wing people do. And I think the parallel

01:57:43.020 --> 01:57:47.980
[Guest]: with Trump is absolutely right that they discarded the principles at the door, the moment he

01:57:47.980 --> 01:57:51.700
[Guest]: went into the White House. Everybody who worked with him, I don't think there was any kind

01:57:51.700 --> 01:57:57.160
[Guest]: of republican sense of like focus on the things that the party had focused on and what had

01:57:57.160 --> 01:57:58.160
[Guest]: made the party.

01:57:58.160 --> 01:58:02.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's sad. And I got to thinking about this, where you mentioned that how no one

01:58:02.740 --> 01:58:06.500
[Amit Varma]: kind of questions and I think there might be a negative feedback loop in loop in play

01:58:06.500 --> 01:58:11.260
[Amit Varma]: there. That once people realize that he wants yes men, or who will give him simplistic narratives

01:58:11.260 --> 01:58:15.260
[Amit Varma]: that he agrees with, they only keep doing that. Absolutely. Only people like that survive

01:58:15.260 --> 01:58:16.260
[Amit Varma]: with him.

01:58:16.260 --> 01:58:17.300
[Amit Varma]: You've probably nailed it.

01:58:17.300 --> 01:58:22.260
[Amit Varma]: And because that is the only feedback that he's getting, it diminishes even him. Because

01:58:22.260 --> 01:58:23.500
[Amit Varma]: that's the only thing he's hearing.

01:58:23.500 --> 01:58:29.980
[Guest]: The difference between Amitabh Kant and Vivek Debroy and of course, P.K. Mishra and Apana

01:58:29.980 --> 01:58:35.660
[Guest]: Garia who at some point would have drawn the line and said, you know, no to this and, and

01:58:35.660 --> 01:58:36.660
[Amit Varma]: moved on.

01:58:36.660 --> 01:58:40.860
[Amit Varma]: The next point I want to make up is, is that you spoke about how he may have the best intentions

01:58:40.860 --> 01:58:44.840
[Amit Varma]: and it's quite possible he may and even he himself, I think after Demon at some point

01:58:44.840 --> 01:58:50.180
[Amit Varma]: he says meri niyat to achi thi. You know, and, and I think of this and it strikes me

01:58:50.180 --> 01:58:56.160
[Amit Varma]: that actually, this doesn't matter at all. I think what we need, what we need is a system

01:58:56.160 --> 01:59:00.940
[Amit Varma]: within which even if the worst human being on the planet became Prime Minister, the worst

01:59:00.940 --> 01:59:06.180
[Amit Varma]: most sociopathic evil person you can think of, they, all their incentives would push

01:59:06.180 --> 01:59:09.500
[Amit Varma]: them towards doing the right things and they wouldn't be able to do much damage.

01:59:09.500 --> 01:59:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And today we have a system which is exactly the opposite, that you know, which is so incredibly

01:59:14.780 --> 01:59:19.300
[Amit Varma]: oppressive that it attracts that kind of person and you're inevitably going to get bad behavior

01:59:19.300 --> 01:59:21.060
[Guest]: and etc.

01:59:21.060 --> 01:59:25.180
[Guest]: I think structurally states try to do this through the checks and balances and the sort

01:59:25.180 --> 01:59:29.140
[Guest]: of division of power. It doesn't work in some parts of the world. I don't think it's working

01:59:29.140 --> 01:59:36.360
[Guest]: here where the in, in many ways, our division is less stronger than that in the US because

01:59:36.360 --> 01:59:41.420
[Guest]: you've got the legislatures merged with the executive more or less. But the judiciary,

01:59:41.420 --> 01:59:47.020
[Guest]: I think it's difficult for strong and charismatic leaders to keep them out of out of either

01:59:47.020 --> 01:59:52.700
[Guest]: meddling with the judges or making sure that they bend to his will. And I think that it's

01:59:52.700 --> 01:59:58.540
[Guest]: there is a systemic problem here, which is which goes beyond him, that if you have people

01:59:58.540 --> 02:00:04.900
[Guest]: like PK Mishra and the rest, who are willing to do this, not just for 22 years, for 20

02:00:04.900 --> 02:00:09.700
[Guest]: years, it means that it's not just the person who's doing the damage. Speaking to intent,

02:00:09.700 --> 02:00:14.740
[Guest]: I think it doesn't exist, right? What is it? I mean, you can't, it doesn't mean anything.

02:00:14.740 --> 02:00:20.140
[Guest]: And it means something only to the person who actually expresses it. He believes he's

02:00:20.140 --> 02:00:24.860
[Guest]: doing it in good intent. But I'm saying that the the follow up to that is if if that is

02:00:24.860 --> 02:00:28.380
[Guest]: the case, you have to learn from the thing that you did in the past. If you continue

02:00:28.380 --> 02:00:31.980
[Guest]: that good intent into your next project, you should bring the learnings of the past he

02:00:31.980 --> 02:00:36.180
[Guest]: doesn't, it's still going to be locked down at four hours notice, it's still going to

02:00:36.180 --> 02:00:39.460
[Guest]: be trauma for millions and still going to be moving on from there saying I did a very

02:00:39.460 --> 02:00:42.500
[Guest]: good job. That is not a good intent.

02:00:42.500 --> 02:00:45.980
[Amit Varma]: And more than that, I think the lesson from something like demonetization, that you can

02:00:45.980 --> 02:00:49.660
[Amit Varma]: take out if you realize it's a mistake, is not that don't demonetize again, that's not

02:00:49.660 --> 02:00:53.660
[Amit Varma]: the lesson. The lesson is have humility, talk to experts, take your time, you know, all

02:00:53.660 --> 02:00:54.660
[Guest]: of that.

02:00:54.660 --> 02:00:57.780
[Guest]: The world is complex, it's not simple. I think that that is the lesson, but that is not going

02:00:57.780 --> 02:01:02.260
[Guest]: to be learned. Because the style is the same when he's sworn in in 2019. There are newspaper

02:01:02.260 --> 02:01:07.060
[Guest]: reports that says that he's clubbed ministries into three groups, each of which has 10 minutes

02:01:07.060 --> 02:01:12.740
[Guest]: to give him a sort of, you know, a presentation. And you've got a fertilizer sitting with railways

02:01:12.740 --> 02:01:18.340
[Guest]: and you know, a foreign and they all have, you know, 10 minutes to put their slides up.

02:01:18.340 --> 02:01:25.060
[Guest]: So no lesson was learned, not only in the period in in Gujarat, but after demonetization

02:01:25.060 --> 02:01:30.860
[Guest]: in the five years full for first five full years of his first term, don't know if the

02:01:30.860 --> 02:01:37.180
[Guest]: word is done here. His first five years in office as a PM, nothing is learned, the style

02:01:37.180 --> 02:01:41.300
[Guest]: is still the same. Everything is the same is the same people as well.

02:01:41.300 --> 02:01:46.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and we mentioned useful idiots. I'm just reminded at your recent Twitter outburst

02:01:46.500 --> 02:01:52.060
[Amit Varma]: against Mr. Jay Shankar. So on a sideline, this I love this Twitter voice that you've

02:01:52.060 --> 02:01:56.100
[Amit Varma]: kind of adopted, you know, how did it kind of come about? Because it seems to be to be

02:01:56.100 --> 02:02:01.760
[Amit Varma]: almost an art form on its own. This kind of masterful parodying and it's perfect for Twitter.

02:02:01.760 --> 02:02:04.820
[Amit Varma]: Because if you did a longer thing with this, it wouldn't work, it would be too much work.

02:02:04.820 --> 02:02:10.100
[Guest]: Some people say book, it doesn't work as a book. So I think we have this wonderful nation

02:02:10.100 --> 02:02:16.100
[Guest]: and a wonderful culture where we are half bilingual in two languages, many of us would

02:02:16.100 --> 02:02:20.940
[Guest]: neither read and speak or write one language properly, the one that we were born into,

02:02:20.940 --> 02:02:26.140
[Guest]: or the one that we learned at school. And we tend to mispronounce words, we tend to

02:02:26.140 --> 02:02:32.140
[Guest]: use grammar and syntax in a particular way. I like that. And so I sort of enjoy that thing.

02:02:32.140 --> 02:02:38.900
[Guest]: It's I don't look down on it in many way. But the fact is that a lot of us recognize

02:02:38.900 --> 02:02:43.900
[Guest]: it, this would make no sense to anybody in say, New Zealand or another, you know, Anglophone

02:02:43.900 --> 02:02:49.980
[Guest]: nation, because this is us, this is the way that we that you know, Punjabis and Tamilians

02:02:49.980 --> 02:02:55.300
[Guest]: speak the language and write it. So yeah, so I use it mostly to entertain myself. How

02:02:55.300 --> 02:03:01.620
[Guest]: did it come to be? I don't know. I think my, my most happy years in journalism were a were

02:03:01.620 --> 02:03:07.700
[Guest]: in a tabloid, either while I was working in the tabloid or when I was writing for it.

02:03:07.700 --> 02:03:13.780
[Guest]: And I think that lowbrow humour, which is the only real humour to my mind, appeals to

02:03:13.780 --> 02:03:19.660
[Guest]: me a lot. I like stuff that is considered stupid, or that you know, some people might

02:03:19.660 --> 02:03:28.020
[Guest]: actually consider silly. Yeah, no. And so that's, that's how, that's how I do it. I,

02:03:28.020 --> 02:03:33.180
[Guest]: it can't be made into a book, there is no scope, there's no depth. It's a moment, basically.

02:03:33.180 --> 02:03:35.980
[Guest]: And I think for that reason, I think it works on Twitter.

02:03:35.980 --> 02:03:41.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's brilliant. And to me, it's lowbrow at the same time, I would say it's high art.

02:03:41.540 --> 02:03:45.580
[Amit Varma]: I just kind of love it. One of the literally, you know, I'm not trying to flatter you. But

02:03:45.580 --> 02:03:50.340
[Amit Varma]: one of the things I've most enjoyed over Twitter in the last 12 years, that I've kind of been

02:03:50.340 --> 02:03:57.060
[Guest]: I knew that it would be a complete addiction for me. I didn't venture into it till I left

02:03:57.060 --> 02:04:01.780
[Guest]: my till my term at Amnesty was over, I didn't touch it. There was a handle in my name, but

02:04:01.780 --> 02:04:06.980
[Guest]: it was being operated by somebody in the office. So the December Shaheen Bagh, when that happened,

02:04:06.980 --> 02:04:13.260
[Guest]: my term ended on the last day of November. And in 15 days time, the world had changed,

02:04:13.260 --> 02:04:18.940
[Guest]: right? You had like, mass protests for the first time on this issue. And that has remained

02:04:18.940 --> 02:04:25.180
[Guest]: for two and a half years, thank God. And I knew that and the reason I didn't come on

02:04:25.180 --> 02:04:31.420
[Guest]: social media was I knew that such great technology. It's such a fabulous tool, that you can't

02:04:31.420 --> 02:04:36.900
[Guest]: stay away from it. And I'm glad I stayed away from it. And I'm glad I'm now completely,

02:04:36.900 --> 02:04:43.580
[Guest]: you know, immersed in it. It's a, it's a tool, I think that it gives, it gives us a dog in

02:04:43.580 --> 02:04:47.140
[Guest]: the fight, like with what has happened to mainstream media, and maybe we can speak about

02:04:47.140 --> 02:04:53.020
[Guest]: that. Structurally, it has taken itself out of the space that it was, and it's not going

02:04:53.020 --> 02:05:01.060
[Guest]: to return anytime soon. If it can in many sort of places like a print, it never will.

02:05:01.060 --> 02:05:05.100
[Guest]: So what do you do then I'm saying that you need to have some place where you put however

02:05:05.100 --> 02:05:09.180
[Guest]: small the reach may be, there has to be some space for us to be able to express ourselves.

02:05:09.180 --> 02:05:16.380
[Guest]: And I think that for many countries, including us, the social media in a time of authoritarian

02:05:16.380 --> 02:05:21.660
[Guest]: government has been the single one release more than sort of opposition politics or the

02:05:21.660 --> 02:05:25.980
[Guest]: judiciary, which has given us a voice to look at the number of Muslims who are active on

02:05:25.980 --> 02:05:34.660
[Guest]: Twitter in India, talking about things that matter to us. It's fantastic. It's also disproportionate.

02:05:34.660 --> 02:05:40.860
[Guest]: It does, it shows many things about our country in data terms, which might not be visible,

02:05:40.860 --> 02:05:46.620
[Guest]: or might be hidden by the kind of appraisal lavish on our constitution and what kind of

02:05:46.620 --> 02:05:53.980
[Guest]: nation we are. The reality comes out fairly, fairly vividly on social media.

02:05:53.980 --> 02:05:57.900
[Amit Varma]: There's a thread or link which I saw on Twitter recently, which just made me very sad. It's

02:05:57.900 --> 02:06:01.740
[Amit Varma]: like heartbreaking. You must have seen it. I think Joy Das put out a thread.

02:06:01.740 --> 02:06:06.140
[Guest]: I did see it. Him asking Muslims, when were you first told to go to Pakistan or something

02:06:06.140 --> 02:06:07.140
[Amit Varma]: like that?

02:06:07.140 --> 02:06:12.100
[Guest]: And it's a long, long thread. You just scroll forever. You just scroll forever and forever

02:06:12.100 --> 02:06:16.380
[Amit Varma]: and forever. And there is story after story after story. Let's talk about the media because

02:06:16.380 --> 02:06:21.020
[Amit Varma]: that's in any case what I was coming to next. And it strikes me that it's like journalism

02:06:21.020 --> 02:06:25.580
[Amit Varma]: is splintered and gone in two directions. And one direction is you become Godi Media

02:06:25.580 --> 02:06:29.140
[Amit Varma]: and you have a whole chapter on that. And we'll discuss the reasons for that. And the

02:06:29.140 --> 02:06:35.140
[Amit Varma]: other direction is that you have a handful of folks who are still fighting the good fight.

02:06:35.140 --> 02:06:39.180
[Amit Varma]: You know, people like News Minute and Wire and Scroll and all of that, who are still

02:06:39.180 --> 02:06:44.940
[Amit Varma]: trying to kind of put up a front and news laundry. And the question here is that we

02:06:44.940 --> 02:06:51.540
[Amit Varma]: seem to have reached a stage where good journalism almost has to be a crusade, where it is only

02:06:51.540 --> 02:06:55.980
[Amit Varma]: people with that crusader spirit who can still do the good journalism. You know, I would

02:06:55.980 --> 02:07:01.740
[Amit Varma]: have imagined that in an ideal world, in an ideal state of equilibrium, there is an understanding

02:07:01.740 --> 02:07:05.620
[Amit Varma]: of what journalism is, where people are, you know, they're reporting the first draft of

02:07:05.620 --> 02:07:09.820
[Amit Varma]: history, they're reporting local news, they're doing the entertainment things, and they're

02:07:09.820 --> 02:07:14.540
[Amit Varma]: speaking truth to power and all of these things are happening. But we've reached a stage where

02:07:14.540 --> 02:07:20.900
[Amit Varma]: you either have the so called Godi Media, where you're just propelling one particular

02:07:20.900 --> 02:07:25.400
[Amit Varma]: narrative being, you know, one of the front lines in the narrative wars that are out there.

02:07:25.400 --> 02:07:30.300
[Amit Varma]: And then you have a bunch of people who are kind of holding firm on the other side. And

02:07:30.300 --> 02:07:34.180
[Amit Varma]: it makes me sad because I don't think that to be a good journalist, you should have to

02:07:34.180 --> 02:07:40.420
[Amit Varma]: be a good crusader. However, you know, in modern times, it seems that like, to me, journalism

02:07:40.420 --> 02:07:44.660
[Amit Varma]: and activism should not go together, they simply should not. But it seems that it's

02:07:44.660 --> 02:07:46.340
[Guest]: being forced in that direction.

02:07:46.340 --> 02:07:52.980
[Guest]: I think structurally, what has happened is that like, when when you and I worked in newsrooms,

02:07:52.980 --> 02:08:00.660
[Guest]: you would the material would transition from being collected, reportage, edited, and then

02:08:00.660 --> 02:08:06.300
[Guest]: opined upon that's the last stage, very few people do that, right. But that is a natural

02:08:06.300 --> 02:08:09.580
[Guest]: transition. And that is what we do that is that is that is how that's what journalists

02:08:09.580 --> 02:08:15.420
[Guest]: do. And this is legitimate. And this is the way that the newsroom is structured. What

02:08:15.420 --> 02:08:25.900
[Guest]: happens when the evidence is in when the evidence is in, if it leads to opinion, where there

02:08:25.900 --> 02:08:31.140
[Guest]: is no difference being made, I think activism comes after to the right of that. So you've

02:08:31.140 --> 02:08:36.980
[Guest]: got reportage, you've got the editing, you've got the opinion. Then after that, what if

02:08:36.980 --> 02:08:43.780
[Guest]: I have the data with me, if I have the information, if the violation is manifest, it's in front

02:08:43.780 --> 02:08:49.820
[Guest]: of my eyes, then what do I do? Do I continue doing steps one, two and three? Or is there

02:08:49.820 --> 02:08:56.780
[Guest]: a legitimate fourth step for me? Our discomfort lies in the fact that in our classical newsrooms,

02:08:56.780 --> 02:09:01.740
[Guest]: this fourth step doesn't really exist. In many newsrooms it did, it did in a different

02:09:01.740 --> 02:09:06.620
[Guest]: form. So in Deccan Chronicle, which I worked for a long time ago, the editor would regularly

02:09:06.620 --> 02:09:11.220
[Guest]: file PILs. So once the once something was known and on issues maybe as mundane as you

02:09:11.220 --> 02:09:16.460
[Guest]: know, power or something like that, I don't know. But often the paper would be a litigant.

02:09:16.460 --> 02:09:21.500
[Guest]: So that is that is actually activism, but it was rare. Does it seem unnatural that a

02:09:21.500 --> 02:09:26.300
[Guest]: paper should do that? Looking at it from here, I would say no, that because the paper seems

02:09:26.300 --> 02:09:32.500
[Guest]: to believe that it's a community of readers, right that ended. So I don't think we should

02:09:32.500 --> 02:09:37.980
[Guest]: be as uncomfortable with it as we are. I'm not because I've, you know, transitioned into

02:09:37.980 --> 02:09:44.300
[Guest]: activism full time, and I no longer see myself as a journalist. But I would urge journalists

02:09:44.300 --> 02:09:49.260
[Guest]: to look at our classical structure and the movement of material within the newsroom and

02:09:49.260 --> 02:09:53.540
[Guest]: ask ourselves whether it is legitimate to have that fourth step. I would say yes, for

02:09:53.540 --> 02:09:59.080
[Guest]: sure that it is there is no running away from the fact that once you've got the evidence,

02:09:59.080 --> 02:10:05.580
[Guest]: and you've put out the opinion, and there is no shift, it is fine for me to act to try

02:10:05.580 --> 02:10:10.180
[Amit Varma]: and bring about that shift. And, you know, one of the things that you've remarked upon,

02:10:10.180 --> 02:10:15.340
[Amit Varma]: and which has been a very sad case for so long, is that when it comes to influencing

02:10:15.340 --> 02:10:19.660
[Amit Varma]: media, the government has a very powerful stick, you forget that. And the very powerful

02:10:19.660 --> 02:10:24.460
[Amit Varma]: stick is government advertising that so many media houses and newspapers and magazines

02:10:24.460 --> 02:10:30.380
[Amit Varma]: depend upon government advertising for survival. And this is to me is something that I feel

02:10:30.380 --> 02:10:36.540
[Amit Varma]: is incredibly sad, because it raises the question that if journalism is valuable, like, I'm

02:10:36.540 --> 02:10:41.060
[Amit Varma]: kind of idealistic in the sense that I believe that if there is anything of value, it should

02:10:41.060 --> 02:10:46.540
[Amit Varma]: be a it should be possible to make a profit from it. Right. So even this podcast, I don't

02:10:46.540 --> 02:10:50.660
[Amit Varma]: think of it in, you know, NGO terms that someone needs to support it. I'm like, No, if I'm

02:10:50.660 --> 02:10:54.700
[Amit Varma]: doing something of value, I'll figure out a way that I make money from it, and I survive

02:10:54.700 --> 02:10:59.740
[Amit Varma]: through it. And therefore, I think that if journalism is valuable, and I believe it is,

02:10:59.740 --> 02:11:06.140
[Amit Varma]: then there has to be a way for it to also be profitable. So you can, you know, so at

02:11:06.140 --> 02:11:11.780
[Amit Varma]: least on this one front, that government advertising, you can just tell the government to get lost,

02:11:11.780 --> 02:11:16.980
[Amit Varma]: and you can kind of survive. And therefore, I think that not enough thought has, like

02:11:16.980 --> 02:11:21.300
[Amit Varma]: either it is not possible, which would be either journalism so far is not valued by

02:11:21.300 --> 02:11:27.020
[Amit Varma]: enough people, which to me would seem very sad, or we have sort of been lax in figuring

02:11:27.020 --> 02:11:32.500
[Amit Varma]: out ways to monetize the value that we are providing for the people. Now, I know people

02:11:32.500 --> 02:11:37.300
[Amit Varma]: like you know, News Laundry is experimenting with subscriber models, you know, the wire

02:11:37.300 --> 02:11:41.380
[Amit Varma]: invites contributions, I think scroll does that also. So all those things are there and

02:11:41.380 --> 02:11:47.780
[Amit Varma]: they're nascent experiments. But at a larger level, it just feels to me that somewhere,

02:11:47.780 --> 02:11:51.620
[Amit Varma]: there was an ecosystem that didn't build up properly, because the point of the matter

02:11:51.620 --> 02:11:56.020
[Amit Varma]: is people spend people back in the day would spend a lot of time reading a newspaper time

02:11:56.020 --> 02:12:00.300
[Amit Varma]: is money. That means you're already paying to read the newspaper. Why is there not a

02:12:00.300 --> 02:12:03.860
[Amit Varma]: way for the newspaper to then capture some of that?

02:12:03.860 --> 02:12:12.420
[Guest]: So I think structurally, the one of the shifts that happened over the last 20 years is that

02:12:12.420 --> 02:12:20.900
[Guest]: because of the idea of sort of India shining and India being the next China, a lot of money

02:12:20.900 --> 02:12:27.100
[Guest]: went into setting up new media, particularly TV channels. So listeners might or might not

02:12:27.100 --> 02:12:32.780
[Guest]: know that there are a handful, I think, five or six, 24 seven news channels in the US,

02:12:32.780 --> 02:12:38.500
[Guest]: which are supported mostly through cable subscriptions. There are more than 100 news channels in India,

02:12:38.500 --> 02:12:44.020
[Guest]: where not only do you not get a cable subscription, the channel needs to pay a carriage fee to

02:12:44.020 --> 02:12:50.420
[Guest]: Tata Sky or to the cable operator. What happens in that situation is two things. One is you've

02:12:50.420 --> 02:12:57.300
[Guest]: got a system where it's not easy to kill a business. You can survive by not paying employees

02:12:57.300 --> 02:13:00.940
[Guest]: or paying them half their salaries or delaying their salaries in a way that you couldn't

02:13:00.940 --> 02:13:04.780
[Guest]: do in a more civilized nation where the rule of law would say that if you don't pay, you

02:13:04.780 --> 02:13:09.580
[Guest]: go to court and then you're shut down and you go bankrupt. The other is the dependency

02:13:09.580 --> 02:13:14.040
[Guest]: on advertising, which has caused once again, two shifts. One is that the union government

02:13:14.040 --> 02:13:21.620
[Guest]: gives out between itself and PSUs 2,400 crore rupees a year to what is called the DAVP,

02:13:21.620 --> 02:13:27.380
[Guest]: a direct rate of audiovisual publicity, which as you say, is a discretionary money. And

02:13:27.380 --> 02:13:30.900
[Guest]: you might think of it as a carrot, but you're right, it's actually a stick. That if you

02:13:30.900 --> 02:13:34.580
[Guest]: don't do the line and you know what the line is, then you don't get that money. And that

02:13:34.580 --> 02:13:39.100
[Guest]: happens all the time, including with the largest newspapers of states, including Rajasthan

02:13:39.100 --> 02:13:44.100
[Guest]: Batrika, which had to go to court against the Sindhia government, or it all happened

02:13:44.100 --> 02:13:51.060
[Guest]: with Denik Bhaskar, as like happened after the photographs and the reportage on the corpses

02:13:51.060 --> 02:13:57.860
[Guest]: in the Ganga. So, structurally speaking, we have too many, too much media, which can't

02:13:57.860 --> 02:14:03.540
[Guest]: be sustained by the size of the market we have. One problem is obviously the old one,

02:14:03.540 --> 02:14:10.820
[Guest]: which is that the rates, the newspaper costs much less than it takes to produce. And so,

02:14:10.820 --> 02:14:16.860
[Guest]: it is subsidized by the advertiser. But to a very large extent, the problem has been

02:14:16.860 --> 02:14:23.300
[Guest]: that advertising has also been squeezed because of the problems with the economy. And the

02:14:23.300 --> 02:14:28.220
[Guest]: fact that the government of India is very, very powerful, not just with the stick of

02:14:28.220 --> 02:14:32.620
[Guest]: advertising, but also with the stick of regulation. It has switched off this TV channel, the only

02:14:32.620 --> 02:14:40.540
[Guest]: one owned by Muslims in India, called MediaOne. It has denied a license to probably the best

02:14:40.540 --> 02:14:46.380
[Guest]: known journalist around the world, who is from India, Raghav Bail, didn't get a license.

02:14:46.380 --> 02:14:52.500
[Guest]: So, you've got a government that's enthusiastic and willing to exercise the agency that it

02:14:52.500 --> 02:14:57.300
[Guest]: has. And so, we will have this problem. And will it go away soon? I don't think so. I

02:14:57.300 --> 02:15:03.940
[Guest]: think that unless a lot of media dies, and a lot of media deserves to die, we are going

02:15:03.940 --> 02:15:10.060
[Guest]: to have channels that are dependent on the government, both for regulatory sticks and

02:15:10.060 --> 02:15:17.060
[Guest]: for the advertising carrot strokes a stick. And we will have a small number of not mass

02:15:17.060 --> 02:15:22.780
[Guest]: reach outfits, such as the ones you named, which will be doing the journalism at the

02:15:22.780 --> 02:15:29.580
[Guest]: other end. The problem is reportage. That my last job in a newspaper, which was some

02:15:29.580 --> 02:15:36.060
[Guest]: time ago, was in a language newspaper, which had 300 reporters just in one state. And these

02:15:36.060 --> 02:15:40.780
[Guest]: reporters had beats. So, for listeners who don't really know what journalism is like

02:15:40.780 --> 02:15:46.740
[Guest]: most journalists on reporting are reporters and they go, they do the same thing over and

02:15:46.740 --> 02:15:50.340
[Guest]: over again every day. When I was a Sessions Court reporter, I went to Sessions Court number

02:15:50.340 --> 02:15:56.380
[Guest]: one, went up to number 42, then went back to one, went up to 42, and then went back

02:15:56.380 --> 02:16:02.460
[Guest]: to the office. So, I knew what was going on there. Those who do civic, which is the corporation

02:16:02.460 --> 02:16:05.660
[Guest]: beat, will know what's going on there, will know whether there are teachers in a school

02:16:05.660 --> 02:16:10.900
[Guest]: or not. That's not what TV journalism does. That's not what these websites that you mentioned

02:16:10.900 --> 02:16:15.300
[Guest]: can do, they don't have the resource. They can do some stories, they can do reportage.

02:16:15.300 --> 02:16:18.820
[Guest]: Reportage can only be done by newspapers, because that's the only material that is not

02:16:18.820 --> 02:16:24.660
[Guest]: dependent on visual narrative. You can't do court stories on a TV channel, even if you

02:16:24.660 --> 02:16:31.220
[Guest]: wanted to. And it deploys large numbers of people to get actual news out. Newspapers

02:16:31.220 --> 02:16:38.020
[Guest]: are dying. So, the latest data shows that 2021, 2020, obviously was less, the share

02:16:38.020 --> 02:16:43.540
[Guest]: of revenue was less than it was in 2019. But the same has remained the case in 2022. That

02:16:43.540 --> 02:16:49.420
[Guest]: in a year when we are speaking of a 9% GDP growth rate, newspapers will have exactly

02:16:49.420 --> 02:16:54.660
[Guest]: the same sum of money that they had five years ago. That's why newspapers are shutting down.

02:16:54.660 --> 02:16:59.980
[Guest]: That's why the Mumbai Mirror does not really exist. Though it had a very large reach, it

02:16:59.980 --> 02:17:05.380
[Guest]: could not attract enough advertising to keep it in the black. Not just that, many, many

02:17:05.380 --> 02:17:11.020
[Guest]: newspapers around the country have gone, more will go. What will go with them is reportage.

02:17:11.020 --> 02:17:20.140
[Guest]: And I think what will remain is what we call debate. And I think that, to my mind, can't

02:17:20.140 --> 02:17:27.900
[Guest]: be fixed. Because even if you have a few good, meaningful outfits, like the ones you named

02:17:27.900 --> 02:17:32.060
[Guest]: Scroll, The Wire, The News Minute, they don't have the resources to be able to do this,

02:17:32.060 --> 02:17:37.020
[Guest]: send out 3,500 reporters across the country. And so we will only have debate.

02:17:37.020 --> 02:17:41.860
[Amit Varma]: I think the open question is there that do enough people value this kind of reportage?

02:17:41.860 --> 02:17:46.900
[Amit Varma]: And if they do, then, you know, is there a way for this kind of value to be expressed

02:17:46.900 --> 02:17:50.860
[Amit Varma]: in a way that causes something new structurally to come up so the reportage can happen?

02:17:50.860 --> 02:17:57.100
[Guest]: So I want a life that's not particularly complex. So as a reporter, it's not easy for me to

02:17:57.100 --> 02:18:02.060
[Guest]: conceive though this has been done and has been done successfully. In places like Chhattisgarh,

02:18:02.060 --> 02:18:05.900
[Guest]: where you got a reporter with a WhatsApp group, which gives him 50 bucks a month where he

02:18:05.900 --> 02:18:10.300
[Guest]: makes sufficient money out of it to be able to run that WhatsApp group and do his work.

02:18:10.300 --> 02:18:16.900
[Guest]: So it is possible. But for most of us, it's the idea of okay, give me a space to sit,

02:18:16.900 --> 02:18:21.020
[Guest]: give me a fan over my head, and then I can come to office and do my work and then go

02:18:21.020 --> 02:18:24.920
[Guest]: back home and I don't have to worry about the other stuff. That's that's most of us.

02:18:24.920 --> 02:18:28.900
[Guest]: So while it's possible that some things will come and replace as has I think The Wire and

02:18:28.900 --> 02:18:34.660
[Guest]: News Minute and all do a bit of that. But the volume is too big. One newspaper in one

02:18:34.660 --> 02:18:41.300
[Guest]: state 300 reporters think of that, that kind of resource is you can't just duplicate that.

02:18:41.300 --> 02:18:46.620
[Guest]: And that's just one newspaper, there were three of that size. Yeah, I fear for what

02:18:46.620 --> 02:18:47.620
[Amit Varma]: what is to come.

02:18:47.620 --> 02:18:53.140
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode ages ago with Ashok Malik, where he also pointed to another structural

02:18:53.140 --> 02:18:57.660
[Amit Varma]: problem. And that explains why so much of TV news channels are just so terrible. And

02:18:57.660 --> 02:19:01.660
[Amit Varma]: that was price controls that the government put price controls on how much you could ask

02:19:01.660 --> 02:19:08.220
[Amit Varma]: the user directly for. And what that led to was that TV stations and TV channels and all

02:19:08.220 --> 02:19:13.780
[Amit Varma]: of that would depend way more on advertising than on subscription. And that also means

02:19:13.780 --> 02:19:18.420
[Amit Varma]: that niches become difficult, like I forget the exact proportion 7030 or whatever, but

02:19:18.420 --> 02:19:22.380
[Amit Varma]: it was the converse of what it was in the US, for example. And if you're allowed to

02:19:22.380 --> 02:19:26.500
[Amit Varma]: charge subscribers what you want, and if subscribers value a certain thing, you can go into niches,

02:19:26.500 --> 02:19:30.340
[Amit Varma]: you can do your little things. But if it's only advertising, then you chase the lowest

02:19:30.340 --> 02:19:34.340
[Amit Varma]: common denominator, and the lowest common denominator is what it is. And you in fact

02:19:34.340 --> 02:19:39.660
[Amit Varma]: have a section in your book where, you know, you talk about why TV has become more strident

02:19:39.660 --> 02:19:46.180
[Amit Varma]: and you kind of give a number of reasons. And is that something that surprises you?

02:19:46.180 --> 02:19:51.540
[Amit Varma]: Because there was a time where you know, when television news first came up, it was respectable,

02:19:51.540 --> 02:19:56.300
[Amit Varma]: it was, you know, it was sort of a audio visual version of what you saw in the newspapers

02:19:56.300 --> 02:20:01.380
[Guest]: and all of that. I mean, but it wasn't competing against any other channel. Yeah. The problem

02:20:01.380 --> 02:20:07.540
[Guest]: is that with this boom that we saw, after India shining a lot of money on the equity

02:20:07.540 --> 02:20:12.820
[Guest]: side coming into media, channels have to compete, compete for what they have to compete for

02:20:12.820 --> 02:20:16.580
[Guest]: money, obviously, how does the money come in, the money comes in through a system where

02:20:16.580 --> 02:20:21.300
[Guest]: data is collected to show which shows and which channels have the most viewers, how

02:20:21.300 --> 02:20:26.020
[Guest]: do you get the most viewers, then that is the question. The good thing about television

02:20:26.020 --> 02:20:32.460
[Guest]: is that unlike newspapers, the feedback loop is pretty good. Like no newspaper editor outside

02:20:32.460 --> 02:20:36.780
[Guest]: of the tabloid world can tell what story works and what doesn't work because most newspapers

02:20:36.780 --> 02:20:41.660
[Guest]: are subscription tabloids for the most part in the West are sold on the street. Television

02:20:41.660 --> 02:20:46.300
[Guest]: gets a rating fairly regularly. So, they know what stories work, what stories didn't work.

02:20:46.300 --> 02:20:49.860
[Guest]: The problem with following the rating system is that you get skewed towards entertainment

02:20:49.860 --> 02:20:55.420
[Guest]: more than you do towards news. Newspapers can avoid that structurally because there

02:20:55.420 --> 02:21:02.540
[Guest]: is no real pressure on them, leaving the tabloids aside to put the sort of, you know, entertaining

02:21:02.540 --> 02:21:10.900
[Guest]: material up front. So, they tend to remain sort of boring, in a sense, a good sense,

02:21:10.900 --> 02:21:16.940
[Guest]: in structural terms. TV has exactly the opposite that the structure forces it to become entertaining.

02:21:16.940 --> 02:21:22.880
[Guest]: And once you go down that road, you're not going to come out of it. The fear of God is

02:21:22.880 --> 02:21:28.300
[Guest]: put into those top three, four sort of editors, managing editors, or whatever you call them.

02:21:28.300 --> 02:21:34.100
[Guest]: Most of them are also anchors, I think, who get the ratings each week and look at where

02:21:34.100 --> 02:21:39.900
[Guest]: they are placed. And so, the pressure is on them to make it even more demented than it

02:21:39.900 --> 02:21:43.100
[Guest]: is, which is why it's gone the way it has so quickly.

02:21:43.100 --> 02:21:49.740
[Amit Varma]: You know, I remember circa 2008, 2009, we called to these TV panels and all that and

02:21:49.740 --> 02:21:53.380
[Amit Varma]: I've come on Annab show a couple of times back in the day. Thankfully, nothing on YouTube

02:21:53.380 --> 02:21:58.820
[Amit Varma]: exists of that, but he was so normal then, you know, not the sort of raging lunatic he

02:21:58.820 --> 02:22:04.140
[Amit Varma]: later kind of began. My next question is that, you know, what are your insights on the kind

02:22:04.140 --> 02:22:10.300
[Amit Varma]: of things that people want to consume? Because it's not, you know, in terms of where TV news

02:22:10.300 --> 02:22:16.180
[Amit Varma]: has gone, it's not just a partisanship that is bothering. It's gone into unhinged territory

02:22:16.180 --> 02:22:20.340
[Amit Varma]: like after Sushant Singh Rajput died, right? The kind of conspiracy theories that came

02:22:20.340 --> 02:22:24.740
[Amit Varma]: up the kind of victimization of Rhea Chakraborty. And of course, social media was a little worse

02:22:24.740 --> 02:22:29.140
[Amit Varma]: because you had crazy conspiracy theories. And I could tell you about some of them, but

02:22:29.140 --> 02:22:35.060
[Amit Varma]: on even on television, you know, there seems to be this appetite for I mean, and that's

02:22:35.060 --> 02:22:38.740
[Amit Varma]: obviously why those channels go in these directions, there are feedback loops, and they realize

02:22:38.740 --> 02:22:42.540
[Amit Varma]: this is what people want, and they give them more of the same. And they go much further

02:22:42.540 --> 02:22:47.100
[Amit Varma]: in this direction than you know, they otherwise would, or maybe then even what the audience

02:22:47.100 --> 02:22:52.180
[Amit Varma]: decides at that time, and it just becomes a downward spiral. So what is it that people

02:22:52.180 --> 02:22:57.060
[Amit Varma]: really want? Like, do you think there is a reasonable constituency for what you would

02:22:57.060 --> 02:23:01.860
[Amit Varma]: call good journalism or good news or so on? Or do you think we just all the time want

02:23:01.860 --> 02:23:08.140
[Amit Varma]: to be entertained with outrageous narratives that get our dopamine going and all of that?

02:23:08.140 --> 02:23:14.300
[Guest]: So I think that there are a few things here. I think one is that all of us surely want

02:23:14.300 --> 02:23:19.460
[Guest]: at some point to receive material which informs us about the world that we are living in.

02:23:19.460 --> 02:23:24.540
[Guest]: We don't want to be fed material that is bad. So it stands to reason that I want to be told

02:23:24.540 --> 02:23:28.140
[Guest]: that this is going on. I might choose to dismiss it or I might choose to not act on it, but

02:23:28.140 --> 02:23:34.260
[Guest]: I want it right. Which is why one goes to news. So there is obviously a constituency.

02:23:34.260 --> 02:23:39.660
[Guest]: The question is then why is that constituency not being reflected in the material? I would

02:23:39.660 --> 02:23:48.900
[Guest]: say two things. One is what I referred to in terms of the structural problems that lead

02:23:48.900 --> 02:23:55.260
[Guest]: channels to chasing advertising money over subscription money, and that leads them automatically

02:23:55.260 --> 02:24:01.100
[Guest]: into a cycle of moving towards entertainment. The other is I think that the sort of bread

02:24:01.100 --> 02:24:05.500
[Guest]: and circuses thing which the ringmaster is controlling and wants material to be pushed

02:24:05.500 --> 02:24:11.020
[Guest]: in a particular direction is successful. So you've got the government saying that this

02:24:11.020 --> 02:24:15.780
[Guest]: is the kind of thing that there are WhatsApp groups in case listeners didn't know, where

02:24:15.780 --> 02:24:20.420
[Guest]: the editors and the reporters of various beats are linked to the government and the government

02:24:20.420 --> 02:24:28.020
[Guest]: tells them. The government tells anchors what to do. The day the CBI chief was raided and

02:24:28.020 --> 02:24:35.100
[Guest]: he was replaced was the same day that the amnesty office was raided in Bangalore. And

02:24:35.100 --> 02:24:39.580
[Guest]: I know this because the anchors called me and told me, they said that our lead story

02:24:39.580 --> 02:24:43.380
[Guest]: is going to be the amnesty thing and not the CBI problem. That's what they are told to

02:24:43.380 --> 02:24:53.260
[Guest]: do. I foresee some change in this. And I think that change will be externally influenced.

02:24:53.260 --> 02:25:01.380
[Guest]: And in small measure, because of what has been done to the economy, and in some measure,

02:25:01.380 --> 02:25:08.380
[Guest]: because of the problems of too many channels, many will go. The issue then will remain if

02:25:08.380 --> 02:25:13.380
[Guest]: you've got people like Ambani controlling the media, which he does, he's got fingers

02:25:13.380 --> 02:25:20.860
[Guest]: in many pies. Will that mean that the channel will continue doing what it's doing even without

02:25:20.860 --> 02:25:32.020
[Guest]: any kind of pressure on say revenue? I don't know. But I do believe that along with my

02:25:32.020 --> 02:25:38.140
[Guest]: sense that this kind of politics can only continue for so long, where external changes

02:25:38.140 --> 02:25:42.980
[Guest]: forced upon you. I think this kind of journalism can be done only for so long that you will

02:25:42.980 --> 02:25:49.500
[Guest]: either have a very strong counter, which is successful, both in the sense of reach and

02:25:49.500 --> 02:25:55.780
[Guest]: in terms of money, which we don't have at the moment, or you will be forced to shut

02:25:55.780 --> 02:26:00.780
[Guest]: and for lack of an audience that wants too much of this stuff. So I think that the future

02:26:00.780 --> 02:26:04.660
[Guest]: is pretty good. The near future might not be as good.

02:26:04.660 --> 02:26:08.860
[Amit Varma]: You know, just as in the context of what we were talking earlier about the politics and

02:26:08.860 --> 02:26:13.020
[Amit Varma]: society and I keep going back to this quote by Andrew Breitbart, where he said politics

02:26:13.020 --> 02:26:17.740
[Amit Varma]: is downstream of culture. And I think there is, you know, something to that. And in a

02:26:17.740 --> 02:26:24.340
[Amit Varma]: similar sense, I think here, what the kind of content that people want to view and consume

02:26:24.340 --> 02:26:30.220
[Amit Varma]: will drive what people provide. And I think what they want to consume and so on, is what

02:26:30.220 --> 02:26:34.780
[Amit Varma]: is disturbing. Like ages ago, I had an informal chat with Pratik Sinha, it wasn't on a podcast

02:26:34.780 --> 02:26:39.500
[Amit Varma]: or something, not in the episode we did together. It was in the sidelines of something. And

02:26:39.500 --> 02:26:44.180
[Amit Varma]: he pointed out about how he had come across this fake news about some minister or the

02:26:44.180 --> 02:26:49.940
[Amit Varma]: other. And he did his usual forensic genius on it, and figured out where it came from.

02:26:49.940 --> 02:26:54.820
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, wrote a post about how it originated with this person and this person

02:26:54.820 --> 02:26:59.540
[Amit Varma]: kind of propagated it. And a little while after he publishes that, he gets a WhatsApp

02:26:59.540 --> 02:27:04.500
[Amit Varma]: message from this guy saying, I am so and so person who started that thing, can I please

02:27:04.500 --> 02:27:09.940
[Amit Varma]: call you? So the guy calls him and it's some 16 year old kid or 15 year old kid somewhere

02:27:09.940 --> 02:27:14.980
[Amit Varma]: in a village. And he's not part of any IT cell, not part of any misinformation campaign.

02:27:14.980 --> 02:27:19.100
[Amit Varma]: But he's just put out, he started a website, he wants hits, what does he do for hits? He

02:27:19.100 --> 02:27:22.900
[Amit Varma]: tries various things, he throws things at the wall, as we should all do. And he finds

02:27:22.900 --> 02:27:27.780
[Amit Varma]: out that the kind of content which gets hits is this kind of rubbish. And then he goes

02:27:27.780 --> 02:27:32.420
[Amit Varma]: all out into this. And this is what kind of gathers the thing. So when you say that this

02:27:32.420 --> 02:27:36.860
[Amit Varma]: kind of journalism won't continue, I would say that if there is an appetite for it, and

02:27:36.860 --> 02:27:41.420
[Amit Varma]: the evidence seems to suggest that there is, then first that appetite has to diminish and

02:27:41.420 --> 02:27:45.020
[Amit Varma]: there has to be an appetite for some other kind of journalism before it ceases.

02:27:45.020 --> 02:27:51.100
[Guest]: So I think that a critical word here is journalism, that will this die off by itself? I don't

02:27:51.100 --> 02:27:59.180
[Guest]: think so. This will remain. What will be journalism when it, right now, this is what passes for

02:27:59.180 --> 02:28:07.140
[Guest]: news as well as what it is, which is mostly nonsense. Will there be, is it possible that

02:28:07.140 --> 02:28:10.580
[Guest]: there is a large enough constituency of people who to say that I don't want this, I want

02:28:10.580 --> 02:28:13.780
[Guest]: something else, and I'm willing to pay for it and make it viable? I'm saying that the

02:28:13.780 --> 02:28:19.260
[Guest]: answer to that is yes, it's too large a nation. And I don't think the time is too far off.

02:28:19.260 --> 02:28:28.180
[Guest]: The issue will be about the person who owns it. Can you have people who control the economy

02:28:28.180 --> 02:28:33.060
[Guest]: in large measure, control the advertising in large measure? Will they let something

02:28:33.060 --> 02:28:40.380
[Guest]: like this exist with their platforms, knowing that this is producing material that's going

02:28:40.380 --> 02:28:47.420
[Guest]: against their own interests? I don't know. But I don't think this is sustainable. And

02:28:47.420 --> 02:28:54.820
[Guest]: I think the reason it's not sustainable is that it is not stable. It is deteriorating.

02:28:54.820 --> 02:28:59.500
[Guest]: It's getting nastier. It's getting more vicious. There has to be an end. There is some end

02:28:59.500 --> 02:29:04.580
[Amit Varma]: point there, which I think will come soon. Yeah, and I actually share the optimism that

02:29:04.580 --> 02:29:08.420
[Amit Varma]: there are enough people who want a certain kind of good journalism that they'll pay for

02:29:08.420 --> 02:29:12.220
[Amit Varma]: it. And one doesn't know if it will reach the scale where you can have 3000 reporters

02:29:12.220 --> 02:29:17.700
[Amit Varma]: in a state. But at least I am optimistic about the likes of the people we named, for example,

02:29:17.700 --> 02:29:23.340
[Amit Varma]: kind of surviving and getting by. But then again, the sticks of the state as it were,

02:29:23.340 --> 02:29:27.460
[Amit Varma]: come into play where you know, you might be, you know, I think Dhanya Rajendran of the

02:29:27.460 --> 02:29:31.740
[Amit Varma]: News Minute tweeted a few days before we are recording this about how there were income

02:29:31.740 --> 02:29:37.020
[Amit Varma]: tax rates on whatever and the kind of trauma. I mean, the process is really the punishment

02:29:37.020 --> 02:29:40.500
[Amit Varma]: and you see the brave people who are kind of standing up and saying we'll continue to

02:29:40.500 --> 02:29:44.380
[Guest]: do this, but I'm sure it has a chilling effect. You have to internalize the fact that if you're

02:29:44.380 --> 02:29:51.620
[Guest]: going to dissent, you will be in trouble. What degree of trouble will depend on how

02:29:51.620 --> 02:29:56.460
[Guest]: much you dissent and how much stick the state can bring against you. But there is no way

02:29:56.460 --> 02:30:02.820
[Guest]: that this government will let you exist without trauma, because it is really malicious and

02:30:02.820 --> 02:30:08.700
[Guest]: really active and willing and sort of enthusiastic about using the powers that it has.

02:30:08.700 --> 02:30:12.500
[Amit Varma]: So let's talk about dissent then. You know, the last chapter of our Hindu Rashtra is called

02:30:12.500 --> 02:30:17.780
[Amit Varma]: how to fight it, right? And elsewhere, I have seen you tweet, quote, protest is a craft,

02:30:17.780 --> 02:30:21.580
[Amit Varma]: stop good. So tell me about that. Because you're like, if there's one thing that gave

02:30:21.580 --> 02:30:27.420
[Amit Varma]: me optimism and filled me with hope, it's all the anti-CAA protests, which were absolutely

02:30:27.420 --> 02:30:31.260
[Amit Varma]: remarkable and inspiring for so many different reasons, the women of Shaheen Bagh, the young

02:30:31.260 --> 02:30:36.580
[Amit Varma]: people holding up the preamble of the constitution, this otherwise boring, unreadable document,

02:30:36.580 --> 02:30:40.380
[Amit Varma]: and that kind of fills you with hope. So when you say protest is a craft, what do you mean

02:30:40.380 --> 02:30:41.740
[Guest]: by that?

02:30:41.740 --> 02:30:47.560
[Guest]: So activism has professionals in it, who have worked on something for a long time. And as

02:30:47.560 --> 02:30:51.380
[Guest]: you and I know, when you're in the newsroom for a long time, or when you're in a podcast

02:30:51.380 --> 02:30:57.420
[Guest]: studio for a long time, you know something more about it than I do. I might be naturally

02:30:57.420 --> 02:31:03.300
[Guest]: sort of gifted, I might be intelligent in many ways, but I don't know the things that

02:31:03.300 --> 02:31:09.340
[Guest]: you do, because I haven't done them. Protest is about showing up, obviously, and saying

02:31:09.340 --> 02:31:14.580
[Guest]: what it is that you want to say, how do you do that? Is the craft. To give you an example

02:31:14.580 --> 02:31:22.900
[Guest]: of how craft can manifest itself is that Greenpeace uses jumpers of very high places to unfurl

02:31:22.900 --> 02:31:28.460
[Guest]: banners, which are very spectacular, that is craft. So there is a technique about how

02:31:28.460 --> 02:31:36.140
[Guest]: to go about doing it, and what you do to make sure that it is enjoyable, participative,

02:31:36.140 --> 02:31:44.340
[Guest]: joyous, which makes it in the long term, effective. So that's one. The second is protest is part

02:31:44.340 --> 02:31:50.660
[Guest]: of civil society, just like a corporate office will function on outcomes. The outcome in

02:31:50.660 --> 02:31:57.820
[Guest]: a corporate in the office might be the quarterly profit or whatever the volume manufactured.

02:31:57.820 --> 02:32:03.620
[Guest]: Rights groups will have outcomes based on changes in laws and policies by the state.

02:32:03.620 --> 02:32:08.620
[Guest]: So they will have something called a power mapping, where they will map who they need

02:32:08.620 --> 02:32:15.620
[Guest]: to shift to be able to get the issue to move towards them. And they will do it in various

02:32:15.620 --> 02:32:19.860
[Guest]: ways. So there is a lot of craft involved, you need to be able to know things that the

02:32:19.860 --> 02:32:23.900
[Guest]: others don't, and you need to be able to apply that knowledge to bring about that change.

02:32:23.900 --> 02:32:29.380
[Guest]: It's not just a large number of people saying this, that or the other. So if we look at

02:32:29.380 --> 02:32:36.620
[Guest]: the success of Shaheen Bagh, there are two, three things in that they were able to do,

02:32:36.620 --> 02:32:42.780
[Guest]: which came to them naturally. We have ghettoized our Muslims fully in this country. Because

02:32:42.780 --> 02:32:47.820
[Guest]: of that, the women were able to have safe spaces where they could spend all day and

02:32:47.820 --> 02:32:54.180
[Guest]: all night. Because of the same fact, they were able to replicate it. That it's just

02:32:54.180 --> 02:33:02.980
[Guest]: a sit-in. It's in our mahala. This is what you do. You sleep the night here. In the evenings,

02:33:02.980 --> 02:33:06.780
[Guest]: we'll have people come and talk to us, there'll be people singing, we will dancing and so

02:33:06.780 --> 02:33:11.060
[Guest]: on. In the afternoon, there'll be very few people, but it'll still be occupied. There

02:33:11.060 --> 02:33:15.740
[Guest]: is that it becomes a template that you can replicate. But you can only do that if you

02:33:15.740 --> 02:33:20.620
[Guest]: have that template, it needs to be a good enough template. So for most of us protest

02:33:20.620 --> 02:33:28.500
[Guest]: is seen as something which is easy, and it's done spontaneously and doesn't have too many

02:33:28.500 --> 02:33:34.340
[Guest]: other sort of elements. That's not the case. It's part of a very, very structured, very

02:33:34.340 --> 02:33:38.500
[Guest]: large set of things that activists do to be able to bring about change. That is what I

02:33:38.500 --> 02:33:43.700
[Guest]: meant in saying that a protest is a craft. That's that's a tweet that got me into trouble.

02:33:43.700 --> 02:33:50.060
[Amit Varma]: I don't know why. Twitter banned you. Sorry? Twitter banned you I think. They took me off.

02:33:50.060 --> 02:33:56.540
[Guest]: There was a case filed against me. And the reason is, I said you know, protest is a craft

02:33:56.540 --> 02:33:59.900
[Guest]: at the end of a tweet, which was retweeting something I think from the Baltimore Sun,

02:33:59.900 --> 02:34:06.780
[Guest]: I think it was. But there was a bunch of people all masked all on the ground, saying, in unison,

02:34:06.780 --> 02:34:11.300
[Guest]: I can't breathe, which is a great way of doing this is the kind of thing that TV that the

02:34:11.300 --> 02:34:15.740
[Guest]: TV cameras will come to, which is what makes it a craft and you think about it in a sort

02:34:15.740 --> 02:34:21.060
[Guest]: of way, which is sort of interesting, and the cameras will come. And I said that this

02:34:21.060 --> 02:34:25.460
[Guest]: is what Adivasis and Muslims and Dalits and women should be doing in this country. So

02:34:25.460 --> 02:34:31.820
[Guest]: this, the police commissioner told the BBC that I was trying to sort of, not his words,

02:34:31.820 --> 02:34:35.980
[Guest]: but create mischief in a time of COVID, you know, protocols or some nonsense. I don't

02:34:35.980 --> 02:34:41.260
[Amit Varma]: know. So yeah, I don't know you laugh about it, man, because it's just so stressful just

02:34:41.260 --> 02:34:44.980
[Amit Varma]: to think about the kind of harassment that this can kind of result in and the process

02:34:44.980 --> 02:34:49.580
[Amit Varma]: absolutely being the punishment. Can you give me more examples of protest being a craft,

02:34:49.580 --> 02:34:52.900
[Amit Varma]: both in the context of organized protest, like when you're doing marches and all of

02:34:52.900 --> 02:34:58.580
[Amit Varma]: this, and also in the context of unorganized protests, like, you know, many people listening

02:34:58.580 --> 02:35:02.340
[Amit Varma]: to this might think that I can't go out on a march, maybe they're not even in India,

02:35:02.340 --> 02:35:06.780
[Amit Varma]: I want to protest in other ways. How can I protest? So any concrete examples?

02:35:06.780 --> 02:35:11.340
[Guest]: I've got a book coming out in a couple of months, hopefully in a couple of months, same

02:35:11.340 --> 02:35:17.780
[Guest]: publisher. No, it's not. This is Harper Collins, India. It's called the anarchist cookbook.

02:35:17.780 --> 02:35:24.140
[Guest]: It's a book on protest on why and how to protest. I'll give an example. So the gay community

02:35:24.140 --> 02:35:32.660
[Guest]: in the United States was empowered and had an outcome in mind. De legitimize decriminalize

02:35:32.660 --> 02:35:39.900
[Guest]: homosexuality and legalize gay marriage, right? What was the opposition? It was the conservatives

02:35:39.900 --> 02:35:45.180
[Guest]: who said no gays in the army, no gay marriage, you know, homosexuality is an offense against

02:35:45.180 --> 02:35:51.340
[Guest]: God, etc. So the campaigners said, we need to move the needle from no to yes, right?

02:35:51.340 --> 02:35:57.740
[Guest]: And there are players here, the church is a player, the government, the president is

02:35:57.740 --> 02:36:02.140
[Guest]: a player, the 500 or whatever it is, you know, congressmen and women, they have they are

02:36:02.140 --> 02:36:06.780
[Guest]: all players. These are the states in which we need to get this fixed. These are the states

02:36:06.780 --> 02:36:11.060
[Guest]: in which victories are easy. This is what we need to do in terms of the Supreme Court

02:36:11.060 --> 02:36:16.580
[Guest]: to look at fundamentally. The campaign would look at how do we shift some of these people.

02:36:16.580 --> 02:36:23.500
[Guest]: So this was, you know, thought about it and said that the opposite to gay marriage, the

02:36:23.500 --> 02:36:30.580
[Guest]: narrative was family values. So the campaign that they built was sort of around how gay

02:36:30.580 --> 02:36:35.620
[Guest]: marriages had the same family values that the non gay marriages that the sort of hetero

02:36:35.620 --> 02:36:41.660
[Guest]: marriages had. And it worked, they were able to over and very quickly knock off the laws

02:36:41.660 --> 02:36:47.820
[Guest]: and get themselves legitimized. Similarly, with Black Lives Matter. I think that in the

02:36:47.820 --> 02:36:57.380
[Guest]: space of a very few weeks, an organized campaign which said that this was unacceptable, became

02:36:57.380 --> 02:37:01.420
[Guest]: popularly accepted and the New York Times said that the majority of people shifted actually

02:37:01.420 --> 02:37:08.740
[Guest]: after that campaign, where you had the very simple messaging that we are dying on the

02:37:08.740 --> 02:37:13.140
[Guest]: street because of who we are. You stop that because our lives matter. That's it. There's

02:37:13.140 --> 02:37:18.220
[Guest]: no other message. But very large numbers of people saying the same thing. So this is a

02:37:18.220 --> 02:37:23.980
[Guest]: simpler, less technical sort of protest, but also works. Outcomes are actually achieved

02:37:23.980 --> 02:37:30.860
[Guest]: because the policing system changes. That is the outcome that they seek. On a smaller,

02:37:30.860 --> 02:37:35.540
[Guest]: that smaller level with like a protest on a rally and stuff, we need to be more creative.

02:37:35.540 --> 02:37:41.580
[Guest]: So a lot of the really grassroots activists in India use a lot of music. So when you have

02:37:41.580 --> 02:37:47.100
[Guest]: when you when the middle class, the sort of so called so middle class is shown in a protest

02:37:47.100 --> 02:37:53.940
[Guest]: is normally the candlelight march or like, you know, a few for the for the majority.

02:37:53.940 --> 02:38:00.380
[Guest]: The sad thing is that it's seen like something that's difficult to do. And so creativity

02:38:00.380 --> 02:38:04.260
[Guest]: is outsourced. Not too many nations in the world have protests where the same banner

02:38:04.260 --> 02:38:08.900
[Guest]: is held with the same placard is held by 50 people. You know, it's like going to a match

02:38:08.900 --> 02:38:11.900
[Guest]: where people are saying Pepsi and for you know, it's like the same thing because somebody

02:38:11.900 --> 02:38:15.900
[Guest]: else has made it and has just distributed it. It's much more effective if you have your

02:38:15.900 --> 02:38:19.740
[Guest]: own. The US is very good with this, the UK also, where you've got everybody holding something

02:38:19.740 --> 02:38:23.900
[Guest]: different. And everybody's thought put some thought in it. That's all you need. You don't

02:38:23.900 --> 02:38:28.820
[Guest]: need anything else, but you stand out because of it. You can only think of this once you

02:38:28.820 --> 02:38:33.420
[Guest]: start doing it. If you're not, if you've only been to a couple in your life, you're not

02:38:33.420 --> 02:38:38.220
[Guest]: going to have the the idea thing. Okay, maybe I need to do something else to attract people

02:38:38.220 --> 02:38:42.700
[Guest]: to what I'm saying. Yeah, that's that's why it's a craft. And it's not as simple as it

02:38:42.700 --> 02:38:47.300
[Guest]: might look from the outside. And that's why also it's fascinating. I think that one of

02:38:47.300 --> 02:38:55.100
[Guest]: the things the moment the young women showed up wearing the hijab, I knew that the government

02:38:55.100 --> 02:38:58.900
[Guest]: would lose. We are talking at a time when it has not lost yet. And we are talking at

02:38:58.900 --> 02:39:02.340
[Guest]: a time when it appears that the high court is going to rule against the women. It doesn't

02:39:02.340 --> 02:39:07.260
[Guest]: matter. Because they have agency. That is the problem. Once you give an once you give

02:39:07.260 --> 02:39:13.180
[Guest]: a community agency to push back against what you're doing to them, they will use it. You

02:39:13.180 --> 02:39:17.740
[Guest]: might bash them down into not using it. But we don't we are not that much of a state that

02:39:17.740 --> 02:39:22.300
[Guest]: you can't just if the women keep showing up at the gate, that's all they need to do nothing

02:39:22.300 --> 02:39:30.660
[Guest]: else. They just need to show up the state will build this that this power. You can only

02:39:30.660 --> 02:39:37.540
[Guest]: understand once you look at activism from the inside of organizations that approach

02:39:37.540 --> 02:39:44.420
[Guest]: it with a technical sense. Yeah, and I think my years in amnesty is really fabulous in

02:39:44.420 --> 02:39:50.300
[Guest]: terms of learning. I had no idea what the heck this they did or how they did it. But

02:39:50.300 --> 02:39:56.180
[Guest]: learning that stuff as you might in a studio, or you might in a newsroom came to me while

02:39:56.180 --> 02:40:00.940
[Amit Varma]: I spent my five years there. Speaking of gay marriage, I remember this classic article

02:40:00.940 --> 02:40:06.100
[Amit Varma]: written by Andrew Sullivan in the early 90s. I think 92. He was an editor of Atlantic then

02:40:06.100 --> 02:40:10.340
[Amit Varma]: called the conservative case for gay marriage, where he did exactly that where he reframed

02:40:10.340 --> 02:40:14.460
[Amit Varma]: it in terms of family values and said every conservative should support gay marriage and

02:40:14.460 --> 02:40:21.780
[Amit Varma]: Sullivan himself was gay. And I think that's a remarkable exercise in reframing that you

02:40:21.780 --> 02:40:25.500
[Amit Varma]: want people to believe, you know, to support you in a certain way. And you frame it in

02:40:25.500 --> 02:40:31.100
[Amit Varma]: a way that brings that support around. And I can't wait for that. And now the other part

02:40:31.100 --> 02:40:36.100
[Amit Varma]: of my question, that this is all organized protest, formal protest in terms of craft,

02:40:36.100 --> 02:40:40.100
[Amit Varma]: and I can't wait to read your book and figure out more about it. But informally, like anybody

02:40:40.100 --> 02:40:46.020
[Guest]: listening to this says that, you know, what can I do is you are already doing stuff. So

02:40:46.020 --> 02:40:52.940
[Guest]: what is it that we mean? By activism, we mean that you are engaging with state and society

02:40:52.940 --> 02:40:56.660
[Guest]: to bring about some kind of outcome change, right? You're doing that through your vote

02:40:56.660 --> 02:41:02.340
[Guest]: in any case, you're doing that through social media. You're doing that by sort of expressing

02:41:02.340 --> 02:41:07.380
[Guest]: yourself on Facebook. The question is, how do you make it more effective? And that has

02:41:07.380 --> 02:41:11.900
[Guest]: dual benefits, you become more prominent, because of the fact that you're doing something

02:41:11.900 --> 02:41:16.340
[Guest]: which is amplified by sort of other people. And you're able to make sure that what you

02:41:16.340 --> 02:41:23.260
[Guest]: want is actually the outcome is actually you know, made real. So that that is your figuring

02:41:23.260 --> 02:41:27.460
[Guest]: out how to use and there are lots of people on social media right now who have figured

02:41:27.460 --> 02:41:33.260
[Guest]: it out and are trying to do it. So you don't need to do anything other than continue using

02:41:33.260 --> 02:41:38.020
[Guest]: social media, just make yourself slightly more effective, no matter whether your use

02:41:38.020 --> 02:41:42.860
[Guest]: on social media is in favor of the BJP or the Hindutva or whatever, the same rules apply

02:41:42.860 --> 02:41:50.060
[Guest]: to all of us. You need to be able to communicate what it is that you want to an end and that

02:41:50.060 --> 02:41:53.980
[Guest]: end has to be the outcome change that you seek. Once you're clear about that, then you

02:41:53.980 --> 02:42:00.080
[Guest]: can figure out what it is that works. And the best activism, I would say the most effective

02:42:00.080 --> 02:42:07.260
[Guest]: activism tool that we have in the modern world is social media. For a long time, those of

02:42:07.260 --> 02:42:11.420
[Guest]: us who are in activism believe that you need the people physically on the ground. And I

02:42:11.420 --> 02:42:17.420
[Guest]: think Shainbhag and Afama show that that is true. But not all protests require mass mobilization

02:42:17.420 --> 02:42:23.060
[Guest]: of that sort, because the because the demand on the sort of individuals is too high. You

02:42:23.060 --> 02:42:29.900
[Guest]: can bring about change purely by using your own social media handle and your page slightly

02:42:29.900 --> 02:42:34.580
[Guest]: more effectively than you than you are. And I'll give tips on how to.

02:42:34.580 --> 02:42:39.820
[Amit Varma]: No, I did an episode a long time back, a couple of years back with Pranik Kotasane, where

02:42:39.820 --> 02:42:44.500
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about what he called radically networked societies, where, you know, taking lessons

02:42:44.500 --> 02:42:49.780
[Amit Varma]: from the Arab Spring and so on, and a combination of sort of in person protest and, you know,

02:42:49.780 --> 02:42:53.980
[Amit Varma]: using them to using the internet to mobilize that. So I linked that from the show notes.

02:42:53.980 --> 02:42:56.580
[Amit Varma]: But when you said you'd give tips or your tips are in the books,

02:42:56.580 --> 02:43:01.460
[Amit Varma]: So it's not very communicable. Fair enough. So we've just got to wait for

02:43:01.460 --> 02:43:05.140
[Amit Varma]: your book and let's be patient. It's not that far off. You mentioned amnesty. Tell me about

02:43:05.140 --> 02:43:10.540
[Amit Varma]: your years in amnesty. Because before that, you were sort of a journalist, love for writing

02:43:10.540 --> 02:43:16.860
[Amit Varma]: language, all of that, you do your journalism, you do it for, you know, a long time. And

02:43:16.860 --> 02:43:20.460
[Amit Varma]: then you move to amnesty where you're now an activist and all of that. So what prompted

02:43:20.460 --> 02:43:25.500
[Amit Varma]: that shift? And what are the kind of lessons you learned? In what ways did it change you?

02:43:25.500 --> 02:43:31.500
[Guest]: So I was I moved to Bangalore in 2010, with the intention of retiring and sort of reading

02:43:31.500 --> 02:43:37.100
[Guest]: and writing full time and so on, which I did for five years. And then I suspect amnesty

02:43:37.100 --> 02:43:41.500
[Guest]: was not able to find anybody to run it because a salaries are pretty low in civil society

02:43:41.500 --> 02:43:45.540
[Guest]: be because it's difficult work. Not difficult to work in the sense of the work itself, but

02:43:45.540 --> 02:43:51.100
[Guest]: because of the government. I suspect this and I could be wrong. But when I was asked

02:43:51.100 --> 02:43:55.820
[Guest]: whether I was sort of interested in the job, I felt immediately attracted to it. And I

02:43:55.820 --> 02:44:03.900
[Guest]: think one reason was that after my years in Gujarat, and I was very dissatisfied towards

02:44:03.900 --> 02:44:08.140
[Guest]: the end of my job as a tabloid editor, because I felt that there was something happening

02:44:08.140 --> 02:44:13.900
[Guest]: in society that was not being captured out of Bombay and Delhi. What it was, I didn't

02:44:13.900 --> 02:44:20.100
[Guest]: know. But I knew that there was something happening in terms of the sort of the communal

02:44:20.100 --> 02:44:24.300
[Guest]: stuff. I had known Modi for some time, you know, before that, I knew that he would do

02:44:24.300 --> 02:44:30.940
[Guest]: well in Delhi. And so I worked for a Gujarati paper, where of course, I was miserable, because

02:44:30.940 --> 02:44:37.020
[Guest]: it there was no, no way that I could express the things that I wanted to say in the paper,

02:44:37.020 --> 02:44:43.700
[Guest]: because the leadership is extremely conservative. And so that thing remained with me to some

02:44:43.700 --> 02:44:47.500
[Guest]: extent that I feel that need to do something I didn't know what. And so when this thing

02:44:47.500 --> 02:44:52.580
[Guest]: came along, I was I was happy to join, but I didn't know what the job was. And I didn't

02:44:52.580 --> 02:44:56.020
[Guest]: realize it for some time, I was the least qualified person in that office, and I'm not

02:44:56.020 --> 02:45:03.060
[Guest]: being modest. So there's very highly, there are three kinds of people who are in activism.

02:45:03.060 --> 02:45:10.860
[Guest]: One is the journalist types who do the the evidence gathering. Often, these are not journalists,

02:45:10.860 --> 02:45:15.060
[Guest]: but these are PhD scholars. So if you look at something deep, deeper, like, you know,

02:45:15.060 --> 02:45:19.580
[Guest]: a climate change or coal mining in the Adivasi belt, there's somebody who studied this for

02:45:19.580 --> 02:45:25.220
[Guest]: a long time and knows a lot of things about it. And the third types are lawyers. So they

02:45:25.220 --> 02:45:31.220
[Guest]: all the material is looked at from the legal lens and cleaned up, they do the the editing

02:45:31.220 --> 02:45:35.940
[Guest]: function of that, but they do it at a level of law rather than at the level of making

02:45:35.940 --> 02:45:42.340
[Guest]: making it more readable. And I like obviously didn't fit into any of this. And nor was I

02:45:42.340 --> 02:45:49.340
[Guest]: meant to I went there as a manager, like, I was I was the the guy who ran the place.

02:45:49.340 --> 02:45:53.780
[Guest]: So I threw myself into fundraising, which is what I did, I raised that I raised money

02:45:53.780 --> 02:46:01.180
[Guest]: to for the for the organization, and I would engage with the output, not from the active

02:46:01.180 --> 02:46:05.060
[Guest]: point of view, but just observing what it is that did because there was so much better

02:46:05.060 --> 02:46:12.260
[Guest]: than me at like what they did. That is where I learned that this is what it is that for

02:46:12.260 --> 02:46:17.540
[Guest]: amnesty, especially the evidence gathering is the primary function. It is the quality

02:46:17.540 --> 02:46:22.980
[Guest]: of the material three years into one research report, which is 50 pages long, like a really

02:46:22.980 --> 02:46:28.100
[Guest]: intense verified doubly verified, if you're using somebody, that person has to sign a

02:46:28.100 --> 02:46:32.820
[Guest]: document saying that it's okay for us to campaign on their behalf, and so on and so on the very

02:46:32.820 --> 02:46:43.700
[Guest]: extremely complex newsrooms will lose their if they saw it, you know. And the once the

02:46:43.700 --> 02:46:48.060
[Guest]: material is in it goes to campaigners, the campaigners are the ones who do that stuff.

02:46:48.060 --> 02:46:52.020
[Guest]: Now those people, they might not even have gone to college. They're sitting in a room

02:46:52.020 --> 02:46:57.140
[Guest]: with people who might have had a PhD, but they are they are both equally good at what

02:46:57.140 --> 02:47:03.260
[Guest]: they do. The campaigner is operating out of experience, instinct and knowledge about what

02:47:03.260 --> 02:47:08.820
[Guest]: it is that can be done. And it's not just about having an event. It's about figuring

02:47:08.820 --> 02:47:15.060
[Guest]: out who the people are who will, who can shift this for us, and how it is that they can be

02:47:15.060 --> 02:47:22.620
[Guest]: influenced, very rich to sort of learn and study and so on. And I've learned that this

02:47:22.620 --> 02:47:29.660
[Guest]: is a, these are the sets of laws we have, I had no, I had no clue that things like the

02:47:29.660 --> 02:47:38.220
[Guest]: coal bearing areas act sort of existed where the government can, without any resistance,

02:47:38.220 --> 02:47:44.780
[Guest]: be able to take over the lands of sort of Adivasis from them, which it still does. Or

02:47:44.780 --> 02:47:51.420
[Guest]: what exactly AFSPA was, and how it was enforced. All these things you learn only when you work

02:47:51.420 --> 02:47:59.260
[Guest]: with them. And I think for me, the very rich learning experience of those five years has

02:47:59.260 --> 02:48:04.740
[Guest]: has, you know, stayed with me, I don't really, I don't really desire working in a newspaper

02:48:04.740 --> 02:48:09.420
[Guest]: anymore. I don't really care if my columns don't go away. In fact, I'm quite bored of

02:48:09.420 --> 02:48:14.380
[Guest]: writing them, I write them because that's the only source of money I have at the moment.

02:48:14.380 --> 02:48:21.940
[Guest]: But this stuff is like a magnet, it's like it draws me very powerfully. Yeah, and, and

02:48:21.940 --> 02:48:24.940
[Guest]: I think it'll stay with me for, for the rest of my life.

02:48:24.940 --> 02:48:27.300
[Guest]: Did it make you a different person?

02:48:27.300 --> 02:48:32.420
[Guest]: It made me more aware of how dumb I was. And I think there are many jobs can do that. But

02:48:32.420 --> 02:48:39.500
[Guest]: I'm saying that it made me more aware of how dumb I was, along with how to try and empathize

02:48:39.500 --> 02:48:44.820
[Guest]: with somebody, which is, I think, very difficult for a job to do. Right? I think so, at least,

02:48:44.820 --> 02:48:49.460
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know, I've done many jobs, and this has not done that to me. So the ability

02:48:49.460 --> 02:48:56.060
[Guest]: to and being a newspaper editor, you're basically a tyrant, especially if you work in newspaper

02:48:56.060 --> 02:49:00.500
[Guest]: organizations where the proprietor likes you and gives you the authority, which I had,

02:49:00.500 --> 02:49:06.540
[Guest]: the Ansari's at midday, they never said anything to me. And I ran the newsroom like an absolute

02:49:06.540 --> 02:49:11.700
[Guest]: tyrant in the wrong sense of the word that I dismissive of people, but here I was in

02:49:11.700 --> 02:49:17.700
[Guest]: an office where when I when I spoke over somebody, they would not stop speaking, they would continue

02:49:17.700 --> 02:49:23.660
[Guest]: speaking, which I was not used to. And they were half my age, perhaps, you know, so the

02:49:23.660 --> 02:49:28.340
[Guest]: idea that you're dumb, and you shouldn't be doing dumb things can only come through a

02:49:28.340 --> 02:49:32.420
[Guest]: lesson which is taught to you in that fashion, which I learned.

02:49:32.420 --> 02:49:36.820
[Amit Varma]: I'm just thinking maybe we need to make Modiji work in Amnesty for a few years.

02:49:36.820 --> 02:49:43.860
[Guest]: No, it's a great place. I love it. It's such a fabulous place and such such a great history.

02:49:43.860 --> 02:49:52.740
[Guest]: So tough, like we had this, we had a report on where Amnesty refers to the Israeli treatment

02:49:52.740 --> 02:49:59.100
[Guest]: of Palestinians inside of Israel as apartheid. And it's not easy to bring out such things

02:49:59.100 --> 02:50:05.460
[Guest]: because we have a unit within that country and so on. But as a movement, it's phenomenal.

02:50:05.460 --> 02:50:11.380
[Guest]: Amnesty is governance structure is democratic, so you vote for people. But because it's democratic,

02:50:11.380 --> 02:50:18.180
[Guest]: it's the country called section in the Amnesty language that has the most members would have

02:50:18.180 --> 02:50:22.820
[Guest]: more votes. So it was six votes, but because it was Europe based, the European sections

02:50:22.820 --> 02:50:29.260
[Guest]: had most members 5 lakh 4 lakh 10 lakh paying us a sort of sum of money every month. So

02:50:29.260 --> 02:50:34.860
[Guest]: they had more votes, six votes. And they were able to get their own stuff, you know, enforced

02:50:34.860 --> 02:50:40.340
[Guest]: over they voluntarily gave up everybody went to one one nation, one vote voluntarily gave

02:50:40.340 --> 02:50:46.940
[Guest]: up power. You don't see that in in too many places. You don't see that anywhere actually.

02:50:46.940 --> 02:50:53.380
[Guest]: Yeah, so it's, it's a great place, which I think should be taught about. I'm glad it

02:50:53.380 --> 02:50:58.700
[Guest]: won its Nobel Peace Prize so long ago, 77, because the world instantly recognized that

02:50:58.700 --> 02:51:03.540
[Guest]: this is you know, quality stuff, death penalty in Europe gone because of our torture, you

02:51:03.540 --> 02:51:10.380
[Guest]: know, yeah, great stuff. What happened in India? In India, it started in 50 years ago,

02:51:10.380 --> 02:51:17.260
[Guest]: when George Fernandes was was a member, it was very urban and remained so activists tend

02:51:17.260 --> 02:51:21.580
[Guest]: to not be very good manager, I suspect one reason why I was asked to run it was that

02:51:21.580 --> 02:51:27.180
[Guest]: there was okay, can you do the kind of the management bit side to it. So when you don't

02:51:27.180 --> 02:51:32.660
[Guest]: have money, it just shuts. So there were four or five times before this time, that it came

02:51:32.660 --> 02:51:38.300
[Guest]: and went each time the government would not like it. And each time it had to shut, not

02:51:38.300 --> 02:51:43.660
[Guest]: go shut, because all the five times was run entirely, as was the case in my time as well

02:51:43.660 --> 02:51:49.380
[Guest]: run by this is it was sort of Indians running. Amnesty is only a brand that is lent to a

